{"title_page": "Luis Bu\u00f1uel", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish film director}}\n{{spanish name|Bu\u00f1uel|Portol\u00e9s}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Luis Bu\u00f1uel\n|image        = Luis Bu\u00f1uel.JPG\n|caption      = Bu\u00f1uel, 1968\n|birth_name   = Luis Bu\u00f1uel Portol\u00e9s\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1900|2|22|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Calanda, Spain|Calanda]], [[Aragon]], Spain\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1983|7|29|1900|2|22|df=y}}\n|death_place  = [[Mexico City]], Mexico\n|citizenship  = {{ubl|Spain (renounced in 1949)|Mexico (since 1949)<ref name=\"Harvard.edu\">{{cite web |title=Bu\u00f1uel's Mexico |url=http://hcl.harvard.edu/hfa/films/2012julsep/bunuel.html |website=Harvard Film Archive |publisher=Fine Arts Library of the Harvard College Library |access-date=10 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304114616/http://hcl.harvard.edu/hfa/films/2012julsep/bunuel.html |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n|alma_mater   = [[Complutense University of Madrid|University of Madrid]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|[[Jeanne Rucar]]|1934}}\n|years_active = 1929\u20131977\n|occupation   = Filmmaker\n}}\n\n'''Luis Bu\u00f1uel Portol\u00e9s''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8lwis \u03b2u\u02c8\u0272wel po\u027eto\u02c8les}}; 22 February 1900 \u2013 29 July 1983) was a Spanish [[filmmaker]], naturalised Mexican in 1949,<ref name =\"Harvard.edu\" /> who worked in France, Mexico and Spain.<ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\">{{cite web|last=Kyrou|first=Ado|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Luis-Bunuel|website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen Bu\u00f1uel died at age 83, his [[obituary]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' called him \"an [[iconoclast]], moralist, and revolutionary who was a leader of [[avant-garde]] [[surrealism]] in his youth and a dominant international movie director half a century later\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last=Flint|first=Peter B.|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel Dies at 83; Filmmaker for 50 Years|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/07/30/obituaries/luis-bunuel-dies-at-83-film-maker-for-50-years.html|access-date=6 August 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=30 July 1983}}</ref>  His first picture, ''[[Un Chien Andalou]]''\u2014made in the [[silent film|silent era]]\u2014was called \"the most famous short film ever made\" by critic [[Roger Ebert]],<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=Un Chien Andalou Movie Review (1928)|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-un-chien-andalou-1928|work=Great Movies: The First 100|publisher=RogerEbert.com|access-date=9 October 2017|date=16 April 2000}}</ref> and his last film, ''[[That Obscure Object of Desire]]''\u2014made 48 years later\u2014won him Best Director awards from the [[National Board of Review]] and the [[National Society of Film Critics]].<ref name=\"Ramirez Berg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.austinfilm.org/essential-cinema/program-notes-that-obscure-object-of-desire |title=Program Notes: THAT OBSCURE OBJECT OF DESIRE |last=Berg |first=Charles Ram\u00edrez |publisher=Austin Film Society |access-date=9 October 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610201718/http://www.austinfilm.org/essential-cinema/program-notes-that-obscure-object-of-desire |archivedate=10 June 2015 }}</ref>  Writer [[Octavio Paz]] called Bu\u00f1uel's work \"the marriage of the film image to the poetic image, creating a new reality...scandalous and subversive\".<ref name=paz>{{cite book|last=Paz|first=Octavio|title=On Poets and Others|year=1986|publisher=Arcade Publishing|location=New York|isbn=978-1-55970-139-6|pages=152|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qoiEQ4FiuFsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>\n\nOften associated with the [[surrealist movement]] of the 1920s, Bu\u00f1uel created films from the 1920s through the 1970s. His work spans two continents, three languages, and an array of genres, including [[experimental film]], [[Documentary film|documentary]], [[Melodrama#Film|melodrama]], [[satire]], [[Musical film|musical]], [[Sex in film|erotica]], [[Comedy film|comedy]], [[Romance film|romance]], [[costume drama]]s, [[Fantasy film|fantasy]], [[crime film]], [[Adventure film|adventure]], and [[Western (genre)#Film|western]]. Despite this variety, filmmaker [[John Huston]] believed that, regardless of genre, a Bu\u00f1uel film is so distinctive as to be instantly recognizable,<ref>{{cite book|last=Sinyard|first=Neil|title=\"The Discreet Charm of Houston and Bu\u00f1uel: Notes on a Cinematic Odd Couple\", in John Huston: Essays on a Restless Director, ed. Tony Tracy and Roddy Flynn|year=2010|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson NC|isbn=978-0-7864-5853-0|pages=73|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xhfl7DdYTMQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> or, as [[Ingmar Bergman]] put it, \"Bu\u00f1uel nearly always made Bu\u00f1uel films\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bergmanorama.webs.com/bergman_on_directors.htm |title=Commentary: Bergman on Filmmakers |publisher=Berganorama |accessdate=9 October 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090624023319/http://bergmanorama.webs.com/bergman_on_directors.htm |archivedate=24 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSeven of Bu\u00f1uel's films are included in ''[[Sight & Sound]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 2012 critics' poll of the top 250 films of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thependragonsociety.com/sight-sound-2012-critics-top-250-films/|title=Sight & Sound 2012 critics top 250 films|last=Pendragon|first=The|date=2018-04-26|website=The Pendragon Society|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Critics' Top 250 Films |url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/sightandsoundpolls/2012/critics |website=Sight and Sound |publisher=British Film Institute |access-date=18 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026034922/http://explore.bfi.org.uk/sightandsoundpolls/2012/critics |archivedate=26 October 2013 }}</ref> Fifteen of his films are included in the ''They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?'' list of the 1,000 greatest films of all time, for which he ranks second only to [[Jean-Luc Godard]], with sixteen,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_all1000films_table.php|title=The 1,000 Greatest Films|publisher=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?}}</ref> and he ranks number 13 on their list of the top 250 directors.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Top 250 Directors|url=http://www.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_top250directors.htm|publisher=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?|access-date=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\n[[File:Vista parcial de Calanda. Foto Jos\u00e9 Antonio Bielsa.JPG|thumb|right|Calanda, Spain|[[Calanda, Spain|Calanda]], Spain]]\nBu\u00f1uel was born in [[Calanda, Spain|Calanda]], a small town in the [[Teruel (province)|province of Teruel]], in the [[Aragon]] region of Spain, to Leonardo Bu\u00f1uel, the cultivated scion of an established Aragonese family, and Mar\u00eda Portol\u00e9s, many years younger than her husband, with wealth and family connections of her own.<ref name=Alcala>{{cite book|last=Alcal\u00e1|first=Manuel|title=Bu\u00f1uel (Cine e ideologia)|year=1973|publisher=Edicusa|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-229-0101-3}}</ref>{{rp|pp.16\u201317}} He would later describe his birthplace by saying that in Calanda, \"the [[Middle Ages]] lasted until [[World War&nbsp;I]]\".<ref>Bu\u00f1uel, Luis. ''My Last Sigh''. Trans. Abigail Israel. Minneapolis: [[University of Minnesota Press]], 2003. {{ISBN|0-8166-4387-3}}. page 8.</ref> The oldest of seven children, Luis had two brothers, Alfonso and Leonardo, and four sisters: Alicia, Concepci\u00f3n, Margarita and Mar\u00eda.<ref name=schwarze>{{cite book|last=Schwarze|first=Michael|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|year=1988|publisher=Plaza & Janes|location=Barcelona|isbn=978-84-01-45079-2|pages=9}}</ref>\n\nWhen Bu\u00f1uel was four and a half months old, the family moved to [[Zaragoza]], where they were one of the wealthiest families in town.<ref name=Alcala />{{rp|p.22}} In Zaragoza, Bu\u00f1uel received a strict [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] education at the private Colegio del Salvador.<ref name=Alcala />{{rp|pp.23\u201336}} After being kicked and insulted by the study hall proctor before a final exam, Bu\u00f1uel refused to return to the school.<ref name=\"directors guide\" />  He told his mother he had been expelled, which was not true; in fact, he had received the highest marks on his world history exam.<ref>Bu\u00f1uel, Luis. ''My Last Sigh''. Trans. Abigail Israel. Minneapolis: University of Minnesota Press, 2003. {{ISBN|0-8166-4387-3}}. page 30.</ref> Bu\u00f1uel finished the last two years of his high school education at the local public school.<ref name=\"directors guide\">{{cite web|title=Luis Bunuel|url=http://www.greatestdirectors.com/buneul.html|website=The Directors Guide|publisher=Website Creations|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref>  Even as a child, Bu\u00f1uel was something of a cinematic showman; friends from that period described productions in which Bu\u00f1uel would project shadows on a screen using a [[magic lantern]] and a bedsheet.<ref name=\"A Proposito de Bunuel\">{{cite web|last=Gobierno de Aragon|title=A Proposito de Bunuel \u2013 Screenplay|url=http://www.american-buddha.com/bunuel.screenplay.htm|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> He also excelled at boxing and playing the violin.<ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\" />\n\n[[File:Salvador Dal\u00ed 1939.jpg|thumb|left|[[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]]]\n\nIn his youth, Bu\u00f1uel was deeply religious, serving at Mass and taking Communion every day, until, at the age of 16, he grew disgusted with what he perceived as the illogicality of the Church, along with its power and wealth.<ref name=brandon>{{cite book|last=Brandon|first=Ruth|title=Surreal Lives: The Surrealists 1917\u20131945|year=1999|publisher=Macmillan|location=London|isbn=978-0-8021-3727-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9_Z0rVDhNGsC&pg=PA291&lpg=PA291&dq=bunuel+agronomy#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20agronomy}}</ref>{{rp|p.292}}\n\nIn 1917, he attended the [[Complutense University of Madrid|University of Madrid]], first studying [[agronomy]] then [[industrial engineering]] and finally switching to [[philosophy]].<ref name=\"smith celebrities\">{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Warren Allen|title=Celebrities in Hell|year=2002|publisher=Barricade Books|location=Fort Lee, NJ|isbn=978-1-56980-214-4|pages=25|url=https://books.google.com/?id=x73FqQgvzgQC&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=luis+bunuel+agronomy#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20agronomy}}</ref>  He developed a very close relationship with painter [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]] and poet [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]], among other important Spanish creative artists living in the [[Residencia de Estudiantes]], with the three friends forming the nucleus of the Spanish Surrealist [[avant-garde]],<ref name=delgado>{{cite book|last=Delgado|first=Manuel and Alice J. Poust|title=Lorca, Bu\u0146uel, Dal\u00ed: Art and Theory|year=2001|publisher=Associated University Presses|location=Cranbury NJ|isbn=978-0-8387-5508-2|pages=passim|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fOJRnesy3x8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  and becoming known as members of \"[[Generation of '27|La Generaci\u00f3n del 27]]\".<ref name=poets.org>{{cite web|title=La Generacion del 27: Dal\u00ed, Bu\u00f1uel, and Lorca|url=http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/5944|publisher=Poets.org|accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel was especially taken with Lorca, later writing in his autobiography: \"We liked each other instantly.  Although we seemed to have little in common\u2014I was a redneck from Aragon, and he an elegant Andalusian\u2014we spent most of our time together... We used to sit on the grass in the evenings behind the Residencia (at that time, there were vast open spaces reaching to the horizon), and he would read me his poems. He read slowly and beautifully, and through him I began to discover a wholly new world.\"<ref name=\"my last sigh\">{{cite book|last=Bu\u00f1uel|first=Luis|title=My last sigh|url=https://archive.org/details/mylastsigh0000buue|url-access=registration|year=1983|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-394-52854-0}}</ref>{{rp|p.62}} Bu\u00f1uel's relationship with Dal\u00ed was somewhat more troubled, being tinged with jealousy over the growing intimacy between Dal\u00ed and Lorca and resentment over Dal\u00ed's early success as an artist.<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.300}}\n\n[[File:Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca. Huerta de San Vicente, Granada.jpg|thumb|[[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]]]]\n\nSince he was 17, he steadily dated the future poet and dramatist [[Concha M\u00e9ndez]], with whom he vacationed every summer at [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]]. He introduced her to his friends at the Residencia as his fianc\u00e9e.<ref name=bellver>{{cite book|last=Bellver|first=Catherine Gullo|title=Absence and Presence: Spanish Women Poets of the Twenties and Thirties|year=2001|publisher=Bucknell University Press|location=Lewisburg, PA|isbn=978-0-8387-5463-4|pages=232}}</ref><ref name=wilcox>{{cite book|last=Wilcox|first=John Chapman|title=Women Poets of Spain, 1860\u20131990: Toward a Gynocentric Vision|year=1997|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana and Chicago| isbn=978-0-252-06559-0|pages=125|url=https://books.google.com/?id=i8RlmBiUl68C&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125&dq=concha+mendez+bunuel#v=onepage&q=concha%20mendez%20bunuel}}</ref>   After five years, she broke off the relationship, citing Bu\u00f1uel's \"insufferable character\".<ref name=agonia.net>{{cite web|title=Biografia Concha Mendez Cuesta|url=http://portugues.agonia.net/index.php/author/0028634/index.html|publisher=Agonia.Net|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring his student years, Bu\u00f1uel became an accomplished hypnotist. He claimed that once, while calming a hysterical prostitute through [[hypnosis|hypnotic]] suggestion, he inadvertently put one of the several bystanders into a trance as well.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.67}} He was often to insist that watching movies was a form of hypnosis:  \"This kind of cinematographic hypnosis is no doubt due to the darkness of the theatre and to the rapidly changing scenes, lights, and camera movements, which weaken the spectator's critical intelligence and exercise over him a kind of fascination.\"<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.69}}\n\nBu\u00f1uel's interest in films was intensified by a viewing of [[Fritz Lang]]'s ''[[Destiny (1921 film)|Der m\u00fcde Tod]]'': \"I came out of the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Vieux-Colombier|Vieux Colombier]] [theater] completely transformed. Images could and did become for me the true means of expression. I decided to devote myself to the cinema\".<ref name=\"Buffalo Film Seminars 1\">{{cite web|last=Christian|first=Diane, and Bruce Jackson|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel That Obscure Object of Desire/ Cet obscur oject du d\u00e9sir 1977|url=http://csac.buffalo.edu/desire.pdf|website=Buffalo Film Seminars|publisher=Market Arcade Film & Arts Center and State University of New York at Buffalo|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref>  At age 72, Bu\u00f1uel had not lost his enthusiasm for this film, asking the octogenarian Lang for his autograph.<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.301}}\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early French period  (1925\u20131930)===\n[[File:Jean epstein 1920.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Jean Epstein]], Bu\u00f1uel's first film collaborator]]\nIn 1925 Bu\u00f1uel moved to Paris, where he began work as a secretary in an organization called the International Society of Intellectual Cooperation.<ref name=\"bfi vol 3\">{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Paul|title=\"L'Age d'Or\" in British Film Institute Film Classics, Volume 3|year=2003|publisher=Taylor and Francis|location=New York|isbn=978-1-57958-328-6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=V96tee1l2q8C&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&dq=bunuel+intellectual+cooperation#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20intellectual%20cooperation}}</ref>{{rp|p.124}} He also became actively involved in cinema and theater, going to the movies as often as three times a day.<ref name=williams>{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Alan Larson|title=Republic of Images: A History of French Filmmaking|year=1992|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-674-76267-1|pages=152|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ESVZOghoi6kC&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=jean+epstein+luis+bunuel#v=onepage&q=jean%20epstein%20luis%20bunuel}}</ref> Through these interests, he met a number of influential people, including the pianist [[Ricardo Vi\u00f1es]], who was instrumental in securing Bu\u00f1uel's selection as artistic director of the Dutch premiere of [[Manuel de Falla]]'s puppet-opera ''[[El retablo de maese Pedro]]'' in 1926.<ref name=talens>{{cite book|last=Tal\u00e9ns|first=Jenaro|title=The Branded Eye: Bu\u00f1uel's Un Chien Andalou|year=1993|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-2046-3|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5209-5Ai_ZwC&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=bunuel+abel+gance#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20abel%20gance}}</ref>{{rp|p.29}}\n\nHe decided to enter the film industry and enrolled in a private film school run by [[Jean Epstein]] and some associates.<ref name=williams />  At that time, Epstein was one of the most celebrated commercial directors working in France, his films being hailed as \"the triumph of [[impressionism]] in motion, but also the triumph of the modern spirit\".<ref name=sadoul>{{cite book|last=Sadoul|first=Georges|title=Dictionary of Film Makers|year=1972|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley & Los Angeles|isbn=978-0-520-02151-8|pages=77|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PvsZikRu-hAC&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=jean+epstein+reputation#v=onepage&q=jean%20epstein%20reputation}}</ref>   Before long, Bu\u00f1uel was working for Epstein as an assistant director on ''[[Mauprat (film)|Mauprat]]'' (1926) and ''[[The Fall of the House of Usher (1928 French film)|La chute de la maison Usher]]'' (1928),<ref name=edwards>{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Gwynne|title=A Companion to Lu\u00eds Bu\u00f1uel|year=2005|publisher=Tamesis|location=Woodbridge|isbn=978-1-85566-108-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=r5_VlQTnbD0C&pg=PA21&lpg=PA21&dq=bunuel+epstein#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20baker}}</ref> and also for [[Mario Nalpas]] on ''La Sir\u00e8ne des Tropiques'' (1927), starring [[Josephine Baker]].<ref name=fandor>{{cite web|title=Siren of the Tropics|url=http://www.fandor.com/films/siren_of_the_tropics|website=fandor|publisher=Our Film Festival, Inc.|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref>  He appeared on screen in a small part as a smuggler in [[Jacques Feyder]]'s ''[[Carmen (1926 film)|Carmen]]'' (1926).<ref name=\"brain juice\">{{cite web|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://www.brain-juice.com/cgi-bin/show_bio.cgi?p_id=136|website=brain-juice|publisher=Brain-Juice.Com, Inc.|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhen Bu\u00f1uel somewhat derisively refused to acquiesce to Epstein's demand that he assist Epstein's mentor, [[Abel Gance]], who was at the time working on the film ''[[Napol\u00e9on (1927 film)|Napol\u00e9on]]'', Epstein dismissed him angrily, saying \"How can a little asshole like you dare to talk that way about a great director like Gance?\"<ref name=talens />{{rp|p.30}} then added \"You seem rather surrealist. Beware of surrealists, they are crazy people.\"<ref name=\"de la colina\">{{cite book|last=De La Colina|first=Jose|title=Objects of Desire: Conversations with Luis Bunuel|year=1994|publisher=Marsilio Publishers|isbn=978-0-941419-69-7|pages=80}}</ref>\n\nAfter parting with Epstein, Bu\u00f1uel worked as film critic for ''La Gaceta Literaria'' (1927) and ''Les Cahiers d'Art'' (1928).<ref name=talens />{{rp|p.30}} In the periodicals ''L'Amic de les Arts'' and ''La gaseta de les Arts'', he and Dal\u00ed carried on a series of \"call and response\" essays on cinema and theater, debating such technical issues as segmentation, [[Cut-up technique|d\u00e9coupage]], \"photogenia\" (founded on the [[Insert (filmmaking)|insert shot]]) and [[Film editing|rhythmic editing]].<ref name=\"dali collected writings\">{{cite book|last=Dal\u00ed|first=Salvador|title=The Collected Writings of Salvador Dal\u00ed|year=1998|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-56027-6|url=http://www.paolocirio.net/work/amazon-noir/amazon-noir-books/AMAZON-NOIR--The_Collected_Writings_of_Salvador_Dal%C3%AD--By--Salvador_Dali_Haim_N_Finkelstein--0521560276.pdf}}</ref>  He also collaborated with the celebrated writer [[Ram\u00f3n G\u00f3mez de la Serna]] on the script for what he hoped would be his first film, \"a story in six scenes\" called ''Los caprichos''.<ref name=talens />{{rp|pp.30\u201331}}  Through his involvement with ''Gaceta Literaria'', he helped establish Madrid's first cine-club and served as its inaugural chairman.<ref name=\"gomez mesa\">{{cite journal|last=G\u00f3mez Mesa|first=Luis.|title=La generaci\u00f3n cinematogr\u00e1fica del '27|journal=Cinema 2002|year=1978|issue= 37|pages=52\u201358}}</ref>\n\nIt was during this time that he met his future wife, Jeanne Rucar Lefebvre,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.redaragon.com/trebede/feb2000/articulo2.asp |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085450/http://www.redaragon.com/trebede/feb2000/articulo2.asp |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://elpais.com/diario/1994/11/07/agenda/784162802_850215.html</ref> a [[gymnastics]] teacher who had won a bronze medal at the 1924 Paris Olympics.<ref name=\"edwards 2009\">{{cite book |last1=Edwards |first1=Gwynne |title=Lorca, Bu\u00f1uel, Dal\u00ed: Forbidden Pleasures and Connected Lives |date=2009 |publisher=I.B. Tauris |location=London |isbn=978-1848850071 |page=86 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=CA34AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT72&lpg=PT72&dq=Olympic+bronze+medal+jeanne+rucar#v=onepage&q=Olympic%20bronze%20medal%20jeanne%20rucar&f=false |accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"max aub 2017\">{{cite book |last1=Aub |first1=Max |title=Conversations with Bunuel: Interviews with the Filmmaker, Family Members, Friends and Collaborators |date=2017 |publisher=McFarland |location=Jefferson, NC |isbn=978-1476668222 |page=154 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=1sm4DgAAQBAJ&pg=PA154&lpg=PA154&dq=Olympic+bronze+medal+jeanne+rucar#v=onepage&q=Olympic%20bronze%20medal%20jeanne%20rucar&f=false}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel courted her in a formal Aragonese manner, complete with a chaperone,<ref name=\"bbc world service\">{{cite web|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: In The Directors' Chair|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/arts/highlights/000919_bunuel.shtml|publisher=BBC World Service|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>  and they married in 1934<ref name=\"brain juice\" /> despite a warning by Jean Epstein when Bu\u00f1uel first proposed in 1930:  \"Jeanne, you are making a mistake... It's not right for you, don't marry him.\"<ref name=\"jeanne rucar\">{{cite book|last=Rucar de Bu\u00f1uel|first=Jeanne|title=Memoirs of a Woman Without a Piano: My Life with Luis Bu\u00f1uel|year=2010|publisher=Five Ties Publishing|location=Brooklyn|isbn=978-0-9794727-6-3|pages=43}}</ref> The two remained married throughout his life and had two sons, [[Juan Luis Bu\u00f1uel|Juan Luis]] and Rafael.<ref name=\"Centro Virtual Cervantes\">{{cite web|title=Rafael Bunuel, Escultor|url=http://cvc.cervantes.es/actcult/bunuel/entrevistas/r_bunuel.htm|website=Centro Virtual Cervantes|publisher=Instituto Cervantes|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> [[Diego Bu\u00f1uel]], filmmaker and host of the [[National Geographic Channel]]'s ''[[Don't Tell My Mother]]'' series, is their grandson.<ref name=\"nat geo\">{{cite web|title=Nat Geo Adventure|url=http://natgeoadventure.tv/int/user.aspx?userid=10703|publisher=NGC-UK Partnership|accessdate=23 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813071957/http://natgeoadventure.tv/int/User.aspx?userId=10703|archivedate=13 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====''Un Chien Andalou'' (1929)====\nAfter this apprenticeship, Bu\u00f1uel shot \nand directed a 16-minute short, ''[[Un Chien Andalou]]'', with [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. The film, financed by Bu\u00f1uel's mother,<ref name=\"brain juice andalusian dog\">{{cite web|title=Un chien Andalou (An Andalusian Dog, 1929) |url=http://www.brain-juice.com/cgi-bin/show_wok.cgi?p_id=136&w_id=391 |publisher=Brain-Juice.Com |accessdate=23 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061205212607/http://www.brain-juice.com/cgi-bin/show_wok.cgi?p_id=136&w_id=391 |archivedate=5 December 2006 }}</ref> consists of a series of startling images of a [[Freudian]] nature,<ref name=mansfield>{{cite book|last=Mansfield|first=Nick|title=Subjectivity: Theories of the Self from Freud to Haraway|year=2000|publisher=New York University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8147-5650-8|pages=36|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qBVh5gVTlC4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  starting with a woman's eyeball being sliced open with a razor blade. ''Un Chien Andalou'' was enthusiastically received by the burgeoning French [[surrealism|surrealist]] movement of the time<ref name=richardson>{{cite book|last=Richardson|first=Michael|title=Surrealism and Cinema|year=2006|publisher=Berg|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-84520-225-5|pages=27|url=https://books.google.com/?id=v1C6E_zJi6UC&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=chien+andalou+reception+surrealist#v=onepage&q=chien%20andalou%20reception%20surrealist}}</ref> and continues to be shown regularly in [[Film society|film societies]] to this day.<ref name=mathijs>{{cite book|last=Mathijs|first=Ernest|title=Cult Cinema|year=2011|publisher=Blackwell|location=West Sussex|isbn=978-1-4051-7374-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uPtuaV7IAt0C&pg=PT194&lpg=PT194&dq=chien+andalou+film+societies#v=onepage&q=chien%20andalou%20film%20societies}}</ref>\n\nThe script was written in six days at Dal\u00ed's home in [[Cadaqu\u00e9s]]. In a letter to a friend written in February 1929, Bu\u00f1uel described the writing process: \"We had to look for the plot line. Dal\u00ed said to me, 'I dreamed last night of ants swarming around in my hands', and I said, 'Good Lord, and I dreamed that I had sliced somebody or other's eye. There's the film, let's go and make it.'\"<ref name=etherington-smith>{{cite book|last=Etherington-Smith|first=Meredith|title=The Persistence of Memory: A Biography of Dal\u00ed|year=1995|publisher=Da Capo Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-306-80662-9|pages=94|url=https://books.google.com/?id=soncxLrkYX0C&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=We+had+to+look+for+the+plot+line.+Dal%C3%AD+said+to+me,+%22I+dreamed+last+night+of+ants+swarming+around+in+my+hands%27,+and+I+said,+%22Good+Lord,+and+I+dreamed+that+I+had+sliced+somebody+or+other%27s+eye.+There%27s+the+film,+let%27s+go+and+make+it.#v=onepage&q=We%20had%20to%20look%20for%20the%20plot%20line.%20Dal%C3%AD%20said%20to%20me%2C%20%22I%20dreamed%20last%20night%20of%20ants%20swarming%20around%20in%20my%20hands%27%2C%20and%20I%20said%2C%20%22Good%20Lord%2C%20and%20I%20dreamed%20that%20I%20had%20sliced%20somebody%20or%20other%27s%20eye.%20There%27s%20the%20film%2C%20let%27s%20go%20and%20make%20it.}}</ref>  In deliberate contrast to the approach taken by Jean Epstein and his peers, which was to never leave anything in their work to chance, with every aesthetic decision having a rational explanation and fitting clearly into the whole,<ref name=\"o'donoghue\">{{cite magazine|last=O'Donoghue|first=Darragh|title=On Some Motifs in Poe: Jean Epstein's La Chute de la maison Usher|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2004/feature-articles/la_chute_de_la_maison_usher/#b4|magazine=Senses of Cinema|accessdate=27 July 2012|date=12 February 2004}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel and Dal\u00ed made a cardinal point of eliminating all logical\nassociations.<ref name=Adamowicz>{{cite book|last=Adamowicz|first=Elza|title=Un Chien Andalou: (Luis Bu\u00f1uel and Salvador Dal\u00ed, 1929)|year=2010|publisher=I.B.Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1-84885-056-9|pages=8|url=http://www.ibtauris.com/Books/The%20arts/Film%20TV%20%20radio/Films%20cinema/Film%20guides%20%20reviews/~/media/Files/Extracts/Visual%20Culture/9781848850569.ashx}}</ref>   In Bu\u00f1uel's words: \"Our only rule was very simple: no idea or image that might lend itself to a rational explanation of any kind would be accepted. We had to open all doors to the irrational and keep only those images that surprised us, without trying to explain why\".<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.104}}\n[[File:Andr\u00e9 Breton 1924.jpg|thumb|right|190px|Andr\u00e9 Breton 1924<br/>Breton defined Surrealism as: \"Pure psychic automatism through which it is intended to express, either orally or in writing, or in any other way, the actual way thought works.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Breton|first=Andre|title=Manifestoes of Surrealism|year=1969|publisher=University of Michigan Press|location=Ann Arbor|isbn=978-0-472-06182-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/manifestoesofsur0000bret/page/3 3]|title-link=Manifestoes of Surrealism}}</ref>]]\nIt was Bu\u00f1uel's intention to shock and insult the intellectual bourgeoisie of his youth, later saying:  \"Historically the film represents a violent reaction against what in those days was called 'avant-garde,' which was aimed exclusively at artistic sensibility and the audience's reason.\"<ref name=\"art in cinema\">{{cite book|last=Bu\u00f1uel|first=Luis|title=\"Notes on the Making of Un Chien Andalou\", in Art in Cinema : documents toward a history of the film society|year=2006|publisher=Temple University Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=978-1-59213-425-0|pages=101\u2013102|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/32547313/Art-in-Cinema}}</ref>  Against his hopes and expectations, the film was a huge success amongst the French bourgeoisie,<ref name=koller>{{cite web|last=Koller|first=Michael|title=Un Chien Andalou|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2001/cteq/chien/|website=Senses of Cinema|publisher=Film Victoria|accessdate=23 July 2012|date=9 June 2011}}</ref> leading Bu\u00f1uel to exclaim in exasperation, \"What can I do about the people who adore all that is new, even when it goes against their deepest convictions, or about the insincere, corrupt press, and the inane herd that saw beauty or poetry in something which was basically no more than a desperate impassioned call for murder?\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bu\u00f1uel|first=Luis|title=Preface to the script for Un Chien Andalou|journal=La R\u00e9volution Surr\u00e9aliste|date=12 December 1929|volume=no. 12}}</ref>\n\nAlthough ''Un Chien Andalou'' is a [[silent film]], during the original screening (attended by the elite of the Parisian art world),  Bu\u00f1uel played a sequence of phonograph records which he switched manually while keeping his pockets full of stones with which to pelt anticipated hecklers.<ref name=\"maverick arts\">{{cite web|title=Un Chien Andalou|url=http://www.maverick-arts.com/cgi-bin/MAVERICK?&issue=340|publisher=Maverick Arts Magazine|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> After the premiere, Bu\u00f1uel and Dal\u00ed were granted formal admittance to the tight-knit community of Surrealists, led by poet [[Andr\u00e9 Breton]].<ref name=hoberman />\n\n====''L'Age d'Or'' (1930)====\nLate in 1929, on the strength of ''Un Chien Andalou'', Bu\u00f1uel and Dal\u00ed were commissioned to make another short film by [[Marie-Laure de Noailles|Marie-Laurie]] and [[Charles de Noailles]], owners of a private cinema on the [[Place des \u00c9tats-Unis]] and financial supporters of productions by Jacques Manuel, [[Man Ray]] and [[Pierre Chenal]].<ref name=\"bfi vol 3\" />{{rp|p.124}}  At first, the intent was that the new film be around the same length as ''Un Chien'', only this time with sound. But by mid-1930, the film had grown segmentally to an hour's duration.<ref name=\"bfi vol 3\" />{{rp|p.116}} Anxious that it was over twice as long as planned and at double the budget, Bu\u00f1uel offered to trim the film and cease production, but Noailles gave him the go-ahead to continue the project.<ref name=\"bfi vol 3\" />{{rp|p.116}}\n\nThe film, entitled ''[[L'Age d'Or]]'', was begun as a second collaboration with Dal\u00ed, but, while working on the scenario, the two had a falling out;  Bu\u00f1uel, who at the time had strong leftist sympathies,<ref name=gubern>{{cite book|last=Gubern|first=Rom\u00e1n and Paul Hammond|title=Luis Bunuel: The Red Years, 1929\u20131939|year=2012|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison|isbn=978-0-299-28474-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=elueEkeLL_oC&pg=PA427&lpg=PA427&dq=bunuel+espana+1936#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20espana%201936}}</ref> desired a deliberate undermining of all bourgeois institutions, while Dal\u00ed, who eventually supported the Spanish fascist [[Francisco Franco]] and various figures of the European aristocracy, wanted merely to cause a scandal through the use of various [[Scatology|scatological]] and anti-Catholic images.<ref name=\"film reference\">{{cite web|title=Marxism \u2013 European Cinema Before and After World War II|url=http://www.filmreference.com/encyclopedia/Independent-Film-Road-Movies/Marxism-EUROPEAN-CINEMA-BEFORE-AND-AFTER-WORLD-WAR-II.html|website=film reference|publisher=Advameg, Inc.|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> The friction between them was exacerbated when, at a dinner party in Cadaqu\u00e9s, Bu\u00f1uel tried to throttle Dal\u00ed's girlfriend, [[Gala Dal\u00ed|Gala]], the wife of Surrealist poet [[Paul \u00c9luard]].<ref name=thurlow>{{cite book|last=Thurlow|first=Clifford|title=Making Short Films: The Complete Guide from Script to Screen, 2nd ed|year=2008|publisher=Berg|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-84520-803-5|pages=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HX8XcfTw6KIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  In consequence, Dal\u00ed had nothing to do with the actual shooting of the film.<ref name=dali>{{cite book|last=Dal\u00ed|first=Salvador|title=The Secret Life of Salvador Dali|year=1942|publisher=Dial Press|location=New York}}</ref>{{rp|pp.276\u2013277}}   During the course of production, Bu\u00f1uel worked around his technical ignorance by filming mostly in sequence and using nearly every foot of film that he shot. Bu\u00f1uel invited friends and acquaintances to appear, gratis, in the film; for example, anyone who owned a tuxedo or a party frock got a part in the salon scene.<ref name=\"bfi vol 3\" />{{rp|p.116}}\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=left|width=25%|quote=\"A film called ''L'Age d'or'', whose non-existent artistic quality is an insult to any kind of technical standard, combines, as a public spectacle, the most obscene, disgusting and tasteless incidents. Country, family, and religion are dragged through the mud\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Bodin|first=Richard Pierre|title=Review of \"L'age d'Or\"|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=7 December 1930}}</ref> |source=Excerpt from Richard Pierre Bodin's review in ''[[Le Figaro]]'', 7 December 1930.}} ''L'Age d'Or'' was publicly proclaimed by Dal\u00ed as a deliberate attack on Catholicism, and this precipitated a much larger scandal than ''Un Chien Andalou''.<ref name=fanes>{{cite book|last=Fan\u00e9s|first=F\u00e8lix|title=Salvador Dali: The Construction of the Image|year=2007|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven|isbn=978-0-300-09179-3|pages=171|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bDpziok_K7gC&pg=PA171&lpg=PA171&dq=l%27age+d%27or+dali+dispute+bunuel#v=onepage&q=l%27age%20d%27or%20dali%20dispute%20bunuel}}</ref>  One early screening was taken over by members of the fascist [[Ligue des Patriotes|League of Patriots]] and the Anti-Jewish Youth Group, who hurled purple ink at the screen<ref name=\"ado kyrou\">{{cite book|last=Kyrou|first=Ado|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: an introduction|year=1963|publisher=Simon and Schuster|location=New York|pages=30}}</ref> and then vandalised the adjacent art gallery, destroying a number of valuable surrealist paintings.<ref name=moria>{{cite web|last=Scheib|first=Richard|title=L'Age d'Or|url=http://www.moria.co.nz/fantasy/lagedor.htm|publisher=Moria \u2013 The Science Fiction, Horror and Fantasy Film Review|accessdate=23 July 2012|date=15 December 2005}}</ref>  The film was banned by the Parisian police \"in the name of public order\".<ref name=\"Instituto Cervantes\">{{cite book|last=Instituto Cervantes|title=Bu\u00f1uel, 100 a\u00f1o: es peligroso asomarse al Interior/ Bu\u00f1uel, 100 Years: It' s Dangerous to Look Inside|year=2001|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8109-6219-4|pages=62}}</ref>  The de Noailles, both Catholics, were threatened with [[Excommunication#Roman Catholic Church|excommunication]] by [[Holy See|The Vatican]] because of the film's blasphemous final scene (which visually links [[Jesus Christ]] with the writings of the [[Marquis de Sade]]), so they made the decision in 1934 to withdraw all prints from circulation, and ''L'Age d'Or'' was not seen again until 1979, after their deaths,<ref name=laufer>{{cite web|last=Laufer|first=Laura|title=L'\u00c2ge d'or\" de Luis Bunuel|url=http://adagio.over-blog.fr/article-25951854.html|publisher=Le Centre Georges-Pompidou|accessdate=23 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615233326/http://adagio.over-blog.fr/article-25951854.html|archivedate=15 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> although a print was smuggled to England for private viewing.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lim|first1=Dennis|title=The Village Voice Film Guide: 50 Years of Movies from Classics to Cult Hits|date=2006|publisher=Wiley|location=New York|isbn=978-0471787815|page=7|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yHcIp0sa6MkC&pg=PA7&dq=l%27age+d%27or+banned#v=onepage&q=l'age%20d'or%20banned|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>  The furor was so great that the premiere of another film financed by the de Noailles, [[Jean Cocteau]]'s ''[[The Blood of a Poet]]'', had to be delayed for over two years until outrage over ''L'Age d'Or'' had died down.<ref name=burke>{{cite book|last=Burke|first=Carolyn|title=Lee Miller: A Life|year=2005|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-375-40147-3|pages=114|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PVmJOWev0p8C&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113&dq=Noailles+excommunication#v=onepage&q=Noailles%20excommunication}}</ref> To make matters worse, Charles de Noailles was forced to withdraw his membership from the [[Jockey-Club de Paris|Jockey Club]].<ref name=teitelbaum>{{cite book|last=Teitelbaum|first=Mo Amelia|title=The Stylemakers: Minimalism and Classic-Modernism 1915\u201345|year=2010|publisher=Philip Willson|location=London|isbn=978-0-85667-703-8|pages=102|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CuT3JqcH8hcC&pg=PA102&lpg=PA102&dq=charles+de+noailles+jockey+club#v=onepage&q=charles%20de%20noailles%20jockey%20club}}</ref>\n\nConcurrent with the ''[[succ\u00e8s de scandale]]'', both Bu\u00f1uel and the film's leading lady, [[Lya Lys]], received offers of interest from [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] and traveled to Hollywood at the studio's expense.<ref name=durgnat>{{cite book|last=Durgnat|first=Raymond|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|year=1968|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley}}</ref> While in the United States, Bu\u00f1uel associated with other celebrity expatriates including [[Sergei Eisenstein]], [[Josef Von Sternberg]], Jacques Feyder, [[Charles Chaplin]] and [[Bertolt Brecht]].<ref name=\"brain juice\" />  All that was required of Bu\u00f1uel by his loose-ended contract with MGM was that he \"learn some good American technical skills\",<ref name=walters>{{cite book|last=Walters|first=Rob|title=Spread Spectrum: Hedy Lamarr And the Mobile Phone|year=2006|publisher=BookSurge Publishing|location=Great Britain|isbn=978-1-4196-2129-1|pages=65|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ciuJ0UTCnmQC&pg=PA65&lpg=PA65&dq=luis+bunuel+MGM#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20MGM}}</ref> but, after being ushered off the first set he visited because the star, [[Greta Garbo]], did not welcome intruders, he decided to stay at home most of the time and only show up to collect his paycheck.<ref name=Doniol-Valcroze>{{cite journal|last=Doniol-Valcroze|first=Jacques|author2=Andr\u00e9 Bazin|title=Entretien avec Luis Bu\u00f1uel|journal=Cahiers du Cinema|date=July 1954|issue=37|pages=44\u201348}}</ref>  His only enduring contribution to MGM came when he served as an extra in ''La Fruta Amarga'', a Spanish-language remake of ''[[Min and Bill]]''.<ref name=jarvinen>{{cite book|last=Jarvinen|first=Lisa|title=The Rise of Spanish-Language Filmmaking: Out from Hollywood's Shadow, 1929\u20131939|year=2012|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=Piscataway NJ|isbn=978-0-8135-5328-3|pages=58|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W10o8udrUakC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>   When, after a few months at the studio, he was asked to watch [[Dailies|rushes]] of [[Lili Damita]] to gauge her Spanish accent, he refused and sent a message to studio boss [[Irving Thalberg]] stating that he was there as a Frenchman, not a Spaniard, and he \"didn't have time to waste listening to one of the whores\".<ref name=bazin>{{cite book|last=Bazin|first=Andre|title=Bu\u0146uel, Dreyer, Welles|year=1991|publisher=Editorial Fundamentos|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-245-0521-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=S4mCa7JzhI8C&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=luis+bunuel+damita#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20damita}}</ref>{{rp|p.18}}  He was back in Spain shortly thereafter.<ref name=durgnat />\n\n===Spain (1931\u20131937)===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Screen capture of classroom scene from Las Hurdas, Tierra Sin Pan.jpeg|299px|thumb|The classroom scene from ''Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan'' is an ironic statement of Bu\u00f1uel's Marxist sympathies.<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.59}}]]  -->\nSpain in the early 1930s was a time of political and social turbulence, a period of intense and bloody upheaval.<ref name=blinkhorn>{{cite book|last=Blinkhorn|first=Martin|title=Democracy And Civil War in Spain 1931\u20131939|year=1988|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-0-415-00699-6|pages=3\u201331|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CnJawWYdjNUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=spain+1931+upheaval#v=onepage&q=spain%201931%20upheaval}}</ref> Anarchists and [[Radical Socialist Republican Party|Radical Socialists]] sacked [[Monarchism|monarchist]] headquarters in [[Madrid]] and proceeded to set afire or otherwise wreck more than a dozen churches in the capital while similar revolutionary acts occurred in a score of other cities in southern and eastern Spain, in most cases with the acquiescence and occasionally with the assistance of the official Republican authorities.<ref name=payne>{{cite book|last=Payne|first=Stanley G.|title=A History of Spain and Portugal, V. 2|year=1976|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison|isbn=978-0-299-06284-2|pages=630|url=http://libro.uca.edu/payne2/payne25.htm}}</ref>\n\nBu\u00f1uel's future wife, Jeanne Rucar, recalled that during that period, \"he got very excited about politics and the ideas that were everywhere in pre-Civil War Spain\".<ref name=\"rucar de bunuel espanol\">{{cite book|last=Rucar de Bu\u00f1uel|first=Jeanne|title=Memorias de un mujer sin piano|year=1990|publisher=Alianza Editorial|location=Madrid|isbn=978-9683903907|pages=58}}</ref> In the first flush of his enthusiasm, Bu\u00f1uel joined the [[Communist Party of Spain]] (PCE) in 1931<ref name=gubern />{{rp|pp.85\u2013114}} though later in life he denied becoming a Communist.<ref name=aub>{{cite book|last=Aub|first=Max|title=Conversaciones con Bu\u00f1uel: Seguidas de 45 entrevistas con familiares, amigos y colaboradores del cineasta aragon\u00e9s |year=1985|publisher=Aguilar|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-03-09195-5}}</ref>{{rp|p.72}}\n\n[[File:Screen capture from Las Hurdas, Tierra Sin Pan.jpeg|left|thumb|269px|An early scene from ''Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan'' depicts a local wedding custom where the bridegroom tears the head off a rooster suspended by its feet from a scaffold above the main street of town.<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.57}}]] \nIn 1932, Bu\u00f1uel was invited to serve as film documentarian for the celebrated ''Mission Dakar-Djibouti'', the first large-scale French anthropological field expedition, which, led by [[Marcel Griaule]], unearthed some 3,500 African artifacts for the new [[Mus\u00e9e de l'Homme]].<ref name=ruoff-45>{{cite journal|last=Ruoff|first=Jeffrey|title=An Ethnographic Surrealist Film: Luis Bu\u00f1uel's Land Without Bread|url=https://www.dartmouth.edu/~jruoff/Articles/EthnographicSurrealist.htm|journal=Visual Anthropology Review|date=Spring\u2013Summer 1998|volume=14|issue=1|pages=45\u201357|accessdate=10 January 2016|doi=10.1525/var.1998.14.1.45}}</ref> Although he declined, the project piqued his interest in [[ethnography]]. After reading the academic study, ''Las Jurdes: \u00e9tude de g\u00e9ographie humaine'' (1927) by Maurice Legendre, he decided to make a film focused on [[peasant]] life in [[Extremadura]], one of Spain's poorest states.<ref name=margulies>{{cite book|last=Margulies|first=Ivone|title=Rites of Realism: Essays on Corporeal Cinema|year=2003|publisher=Duke University Press|location=Durham, NC|isbn=978-0-8223-3078-3|pages=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UP3Gf8KfsXwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  The film, called ''[[Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan]]'' (1933), was financed on a budget of 20,000 pesetas donated by a working-class [[anarchist]] friend named [[Ram\u00f3n Ac\u00edn]], who had won the money in a lottery.<ref name=weir>{{cite book|last=Weir|first=David|title=Anarchy & Culture: The Aesthetic Politics of Modernism|year=1997|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|location=Amherst| isbn=978-1-55849-083-3| pages=253 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=fRR8eWzRhbYC&pg=PA253&lpg=PA253&dq=las+hurdes+acin#v=onepage&q=las%20hurdes%20acin}}</ref> In the film, Bu\u00f1uel matches scenes of deplorable social conditions with narration that resembles travelogue commentary delivered by a detached-sounding announcer,<ref name=\"Harvard Film Archive\">{{cite web|title=Bu\u00f1uel: The Beginning and the End|url=http://hcl.harvard.edu/hfa/films/2011aprjun/bunuel.html|publisher=Harvard Film Archive|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> while the soundtrack thunders inappropriate music by [[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]].<ref name=\"Sloniowski\">{{cite journal |last1=Sloniowski |first1=Jeannette |title=\"Las Hurdes\" and the political efficacy of the grotesque |journal=Revue Canadienne d'\u00c9tudes cin\u00e9matographiques / Canadian Journal of Film Studies |date=Fall 1998 |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=30\u201348 |jstor=24402254 |doi=10.3138/cjfs.7.2.30 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"Though the material is organized with masterly skill, the very conception of 'art' here seems irrelevant.  It is the most profoundly disturbing film I have ever seen.\"<ref name=\"tony richardson\">{{cite book|last=Richardson|first=Tony|title=\"The Films of Luis Bu\u00f1uel,\" in The World of Luis Bu\u00f1uel, ed. Joan Mellen|year=1978|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-502398-5|pages=[https://archive.org/details/worldofluisbunue00luis/page/129 129]|url=https://archive.org/details/worldofluisbunue00luis/page/129}}</ref>  |source=Award-winning film director [[Tony Richardson]] on ''Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan''}}\n\n''Las Hurdes'' was banned by three successive Republican governments, definitively by [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] when he came to power.<ref name=Russell>{{cite web|last=Russell|first=Dominique|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2005/great-directors/bunuel/|website=Great Directors, Issue 35|publisher=Senses of Cinema|accessdate=31 July 2012|date=15 April 2005}}</ref> It is a film which continues to perplex viewers and resists easy categorization by film historians.<ref name=juhasz>{{cite book|last=Juhasz |first=Alexandra|title=F Is For Phony: Fake Documentary And Truth's Undoing|year=2006|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4251-9|pages=101|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TXaFokB-qx4C&dq=bunuel+las+hurdes+reading+ethnographic}}</ref>  ''Las Hurdes'' has been called one of the first examples of [[mockumentary]],<ref name=mockumentary>{{cite web|title=Week 16: Mockumentary|url=http://www.documentarysite.com/?p=101|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130121172356/http://www.documentarysite.com/?p=101|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 January 2013|website=Documentary film and video course syllabus.|publisher=Documentary Site|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref>  and has been labeled a \"surrealist documentary\", a term defined by critic Merc\u00e8 Ibarz as \"A multi-layered and unnerving use of sound, the juxtaposition of narrative forms already learnt from the written press, travelogues and new pedagogic methods, as well as a subversive use of photographed and filmed documents understood as a basis for contemporary propaganda for the masses\".<ref name=ibarz>{{cite book|last=Ibarz|first=Merc\u00e8|title=\"A Serious Experiment: Land Without Bread, 1933\", in Luis Bu\u00f1uel: New Readings. ed. Isabel Santaolalla and Peter William Evans|year=2004|publisher=British Film Institute|location=London|isbn=978-1-84457-003-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/luisbunuelnewrea0000unse/page/28 28]|url=https://archive.org/details/luisbunuelnewrea0000unse/page/28}}</ref> Catherine Russell has stated that in ''Las Hurdes'', Bu\u00f1uel was able to reconcile his political philosophy with his surrealist aesthetic, with surrealism becoming \"a means of awakening a marxist materialism in danger of becoming a stale orthodoxy\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Russell|first=Catherine|title=\"Surrealist Ethnography: Las Hurdes and the Documentary Unconscious\", in F Is for Phony: Fake Documentary And Truth's Undoing, edited by Alexandra Juhasz and Jesse Lerner|year=2006|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4251-9|page=112|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TXaFokB-qx4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Las Hurdes'' in 1933, Bu\u00f1uel worked in Paris in the [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbing]] department of [[Paramount Pictures]], but following his marriage in 1934, he switched to [[Warner Brothers]] because they operated dubbing studios in Madrid.<ref name=acevedo-munoz>{{cite book|last=Acevedo-Mu\u00f1oz|first=Ernesto R.|title=Bu\u00f1uel and Mexico: The Crisis of National Cinema|year=2003|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles| isbn=978-0-520-23952-4| url=https://books.google.com/?id=M-Q1iOxo00wC&dq=bunuel+filmofono}}</ref>{{rp|p.39}} A friend, Ricardo Urgoiti, who owned the commercial film company Film\u00f3fono, invited Bu\u00f1uel to [[Film producer|produce]] films for a mass audience. He accepted the offer, viewing it as an \"experiment\" as he knew the film industry in Spain was still far behind the technical level of Hollywood or Paris.<ref name=higginbotham>{{cite book|last=Higginbotham|first=Virginia|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|year=1979|publisher=Twayne Publishers|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8057-9261-4}}</ref>{{rp|p.56}} According to film historian Manuel Rotellar's interviews with members of the cast and crew of the Film\u00f3fono studios, Bu\u00f1uel's only condition was that his involvement with these pictures be completely anonymous, apparently for fear of damaging his reputation as a surrealist.<ref name=rotellar>{{cite journal|last=Rotellar|first=Manuel|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel en Film\u00f3fono|journal=Cinema 2002|year=1978|issue= 37|pages=36\u201340}}</ref> Rotellar insists, however, \"the truth is that it was Luis Bu\u00f1uel who directed the Film\u00f3fono productions\".<ref name=rotellar />{{rp|p.37}} [[Jos\u00e9 Luis S\u00e1enz de Heredia]], the titular director of two of the films created during Bu\u00f1uel's years as \"executive producer\" at Film\u00f3fono, recounted that it was Bu\u00f1uel who \"explained to me every morning what he wanted...We looked at the takes together and it was Bu\u00f1uel who chose the shots, and in editing, I wasn't even allowed to be present.\"<ref name=rotellar />{{rp|p.39}} Of the 18 films produced by Bu\u00f1uel during his years at Film\u00f3fono, the four that are believed by critical consensus to have been directed by him<ref name=mortimore>{{cite journal|last=Mortimore|first=Roger|title=Bu\u00f1uel, S\u00e1enz de Heredia, and Film\u00f3fono|journal=Sight and Sound|date=Summer 1975|volume=44|pages=180\u2013182}}</ref> are:\n<blockquote>\n* ''Don Quint\u00edn el amargao'' (Don Quintin the Sourpuss), 1935 \u2013 a musical based on a play by [[Carlos Arniches]],<ref name=\"fuentes, victor\">{{cite book|last=Fuentes|first=Victor|title=Los mundos de Bu\u00f1uel|year=2000|publisher=[[Ediciones Akal]]|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-460-1450-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Mdz1N3xs24IC&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57&dq=Don+Quint%C3%ADn+el+amargao+arniches+bunuel#v=onepage&q=Don%20Quint%C3%ADn%20el%20amargao%20arniches%20bunuel}}</ref> the first ''[[zarzuela]]'' (a type of Spanish opera) filmed in sound.<ref>{{cite web|title=Don Quint\u00edn el Amargao on AllMovie Don Quint\u00edn el Amargao (1935)|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/don-quint%C3%ADn-el-amargao-v235543|website=allmovie.com|publisher=AllMovie, a division of All Media Network|accessdate=2 November 2013}}</ref> \n* ''[[La hija de Juan Sim\u00f3n]]'' (Juan Sim\u00f3n's Daughter), 1935 \u2013 another musical and a major commercial success<ref name=bentley>{{cite book|last=Bentley|first=Bernard P. E.|title=A Companion to Spanish Cinema|year=2008|publisher=Tamesis|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|isbn=978-1-85566-176-9|pages=61|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M6kRqqwNMm0C&pg=PA61#v=onepage}}</ref>\n* ''\u00bfQui\u00e9n me quiere a m\u00ed?'' (Who Loves Me?), 1936 \u2013 a sentimental comedy that Bu\u00f1uel called \"my only commercial failure, and a pretty dismal one at that\".<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.144}}\n* ''\u00a1Centinela, alerta!'', (Sentry, Keep Watch!), 1937 \u2013 a comedy and Film\u00f3fono's biggest box-office hit.<ref name=bentley />\n</blockquote>\n\nDuring the [[Spanish Civil War]] (1936\u20131939), Bu\u00f1uel placed himself at the disposal of the Republican government.<ref name=\"an unspeakable betrayal\">{{cite book|last=Bu\u00f1uel|first=Luis|title=An Unspeakable Betrayal: Selected Writings of Luis Bu\u00f1uel|year=2002|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles|isbn=978-0-520-23423-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tK3KPgv34U8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.255}} The minister for foreign affairs sent him first to [[Geneva]] {{when|date=January 2016}} and then to Paris<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=elueEkeLL_oC&pg=PA260&lpg=PA260&dq=luis+bunuel+in+geneva#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20in%20geneva&f=false|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: The Red Years, 1929\u20131939, p.260|last=Gubern|first=Rom\u00e1n|last2=Hammond|first2=Paul|date=2012-01-04|publisher=University of Wisconsin Pres|isbn=9780299284732|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>{{when|date=January 2016}} for two years, with official responsibility for cataloging Republican propaganda films.<ref name=edwards />{{rp|p.6}} Besides the cataloguing, Bu\u00f1uel took left-wing tracts to Spain, did some occasional spying, acted as a bodyguard, and supervised the making of a documentary, entitled ''[[Espa\u00f1a 1936 (film)|Espa\u00f1a 1936]]''  in France and ''Espana leal, \u00a1en armas!'' in Spain, that covered the elections, the parades, the riots, and the war.<ref name=\"del olmo\">{{cite journal|last=del Olmo|first=F. Javier Ruiz|title=Language and Collective Identity in Bu\u00f1uel. Propaganda in the Film \"Espa\u00f1a 1936\" |journal=Comunicar| year=2010|volume=XVIII|issue=35|pages=69\u201376|doi=10.3916/C35-2010-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Espana leal, en armas|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b712e8a58|website=BFI Film Forever|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=6 August 2012}}</ref> In August 1936, [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]] was shot and killed by Nationalist militia.<ref name=beevor>{{cite book|last=Beevor|first=Antony|title=The Battle for Spain. The Spanish Civil War 1936\u20131939|year=2006|publisher=Penguin Books|location=London|isbn=978-0-14-303765-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/battleforspainsp00anto/page/100 100]|url=https://archive.org/details/battleforspainsp00anto/page/100}}</ref> According to his son, [[Juan Luis Bu\u00f1uel|Juan Luis]], Bu\u00f1uel rarely talked about Lorca but mourned the poet's untimely death throughout his life.<ref name=ehrlich>{{cite magazine|last=Ehrlich|first=Linda C.|title=A Bu\u00f1uel Scrapbook: The Last Script: Remembering Luis Bu\u00f1uel (1) and Calanda: 40 Years Later| url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2009/feature-articles/last-script-bunuel-calanda/|magazine=Senses of Cinema|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=9 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nBu\u00f1uel essentially functioned as the coordinator of film propaganda for the Republic, which meant that he was in a position to examine all film shot in the country and decide what sequences could be developed and distributed abroad.<ref name=faber>{{cite web|last=Faber|first=Sebastiaan|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel, chameleon: Revelations from the \"Red Decade\" |url=http://www.albavolunteer.org/2011/12/luis-bunuel-chameleon-revelations-from-the-%E2%80%9Cred-decade%E2%80%9D/|website=The Volunteer|publisher=Abraham Lincoln Brigade Archives (ALBA)|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> The Spanish Ambassador suggested that Bu\u00f1uel revisit Hollywood where he could give technical advice on films being made there about the Spanish Civil War,<ref name=edwards />{{rp|p.6}} so in 1938, he and his family traveled to the United States using funds obtained from his old patrons, the Noailles.<ref name=hoberman>{{cite journal|last=Hoberman|first=J.|title=A Charismatic Chameleon: On Luis Bu\u00f1uel|journal=The Nation|date=14 May 2012|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/167559/charismatic-chameleon-luis-bunuel#|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> Almost immediately upon his arrival in America, however, the war ended and the [[Motion Picture Association of America|Motion Picture Producers and Distributors Association of America]] discontinued making films on the Spanish conflict.<ref name=\"robert cole\">{{cite book|last=Cole|first=Robert|title=Propaganda, Censorship And Irish Neutrality in the Second World War|year=2006|publisher=Edinburgh University Press |location=Edinburgh|  isbn=978-0-7486-2277-1|pages=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wu_bOQiXGs4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> According to Bu\u00f1uel's wife, returning to Spain was impossible since the Fascists had seized power,<ref name=\"rucar de bunuel espanol\" />{{rp|p.63\u201364}} so Bu\u00f1uel decided to stay in the U.S. indefinitely, stating that he was \"immensely attracted by the American naturalness and sociability\".<ref name=\"an unspeakable betrayal\" />{{rp|p.255}}\n\n===United States (1938\u20131945)===\n[[File:Museum of modern art airways to peace exhibition 1943.jpg|295px|thumb|Museum of Modern Art, 1943]]\nReturning to Hollywood in 1938, he was befriended by Frank Davis, an MGM producer and member of the [[Communist Party USA]],<ref name=gubern />{{rp|p.349}} who placed Bu\u00f1uel on the payroll of ''Cargo of Innocence'', a film about Spanish refugee mothers and children fleeing from [[Bilbao]] to the USSR.<ref name=\"edwards - lorca etc.\">{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Gwynne|title=Lorca, Bu\u00f1uel, Dal\u00ed: forbidden pleasures and connected lives|year=2009|publisher=I. B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1-84885-007-1|pages=194}}</ref>  The project was shelved precipitately when another Hollywood film about the Spanish Civil War, ''[[Blockade (1938 film)|Blockade]]'', was met with disfavor by the [[National Legion of Decency|Catholic League of Decency]].<ref name=manchel>{{cite book|last=Manchel|first=Frank|title=Film Study: An Analytical Bibliography, Volume 1|year=1990|publisher=Associated University Presses|location=Cranbury NJ|isbn=978-0-8386-3186-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/filmstudyanalyti0000manc/page/219 219\u2013220]|url=https://archive.org/details/filmstudyanalyti0000manc/page/219}}</ref>  In the words of biographer Ruth Brandon, Bu\u00f1uel and his family \"lived from one unsatisfactory crumb of work to another\" because he \"had none of the arrogance and pushiness essential for survival in Hollywood\".<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.358}}  He just wasn't flamboyant enough to capture the attention of Hollywood decision makers, in the opinion of film composer [[George Antheil]]: \"Inasmuch as [Bu\u00f1uel], his wife and his little boy seemed to be such absolutely normal, solid persons, as totally un-Surrealist in the Dal\u00ed tradition as one could possibly imagine.\"<ref name=baxter>{{cite book|last=Baxter|first=John|title=Bu\u00f1uel|year=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7867-0619-8}}</ref>{{rp|p.172}} For the most part, he was snubbed by many of the people in the film community whom he met during his first trip to America,<ref>{{cite news|title=A documentary shows the most bitter of Bu\u00f1uel and intimate portrait|url=http://www.deltaworld.org/cinema/A-documentary-shows-the-most-bitter-of-Bu-uel-and-intimate-portrait/|accessdate=8 August 2012|newspaper=The Delta World.|date=13 July 2012}}</ref> although he was able to sell some gags to Chaplin for his film ''[[The Great Dictator]]''.<ref name=taylor />{{rp|p.213}}\n\nIn desperation, to market himself to independent producers, he composed a 21-page autobiography, a section of which, headed \"My Present Plans\", outlined proposals for two documentary films:\n* \"The Primitive Man\", which would depict \"the terrible struggle of primitive man against a hostile universe, how the world appeared, ''how they saw it'', what ideas they had on love, on death, on fraternity, how and why religion is born\", [italics in original]\n* \"Psycho-Pathology\", which would \"expose the origin and development of different psychopathic diseases... Such a documental film, apart from its great scientific interest, could depict on screen a ''New Form of Terror'' or its synonym ''Humour''.\" [italics in original]<ref name=\"an unspeakable betrayal\" />{{rp|p.257}}\n\nNobody showed any interest and Bu\u00f1uel realized that staying in Los Angeles was futile, so he traveled to New York to see if he could change his fortunes.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.174}}\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=left|width=25%|quote=\"Luis Bu\u00f1uel was there, with his thyroid eyes, the moles on his chin which I remember from so long ago when we first saw the surrealist films in the [[Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que Fran\u00e7aise|Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que]],... and as he talked I remember thinking that his paleness was most appropriate for someone who spent his life in dark projection rooms... He has a sharp humor, a bitter sarcasm, and at the same time towards women a gentle, special smile\".<ref name=Nin>{{cite book|last=Nin|first=Anais|title=Diary of Ana\u00efs Nin Volume 3 1939\u20131944: Vol. 3 (1939\u20131944)|year=1969|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|location=New York|isbn=978-0-15-626027-5|pages=109|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=igytZ9t8jsAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>   |source=[[Ana\u00efs Nin]], in her diary entry on encountering Bu\u00f1uel when he was working at MoMA}}\nIn New York, Antheil introduced Bu\u00f1uel to [[Iris Barry]], chief curator of film at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA).<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.360}}  Barry talked Bu\u00f1uel into joining a committee formed to help educate those within the U.S. government who might not have appreciated fully the effectiveness of film as a medium of propaganda. Bu\u00f1uel was hired to produce a shortened version of [[Leni Riefenstahl]]'s ''[[Triumph of the Will]]'' (1935) as a demonstration project.<ref name=trimborn>{{cite book|last=Trimborn|first=J\u00fcrgen|title=Leni Riefenstahl: A Life|year=2007|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|location=New York|isbn=978-0-374-18493-3|pages=123\u2013124|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4IFvjEArNg8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> The finished product was a compilation of scenes from Riefenstahl's [[Nazism|Nazi]] epic with [[Hans Bertram]]'s ''Feuertaufe''.<ref name=higginbotham />{{rp|p.58}} Bu\u00f1uel stayed at MoMA to work for the [[Office of the Coordinator of Inter-American Affairs]] (OCIAA) as part of a production team that would gather, review and edit films intended as anti-fascist propaganda to be distributed in [[Latin America]] by American embassies.<ref name=schreiber>{{cite book|last=Schreiber|first=Rebecca M.|title=Cold War Exiles in Mexico: U.S. Dissidents and the Culture of Critical Resistance|year=2008|publisher=Univ of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4308-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4O1AElNqAZYC&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72&dq=bunuel+museum+of+modern+art#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20museum%20of%20modern%20art}}</ref>{{rp|p.72}}  While being vetted for the job at the OCIAA, upon being asked if he was a Communist, he replied: \"I am a Republican,\" and, apparently, the interviewer did not realize that Bu\u00f1uel was referring to the Spanish socialist coalition government, not the American political party.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.180}}  Describing Bu\u00f1uel's work at MoMA, his friend, composer Gustavo Pittaluga, stated: \"Luis created maybe 2,000 remarkable works.  We were sent anodyne documentaries, often extremely feeble primary materials, which the Museum team turned into marvellous films.  And not just Spanish versions, but also Portuguese, French and English... He would ''create'' a good documentary through editing.\" [italics in original]<ref name=aranda>{{cite book|last=Aranda|first=Francisco|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: A Critical Biography|year=1976|publisher=Da Capo Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-306-70754-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/luisbunuelcritic0000aran}}</ref>{{rp|p.124}}\n\nIn 1942, Bu\u00f1uel applied for American citizenship, because he anticipated that MoMA would soon be put under federal control.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.183}}  But that same year, Dal\u00ed published his autobiography, ''[[The Secret Life of Salvador Dal\u00ed]]'', in which he made it clear that he had split with Bu\u00f1uel because the latter was a Communist and an [[atheist]].<ref name=navarro>{{cite book|last=Navarro|first=Vicente|title=\"The Jackboot of Dada\", in Serpents in the Garden: Liaisons with Culture & Sex, ed. Alexander Cockburn and Jeffery St. Clair|year=2004|publisher=AK Press|location=Oakland, CA|isbn=978-1-902593-94-4|pages=148\u2013149|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ShbksjUcH5YC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> News of this reached [[Francis Spellman|Archbishop Spellman]], who angrily confronted Barry with the question: \"Are you aware that you are harbouring in this Museum the Antichrist, the man who made a blasphemous film ''L'Age d'Or''?\"<ref name=taylor>{{cite book|last=Taylor|first=John Russell|title=Strangers in paradise: the Hollywood \u00e9migr\u00e9s, 1933\u20131950|year=1983|publisher=Holt, Rinehart & Winston|location=New York|isbn=978-0-03-061944-1|url=https://archive.org/details/strangersinparad00tayl}}</ref>{{rp|p.214}}  At the same time, a campaign on the part of Hollywood, through its industry trade paper, the ''[[Motion Picture Herald]]'', to undermine the MoMA film unit resulted in a 66% reduction in the department's budget and Bu\u00f1uel felt himself compelled to resign.<ref name=\"robert sitton\">{{cite book|last1=Sitton|first1=Robert|title=Lady in the Dark: Iris Barry and the Art of Film|date=2014|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0231165785|page=317|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fyMZBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=16 January 2015}}</ref>  In 1944, he returned to Hollywood for the third time, this time as Spanish Dubbing Producer for [[Warner Brothers]].<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.190}} Before leaving New York, he confronted Dal\u00ed at his hotel, the [[Sherry Netherland Hotel|Sherry Netherland]], to tell the painter about the damage his book had done and then shoot him in the knee.<ref name=\"don harrison\">{{cite web|last=Harrison|first=Don|title=15 Footnotes on the Moustache of Bunuel \u2013 Episodes of Luis|url=http://www.naderlibrary.com/bunuel15footnotesmoustache.htm|publisher=American Buddha|accessdate=21 August 2012}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel did not carry out the violent part of his plan. Dal\u00ed explained himself by saying: \"I did not write my book to put YOU on a pedestal. I wrote it to put ME on a pedestal\".<ref name=\"don harrison\" />\n\n[[File:Man Ray 1934.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Man Ray \u2013 a friend from Bu\u00f1uel's surrealist period and collaborator on unrealized Hollywood projects]]\nBu\u00f1uel's first dubbing assignment on returning to Hollywood was ''[[My Reputation]]'', a [[Barbara Stanwyck]] picture which became ''El Que Diran'' in Bu\u00f1uel's hands.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.190}}  In addition to his dubbing work, Bu\u00f1uel attempted to develop a number of independent projects:\n* In collaboration with an old friend from his Surrealist days, [[Man Ray]], he worked on a scenario called ''The Sewers of Los Angeles'', which took place on a mountain of excrement close to a highway and a dust basin.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.129}}\n* With his friend, [[Jos\u00e9 Rubia Barcia]], he co-wrote a screenplay called ''La novia de medianoche'' (The Midnight Bride), a gothic thriller, which lay dormant until it was filmed by Antonio Sim\u00f3n in 1997.<ref>{{cite book|last=Barcia|first=Jos\u00e9 Rubia|title=Con Luis Bu\u00f1uel en Hollywood y despu\u00e9s|year=1992|publisher=Edici\u00f3s do Castro|location=Sada, A Coru\u00f1a|isbn=978-84-7492-582-1|pages=105\u2013160}}</ref>\n* He continued working on a screenplay called \"Goya and the Duchess of Alba\", a treatment he had started as early as 1927, with the actor/producer [[Flori\u00e1n Rey]] and cameraman [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Beltr\u00e1n]], and then resuscitated in 1937 as a project for Paramount.<ref>{{cite book|last=S\u00e1nchez Vidal|first=Agust\u00edn|title=G\u00f3ngora, Bu\u00f1uel, Spanish Avant-Garde and Centenary of Goya's Death, in The Spanish Avant-Garde, ed. Derek Harris|year=1995|publisher=Manchester University Press|location=Manchester|isbn=978-0-7190-4342-0|pages=117|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cQbpAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>\n* In his 1982 autobiography ''Mon Dernier soupir'' (''My Last Sigh'', 1983, ''My Last Breath'', 1994), Bu\u00f1uel wrote that at the request of director [[Robert Florey]], he submitted a treatment of a scene about a disembodied hand, which was later included in the movie ''[[The Beast with Five Fingers]]'' (1946), starring [[Peter Lorre]], without acknowledgement of Bu\u00f1uel's contribution or payment of any compensation.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.189}}  However, Brian Taves, film scholar and archivist with the [[Library of Congress]], has challenged the truth of this claim.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Taves|first=Brian|title=Whose Hand? Correcting a Bu\u00f1uel myth|journal=Sight and Sound|date=Summer 1987|volume=56|issue=3|pages=210\u2013211}}</ref>\n\nIn 1945, Bu\u00f1uel's contract with Warner Brothers expired, and he decided not to renew it in order, as he put it: \"to realize my life's ambition for a year: to do nothing\".<ref name=\"bazin cinema of cruelty\">{{cite book|last=Bazin|first=Andr\u00e9|title=The cinema of cruelty: from Bu\u00f1uel to Hitchcock|year=1982|publisher=Seaver Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0-86579-018-6|pages=89}}</ref>  While his family enjoyed themselves at the beach, Bu\u00f1uel spent much of his time in [[Antelope Valley]] with new acquaintances writer [[Aldous Huxley]] and sculptor [[Alexander Calder]], from whom he rented a house.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.130}}\n\nIn his autobiography, in a chapter about his second spell in America, Bu\u00f1uel states that \"[o]n several occasions, both American and European producers have suggested that I tackle a film version of [[Malcolm Lowry]]'s ''[[Under the Volcano]]''\",  but that after reading the book many times as well as eight different screenplays he was unable to come up with a solution for the cinema.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.194}} [[Under the Volcano (film)|The movie]] was eventually made in 1984 by [[John Huston]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Maslin |first1=Janet |title=Under the Volcano |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/06/13/movies/film-huston-s-under-the-volcano.html |website=New York Times |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Intermediate years (1946\u20131961)===\n\n====Mexico (1946\u20131953)====\n\nThe following year, an old friend, producer [[Denise Batcheff|Denise Tual]], the widow of [[Pierre Batcheff]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Pallister|first=Janis L.|title=French-Speaking Women Film Directors: A Guide|year=1997|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|location=Madison NJ|isbn=978-0-8386-3736-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/frenchspeakingwo0000pall/page/93 93]|url=https://archive.org/details/frenchspeakingwo0000pall/page/93}}</ref>  the [[leading man]] in ''Un Chien Andalou'', proposed that she and Bu\u00f1uel adapt Lorca's play ''[[The House of Bernarda Alba|La casa de Bernarda Alba]]'' for production in Paris.<ref name=camacho>{{cite book|last=Camacho|first=Enrique, Javier P\u00e9rez Bazo and Manuel Rodr\u00edguez Blanco|title=Bu\u00f1uel, 100 a\u00f1os : es peligroso asomarse al interior = Bu\u00f1uel, 100 years : it's dangerous to look inside|year=2001|publisher=Instituto Cervantes / The Museum of Modern Art|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8109-6219-4|pages=83}}</ref>  As it turned out, though, before they could both make their way to Europe, they encountered problems in securing the rights from Lorca's family.<ref name=bazin />{{rp|p.21}}  While in Mexico City, on a stopover, they had asked \u00d3scar Dancigers, a Russian \u00e9migr\u00e9 producer active in Mexico, for financing.<ref name=camacho />  Dancigers ran an independent production company that specialized in assisting U.S. film studios with on-location shooting in Mexico, but following World War&nbsp;II, he had lost his connection with Hollywood due to his being blacklisted as a Communist.<ref name=schreiber />{{rp|p.73}}  Although Dancigers wasn't enthusiastic about the Lorca project, he did want to work with Bu\u00f1uel and persuaded the Spanish director to make a film for him.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.197}}\n\n[[File:Libertad Lamarque.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Libertad Lamarque, star of Bu\u00f1uel's first Mexican film. Bu\u00f1uel was said to have held a long-time grudge against Lamarque because the actress was able to bring him to tears when he viewed a \"corny melodrama\" which she had made in Argentina: \"How could I let myself cry over such an absurd, grotesque, ridiculous scene?\"<ref name=\"bill krohn\">{{cite book|last1=Krohn|first1=Bill and Paul Duncan|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Cinema 1900\u20131983|date=2005|publisher=Taschen|location=Cologne|isbn=978-3822833759}}</ref>{{rp|p.147}}]]\nThe  [[Golden Age of Mexican cinema]] was peaking in the mid-to-late 1940s, at just the time Bu\u00f1uel was connecting with Dancigers.<ref name=fein>{{cite journal|last=Fein|first=Seth|title=Hollywood, U.S.-Mexican Relations, and the Devolution of the \"Golden Age\" of Mexican Cinema|journal=Film-Historia|year=1994|volume=IV|issue=2|pages=103\u2013135|url=http://161.116.18.149/bibliotecaDigital/cinema/filmhistoria/Art.Fein.pdf|accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref>  Movies represented Mexico's third largest industry by 1947, employing 32,000 workers, with 72 film producers who invested 66 million pesos (approximately U.S. $13 million) per year, four active studios with 40 million pesos of invested capital, and approximately 1,500 theaters throughout the nation, with about 200 in Mexico City alone.<ref name=huer>{{cite book|last=Huer|first=Federico|title=La industria cinematogr\u00e1fica mexicana|year=1964|publisher=Policrom\u00eda|location=M\u00e9xico. DF|pages=48\u201369}}</ref>  For their first project, the two men selected what seemed like a sure-fire success, ''[[Gran Casino]]'', a musical [[period piece]] set in [[Tampico]] during the boom years of oil exploitation, starring two of the most popular entertainers in Latin America: [[Libertad Lamarque]], an Argentine actress and singer, and [[Jorge Negrete]], a Mexican singer and leading man in [[Charro#Other uses|\"charro\" films]].<ref name=\"Mira Nouselles\">{{cite book|last=Mira Nouselles|first=Alberto|title=Historical Dictionary of Spanish Cinema|year=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0-8108-5957-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iZm8wWNXeioC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.64}} Bu\u00f1uel recalled:  \"I kept them singing all the time\u2014a competition, a championship\".<ref name=aranda />{{rp|pp.130\u2013131}}\n\nThe film was not successful at the box office, with some even calling it a fiasco.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Est\u00e8ve|first=Michel|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|journal=Etudes Cin\u00e9matographiques|year=1963|issue=20\u201321|pages=82}}</ref> Different reasons have been given for its failure with the public; for some, Bu\u00f1uel was forced to make concessions to the bad taste of his stars, particularly Negrete,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mart\u00ednez Herranz|first=Amparo|title=Gran Casino de Luis Bu\u00f1uel|journal=Artigrama|year=2002|issue=17|pages=525}}</ref> others cite Bu\u00f1uel's rusty technical skills<ref name=\"fuentes discourse\">{{cite journal|last=Fuentes|first=V\u00edctor|title=Bu\u00f1uel's Cinematic Narrative and the Latin American New Novel|journal=Discourse|date=Winter\u2013Spring 2004  |volume=26|issue=1 & 2|pages=92}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Garc\u00eda Riera|first=Emilio|title=Historia documental del cine mexicano. Vol. 3|year=1969|publisher=Era|location=Mexico|isbn=978-968-895-343-3|pages=90}}</ref>  and lack of confidence after so many years out of the director's chair,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Charity|first=Tom|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Two-Disc Collector's Edition|journal=Sight and Sound|date=December 2007|volume=17|issue=12|pages=105}}</ref> while still others speculate that Mexican audiences were tiring of genre movies, called \"churros\", that were perceived as being cheaply and hastily made.<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.48}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mraz|first=John|title=Mexican Cinema: Of churros and charros|journal=Jump Cut|date=February 1984|issue=29|pages=23|url=http://www.ejumpcut.org/archive/onlinessays/JC29folder/MexFilmBook.html}}</ref>\n\nThe failure of ''Gran Casino'' sidelined Bu\u00f1uel, and it was over two years before he had the chance to direct another picture.<ref>{{cite book|last=Paranagu\u00e1|first=Paulo Antonio|title=Mexican Cinema|year=1995|publisher=British Film Institute|location=London|isbn=978-0-85170-516-3|pages=202|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U7wuAAAAYAAJ&q=bunuel+gran+casino+failure&dq=bunuel+gran+casino+failure}}</ref>  According to Bu\u00f1uel, he spent this time \"scratching my nose, watching flies and living off my mother's money\",<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.199}} but he was actually somewhat more industrious than that may sound.  With the husband/wife team of Janet and [[Luis Alcoriza]], he wrote the scenario for ''Si usted no puede, yo s\u00ed'', which was filmed in 1950 by [[Juli\u00e1n Soler]].<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.203}} He also continued developing the idea for a surrealistic film called ''Ilegible, hijo de flauta'', with the poet [[Juan Larrea (poet)|Juan Larrea]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gurney|first=Robert|title=\"Juan Larrea and the Film Bu\u00f1uel Did Not Make\", in Companion to Spanish Surrealism, ed. Robert Havard|year=2004|publisher=Tamesis Books|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|isbn=978-1-85566-104-2|pages=49|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jYOIwLxBLfMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> Dancigers pointed out to him that there was currently a vogue for films about street urchins, so Bu\u00f1uel scoured the back streets and slums of Mexico City in search of material, interviewing social workers about street gang warfare and murdered children.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|pp.203\u2013204}}\n\nDuring this period, Dancigers was busy producing films for the actor/director [[Fernando Soler]], one of the most durable of Mexican film personalities, having been referred to as the \"national paterfamilias\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Stock|first=Ann Marie|title=Framing Latin American Cinema: Contemporary Critical Perspectives|year=1997|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-2972-5|pages=213|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2VFTpFmrV5cC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>   Although Soler typically preferred to direct his own films, for their latest collaboration, ''[[El Gran Calavera]]'', based on a play by Adolfo Torrado, he decided that doing both jobs would be too much trouble, so he asked Dancigers to find someone who could be trusted to handle the technical aspects of the directorial duties.<ref name=\"cine mexicano\">{{cite web|title=El gran calavera (1949)|url=http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/gran_calavera.html|website=M\u00e1s de Cien A\u00f1os de Cine Mexicano|publisher=Cine Club \u2013 Cine Mexicano|accessdate=16 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421140309/http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/gran_calavera.html|archive-date=21 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel welcomed the opportunity, stating that: \"I amused myself with the montage, the constructions, the angles... All of that interested me because I was still an apprentice in so-called 'normal' cinema.\"<ref name=\"cine mexicano\" />  As a result of his work on this film, he developed a technique for making films cheaply and quickly by limiting them to 125 shots.<ref name=schreiber />{{rp|p.73}} ''El Gran Calavera'' was completed in 16 days at a cost of 400,000 pesos (approximately $46,000 US at 1948 exchange rates).<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.52}}  The picture has been described as \"a hilarious screwball send-up of the Mexican [[nouveau riche]]... a wild roller coaster of mistaken identity, sham marriages and misfired suicides\",<ref name =\"Harvard.edu\" /> and it was a big hit at the box office in Mexico.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dent|first=David W.|title=Encyclopedia of Modern Mexico|year=2002|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0-8108-4291-5|pages=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HkiJlXXbAy4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  In 2013, the picture was re-made by Mexican director Gary Alazraki under the title ''[[The Noble Family]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=de las Carreras|first1=Mar\u00eda Elena|title=El gran calavera (The Great Madcap, 1949), directed by Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=https://www.laconservancy.org/sites/default/files/files/GranCalavera_EssayDeLasCarreras.pdf|publisher=The Los Angeles Conservancy|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>  In 1949, Bu\u00f1uel renounced his Spanish citizenship to become a naturalized Mexican.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pulver|first=Andrew|title=A short history of Spanish cinema|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2011/mar/29/short-history-spanish-cinema|work=newEurope|publisher=Guardian News and Media|accessdate=1 September 2012|location=London|date=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe commercial success of ''El Gran Calavera'' enabled Bu\u00f1uel to redeem a promise he had extracted from Dancigers, which was that if Bu\u00f1uel could deliver a money-maker, Dancigers would guarantee \"a degree of freedom\" on the next film project.<ref name=Doniol-Valcroze />  Knowing that Dancigers was uncomfortable with experimentalism, especially when it might affect the bottom line, Bu\u00f1uel proposed a commercial project titled ''\u00a1Mi huerfanito jefe!'', about a juvenile street vendor who can't sell his final lottery ticket, which ends up being the winner and making him rich.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los olvidados (1950)|url=http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/olvidados.html|website=Las 100 mejores pel\u00edculas del cine mexicano: 2|publisher=Cine Club \u2013 Cine Mexicano|accessdate=20 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717025021/http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/olvidados.html|archive-date=17 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Dancigers was open to the idea, but instead of a \"''[[feuilleton]]''\", he suggested making \"something rather more serious\".<ref name=\"ibanez and palacio\">{{cite book|last=Iba\u00f1ez|first=Juan Carlos and Manuel Palacio|title=\"Los Olvidados/The Young and the Damned\", in The Cinema of Latin America, ed. Alberto Elena and Marina D\u00edaz L\u00f3pez|year=2003|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-1-903364-84-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hx5VfnjrGLUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.60}}  During his recent researches through the slums of Mexico City, Bu\u00f1uel had read a newspaper account of a twelve-year-old boy's body being found on a garbage dump, and this became the inspiration, and final scene, for the film, called ''[[Los olvidados]]''.<ref name=\"de la colina\" />{{rp|pp.53\u201354}}\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"The world doesn't work like Hollywood told us it does, and Bu\u00f1uel knew well that poverty's truths could not be window-dressed in any way. This film continues to provoke reactions for its unapologetic portrayal of life without hope or trust. It stands out among Bu\u00f1uel's works as the moment when he broke surface and bellowed, before sinking back into the world of the privileged where his surreal view most loved to play.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pierre|first=DBC|title=The lost boys|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/feb/17/film|work=The Guardian, 16 February 2007|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|accessdate=20 August 2012|location=London|date=16 February 2007}}</ref>  |source=[[Booker Prize]] winning author [[DBC Pierre]] on ''Los olvidados''}}\nThe film tells the story of a street gang of children who terrorize their impoverished neighborhood, at one point brutalizing a blind man<ref>{{cite book|last=Villarreal|first=Rachel Kram|title=Gladiolas for the Children of Sanchez: Ernesto P. Uruchurtu's Mexico City, 1950\u20141968|year=2008|location=Ann Arbor MI|pages=31|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LlRhRyTNbqMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|isbn=9781109029550}}</ref> and at another assaulting a legless man who moves around on a dolly, which they toss down a hill.<ref name=\"ed gonzalez\">{{cite magazine|last=Gonzalez|first=Ed|title=Los Olvidados ****|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/los-olvidados/208|magazine=Slant Magazine|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref>  Film historian Carl J. Mora has said of ''Los olvidados'' that the director: \"visualized poverty in a radically different way from the traditional forms of Mexican melodrama.  Bu\u00f1uel's street children are not 'ennobled' by their desperate struggle for survival; they are in fact ruthless predators who are not better than their equally unromanticized victims\".<ref name=mora>{{cite book|last=Mora|first=Carl J.|title=Mexican Cinema: Reflections of a Society|year=1982|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles|isbn=978-0-520-04304-6|url=https://archive.org/details/mexicancinemaref00mora}}</ref>{{rp|p.91}}  The film was made quickly (18 days) and cheaply (450,000 pesos), with Bu\u00f1uel's fee being the equivalent of $2,000.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|pp.210\u2013211}}  During filming, a number of members of the crew resisted the production in a variety of ways:  one technician confronted Bu\u00f1uel and asked why he didn't make a \"real\" Mexican movie \"rather than a miserable picture like this one\",<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.200}} the film's hairdresser quit on the spot over a scene in which the protagonist's mother refuses to give him food (\"In Mexico, no mother would say that to her son.\"),<ref name=\"mraz nacho lopez\">{{cite book|last=Mraz|first=John|title=Nacho Lopez, Mexican Photographer|year=2003|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4047-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e4f6kkFbbJQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.99}} another staff member urged Bu\u00f1uel to abandon shooting on a \"garbage heap\", noting that there were many \"lovely residential neighborhoods like [[Lomas de Chapultepec|Las Lomas]]\" that were available,<ref name=\"mraz nacho lopez\" />{{rp|p.99}} while Pedro de Urdimalas, one of the scriptwriters, refused to allow his name in the credits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pedro de Urdimalas|url=http://www.sacm.org.mx/archivos/biografias.asp?txtSocio=08285&offset=0|publisher=Sociedad de Autores y Compositores de M\u00e9xico (SACM)|accessdate=21 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506103309/http://www.sacm.org.mx/archivos/biografias.asp?txtSocio=08285&offset=0|archivedate=6 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Paz0.jpg|thumb|left|133px|Octavio Paz, ardent champion of ''Los olvidados'' and close friend during Bu\u00f1uel's exile in Mexico<ref>{{cite book|last=Caistor|first=Nick|title=Octavio Paz|year=2007|publisher=Reaktion Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-86189-303-1|page=36|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OkPr_MWp2wMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>]]\nThis hostility was also felt by those who attended the movie's premi\u00e8re in Mexico City on 9 November 1950, when ''Los olvidados'' was taken by many as an insult to Mexican sensibilities and to the Mexican nation.<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.67}}  At one point, the audience shrieked in shock as one of the characters looked straight into the camera and hurled a rotten egg at it, leaving a gelatinous, opaque ooze on the lens for a few moments.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Faber|first=Sebastiaan|title=Bu\u00f1uel's Impure Modernism|journal=Modernist Cultures|year=2012|volume=7|issue=1|pages=56\u201376|doi=10.3366/mod.2012.0028}}</ref>  In his memoir, Bu\u00f1uel recalled that after the initial screening, painter [[Diego Rivera]]'s wife [[Frida Kahlo]] refused to speak to him, while poet [[Le\u00f3n Felipe]]'s wife had to be restrained physically from attacking him.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|pp.200\u2013201}}  There were even calls to have Bu\u00f1uel's Mexican citizenship revoked.<ref name=\"de la colina\" />{{rp|p.61}}  Dancigers, panicked by what he feared would be a complete debacle, quickly commissioned an alternate \"happy\" ending to the film,<ref name=unesco>{{cite web|title=Nomination Form, Memory of the World Register|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/fileadmin/MULTIMEDIA/HQ/CI/CI/pdf/mow/nomination_forms/los_olvidados.pdf|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> and also tacked on a preface showing stock footage of the skylines of New York, London and Paris with voice-over commentary to the effect that behind the wealth of all the great cities of the world can be found poverty and malnourished children, and that Mexico City \"that large modern city, is no exception\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=John|title=El Monstruo: Dread and Redemption in Mexico City|year=2009|publisher=Nation Books|location=New York|isbn=978-1-56858-424-9|pages=203|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=psHQERn0VMcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  Regardless, attendance was so poor that Dancigers withdrew the film after only three days in theaters.<ref name=\"berg los olvidados\">{{cite web|last=Berg|first=Charles Ram\u00edrez|title=Los Olvidados (1950)|url=http://www.austinfilm.org/page.aspx?pid=1692|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130414101344/http://www.austinfilm.org/page.aspx?pid=1692|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 April 2013|website=Essential Cinema|publisher=Austin Film Society|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>\n \nThrough the determined efforts of future Nobel Prize winner for Literature [[Octavio Paz]], who at the time was in Mexico's diplomatic service, ''Los olvidados'' was chosen to represent Mexico at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] of 1951, and Paz promoted the film assiduously by distributing a supportive manifesto<ref>{{cite news|last=Paz|first=Octavio|title=Cannes, 1951. Los olvidados|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1983/09/29/opinion/433638005_850215.html|accessdate=30 August 2012|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|date=29 September 1983}}</ref> and parading outside the cinema with a placard.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=Jason|title=Octavio Paz, a Study of His Poetics|year=1979|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-22306-5|pages=25|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6wk4AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  Opinion in general was enthusiastic, with the Surrealists (Breton and poet [[Jacques Prevert]]) and other artistic intellectuals (painter [[Marc Chagall]] and poet/dramatist/filmmaker [[Jean Cocteau]]) laudatory, but the communists objected to what they saw as the film's \"bourgeois morality\" for containing a scene in which the police stop a pederast from assaulting a child.<ref>{{cite web|last=Garmendia|first=Arturo|title=La batalla por \"Los Olvidados\" de Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://www.cineforever.com/2010/01/27/la-batalla-por-los-olvidados-de-bunuel/|publisher=Cineforever|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=27 January 2010}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel won the Best Director prize that year at Cannes, and also won the [[International Federation of Film Critics|FIPRESCI International Critics' Award]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Steffen|first=James|title=Los Olvidados|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/93547%7C0/Los-Olvidados.html|website=Turner Classic Movies Film Article|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks}}</ref>  After receiving these accolades, the film was reissued in Mexico where it ran for two months to much greater acceptance and profit.<ref>{{cite book|last=Faber|first=Sebastiaan|title=Exile and Cultural Hegemony: Spanish Intellectuals in Mexico, 1939\u20131975|year=2002|publisher=Vanderbilt University Press|location=Nashville|isbn=978-0-8265-1422-6|pages=xiv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WAY693mPUWsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  ''Los olvidados'' and its triumph at Cannes made Bu\u00f1uel an instant world celebrity and the most important Spanish-speaking film director in the world.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gazetas|first=Aristides|title=An Introduction to World Cinema|year=2008|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson NC|isbn=978-0-7864-3907-2|pages=198|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CPuZ-2UtVRwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  In 2003, ''Los olvidados'' was recommended by [[UNESCO]] for inclusion in the [[Memory of the World Programme#Memory of the World Register|Memory of the World Register]], calling it: \"the most important document in Spanish about the marginal lives of children in contemporary large cities\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Los olvidados|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/communication-and-information/flagship-project-activities/memory-of-the-world/register/full-list-of-registered-heritage/registered-heritage-page-5/los-olvidados/|website=Memory of the World|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"Here in Mexico, I have become a professional in the film world.  Until I came here I made a film the way a writer makes a book, and on my friends' money at that.  I am very grateful and happy to have lived in Mexico, and I have been able to make my films here in a way I could not have in any other country in the world.  It is quite true that in the beginning, caught up by necessity, I was forced to make cheap films. But I never made a film which went against my conscience or my convictions.  I have never made a superficial, uninteresting film.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=Interview with Wilfried Berghahn|journal=Filmkritik|date=1963|issue= 5}}</ref>  |source= \u2013 Luis Bu\u00f1uel on his mid-century career in Mexico. }}\nBu\u00f1uel remained in Mexico for the rest of his life, although he spent periods of time filming in France and Spain. In Mexico, he filmed 21 films during an 18-year period.  For many critics, although there were occasional widely acknowledged masterpieces like ''Los olvidados'' and [[\u00c9l (film)|''\u00c9l'']] (1953), the majority of his output consisted of generic fare which was adapted to the norms of the national film industry, frequently adopting melodramatic conventions that appealed to local tastes.<ref name=lim>{{cite news|last1=Lim|first1=Dennis|title=Mexican-era Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/08/entertainment/ca-secondlook8|accessdate=20 September 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=8 February 2009}}</ref>  Other commentators, however, have written of the deceptive complexity and intensity of many of these films, arguing that, collectively, they, \"bring a philosophical depth and power to his cinema, together offering a sustained meditation on ideas of religion, class inequity, violence and desire\".<ref name =\"Harvard.edu\" /> Although Bu\u00f1uel usually had little choice regarding the selection of these projects,<ref name=Delmas>{{cite journal|last1=Delmas|first1=Jean|title=Bu\u00f1uel, Citizen of Mexico|journal=Jeune Cinema|date=February 1966|issue= 12}}</ref> they often deal with themes that were central to his lifelong concerns:<ref name=adler>{{cite news|last1=Adler|first1=Renata|title=Screen: Bunuel's Relentless 'Nazarin':Film Set in the Mexico of Porfirio Diaz|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C02E1D7163AE134BC4951DFB0668383679EDE|accessdate=27 September 2014|work=New York Times|agency=The New York Times Company|date=21 June 1968}}</ref> \n* sexual pathology:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gutierrez-Albill|first1=Julian Daniel|title=Queering Bu\u00f1uel: Sexual Dissidence and Psychoanalysis in His Mexican and Spanish Cinema|date=2008|publisher=I.B.Tauris|location=London|isbn=9781845116682|pages=59\u201362|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E38AAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>  ''\u00c9l'' (1953), ''[[Ensayo de un crimen]]'' (1955), and ''[[Wuthering Heights (1954 film)|Abismos de pasi\u00f3n]]'' (1954)\n*the destructive effects of rampant [[machismo]]:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Evans|first1=Peter William|title=The Films of Luis Bu\u00f1uel. Subjectivity and Desire|date=1995|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0198159063|page=143}}</ref> ''[[El Bruto]]'', (1953), ''[[El r\u00edo y la muerte]]'', (1955); \n*the blurring of fantasy and reality:<ref>{{cite web|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel's Cinema of Entrapment in the Age of Cowardice: The Search for a Greater Truth|url=http://users.hal-pc.org/~questers/JAVA/fire/Bunuel.html|publisher=Gregory and Maria Pearse|accessdate=27 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402034318/http://users.hal-pc.org/~questers/JAVA/fire/Bunuel.html|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[Subida al cielo]]'' (1952), ''[[La ilusi\u00f3n viaja en tranv\u00eda]]'' (1954); \n*the disruptive status of women in a male-dominated culture:<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mu\u00f1oz|first1=Sara|title=La construcci\u00f3n femenina en el discurso cinematogr\u00e1fico de Bu\u00f1uel: la femme fatale|url=http://www.hispanetjournal.com/4Surrealfemme-EDITADO.pdf|website=Hispanet Journal 2|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> ''[[Susana (film)|Susana]]'' (1951), ''[[La hija del enga\u00f1o]]'' (1951\u2014a remake of the Film\u00f3fono production ''Don Quint\u00edn el amargao'' of 16 years earlier),<ref>{{cite web|title=La hija del enga\u00f1o (1951)|url=http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/hija_enganio.html|website=M\u00e1s de Cien A\u00f1os de Cine Mexicano|publisher=Maximiliano Maza|accessdate=1 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012084702/http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/hija_enganio.html|archive-date=12 October 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[Una mujer sin amor]]'' (1952); and\n*the absurdity of the religious life:<ref name=edwards />{{rp|pp.118\u201319}} ''[[Nazar\u00edn]]'' (1959) and ''Sim\u00f3n del desierto'' (1965).\n\nAs busy as he was during the 1950s and early 1960s, there were still many film projects that Bu\u00f1uel had to abandon due to lack of financing or studio support, including a cherished plan to film Mexican novelist [[Juan Rulfo]]'s ''[[Pedro P\u00e1ramo]]'', of which he said how much he enjoyed \"the crossing from the mysterious to the real, almost without transition.  I really like this mixture of reality and fantasy,  but I don't know how to bring it to the screen.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Poniatowska|first=Elena|title=Palabras cruzadas|year=1961|publisher=Ediciones Era|location=Mexico City|pages=191}}</ref>  Other unrealized projects during his lifetime included adaptations of [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]]'s ''Les caves du Vatican''; [[Benito P\u00e9rez Gald\u00f3s]]'s ''[[Fortunata y Jacinta]]'', ''[[Do\u00f1a Perfecta]]'', and ''\u00c1ngel Guerra''; [[Evelyn Waugh]]'s ''[[The Loved One]]''; [[William Golding]]'s ''[[Lord of the Flies]]''; [[Dalton Trumbo]]'s ''[[Johnny Got His Gun]]''; [[J. K. Huysmans]]' ''[[L\u00e0-bas (novel)|L\u00e0-Bas]]''; [[Matthew Lewis (writer)|Matthew Lewis]]'s ''[[The Monk]]''; [[Jos\u00e9 Donoso]]'s ''[[Hell Has No Limits|Lugar sin l\u00edmites]]''; a film of four stories based on [[Carlos Fuentes]]'s ''[[Aura (Fuentes)|Aura]]''; and [[Julio Cort\u00e1zar]]'s ''[[Final del juego|Las m\u00e9nades]]''.<ref name=\"fuentes discourse\" />{{rp|p.96}}\n\n====Mexico and beyond: return to international filmmaking (1954\u20131960)====\n[[File:S.Kragujevic, G\u00e9rard Philipe 1955.JPG|thumb|175px|[[G\u00e9rard Philipe]], popular French star of Bu\u00f1uel's ''[[La Fi\u00e8vre Monte \u00e0 El Pao]]''. At one point during the filming, Bu\u00f1uel asked Philipe, who was visibly dying of cancer, why the actor was making this film, and Philipe responded by asking the director the same question, to which both said they didn't know.<ref name=hagopian>{{cite web|last1=Hagopian|first1=Kevin|title=Fever Mounts in El Pao|url=http://www.albany.edu/writers-inst/webpages4/filmnotes/fnf02n11.html|website=New York State Writers Institute|publisher=Writers Institute|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>]]\nAs much as he welcomed steady employment in the Mexican film industry, Bu\u00f1uel was quick to seize opportunities to re-emerge onto the international film scene and to engage with themes that were not necessarily focused on Mexican preoccupations.<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.144}}  His first chance came in 1954, when Dancigers partnered with Henry F. Ehrlich, of [[United Artists]], to co-produce a film version of [[Daniel Defoe]]'s ''[[Robinson Crusoe]]'', using a script developed by the Canadian writer [[Hugo Butler]].  The film was produced by George Pepper, the former executive secretary of the Hollywood Democratic Committee.  Both Butler and Pepper were emigres from Hollywood who had run afoul of authorities seeking out communists.<ref name=schreiber />{{rp|p.75}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsdefrance.com/review/the-young-one-1960.html|title=Review of the film The Young One (1960)|first=James|last=Travers|date=27 October 2017|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref>  The result, ''[[Adventures of Robinson Crusoe]]'', was Bu\u00f1uel's first color film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=The Adventures of Robinson Crusoe|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-adventures-of-robinson-crusoe|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel was given much more time than usual for the filming (three months), which was accomplished on location in Manzanillo, a Pacific seaport with a lush jungle interior, and was shot simultaneously in English and Spanish.<ref name=\"axmaker robinson crusoe\">{{cite web|last1=Axmaker|first1=Sean|title=Adventures of Robinson Crusoe (1954)|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/66823/Adventures-of-Robinson-Crusoe/articles.html|website=Turner Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>  When the film was released in the United States, its young star [[Dan O'Herlihy]] used his own money to fund a Los Angeles run for the film and gave free admission to all members of the [[Screen Actors Guild]], who in turn rewarded the little-known actor with his only [[Oscar award|Oscar]] nomination.<ref name=\"axmaker robinson crusoe\" />\n\nIn the mid-1950s, Bu\u00f1uel got the chance to work again in France on international co-productions.  The result was what critic [[Raymond Durgnat]] has called the director's \"revolutionary triptych\", in that each of the three films is \"openly, or by implication, a study in the morality and tactics of armed revolution against a right-wing dictatorship\".<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.100}}  The first, ''[[Cela s'appelle l'aurore]]'' (Franco-Italian, 1956) required Bu\u00f1uel and the [['Pataphysics|\"pataphysical\"]] writer [[Jean Ferry]] to adapt a novel by [[Emmanuel Robl\u00e8s]] after the celebrated writer [[Jean Genet]] failed to deliver a script after having been paid in full.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.100}}  The second film was [[Death in the Garden|''La Mort en ce jardin'']] (Franco-Mexican, 1956), which was adapted by Bu\u00f1uel and his frequent collaborator [[Luis Alcoriza]] from a novel by the Belgian writer [[Jos\u00e9-Andr\u00e9 Lacour]].  The final part of the \"triptych\" was ''[[La Fi\u00e8vre Monte \u00e0 El Pao]]'' (Franco-Mexican, 1959), the last film of the popular French star [[G\u00e9rard Philipe]], who died in the final stages of the production.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Canby|first1=Vincent|title=Film: From Bunuel, 'Los Ambiciosos,' at the Public|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/12/movies/film-from-bunuel-los-ambiciosos-at-the-public.html|accessdate=30 September 2014|agency=New York Times|date=12 February 1988}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel was later to explain that he was so strapped for cash that he, \"took everything that was offered to me, as long as it wasn't humiliating\".<ref name=hagopian />\n\nIn 1960, Bu\u00f1uel re-teamed with scenarist Hugo Butler and organizer George Pepper, allegedly his favorite producer,  to make his second English-language film, a US/Mexico co-production called ''[[The Young One]]'', based on a short story by writer and former CIA-agent [[Peter Matthiessen]].<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=hZuzxKQfhYUC&pg=PA191&lpg=PA191&dq=george+pepper+Bu\u00f1uel#v=onepage&q=pepper | title=My Last Sigh: The Autobiography of Luis Bunuel| isbn=9780345803719| last1=Bunuel| first1=Luis| date=2013-03-26}}</ref>  This film has been called \"a surprisingly uncompromising study of racism and sexual desire, set on a remote island in the Deep South\"<ref name =\"Harvard.edu\" /> and has been described by critic Ed Gonzalez as, \"salacious enough to make [[Elia Kazan]]'s [[Baby Doll]] and [[Louis Malle|Luis Malle's]] [[Pretty Baby (1978 film)|''Pretty Baby'']] blush\".<ref name=\"The Young One 4 out of 4\">{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=The Young One 4 out of 4|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-young-one|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>  Although the film won a special award at the Cannes Film Festival for its treatment of racial discrimination,<ref name=bentley />{{rp|p.151}} the US critics were so hostile upon its release that Bu\u00f1uel was later to say that, \"a Harlem newspaper even wrote that I should be hung upside down from a lamppost on Fifth Avenue....I made this film with love, but it never had a chance.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rosenbaum|first1=Jonathan|title=The Young One: Bu\u00f1uel's Neglected Masterpiece|url=http://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/2009/07/22909/|website=jonathanrosenbaum.net|accessdate=30 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006084401/http://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/2009/07/22909/|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In the words of film historian Peter Harcourt: \"if ''The Young One'' must still be considered a 'bad' film by conventional standards, then it is one of the most subtle, most challenging and most distinguished bad films ever made.\"<ref name=\"peter harcourt\">{{cite journal|last1=Harcourt|first1=Peter|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Spaniard and Surrealist|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1967|volume=20|issue=3|page=12|url=http://www.austinlibrary.com:2138/stable/pdfplus/1210106.pdf?acceptTC=true&jpdConfirm=true|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Late international period (1961\u20131977)===\nAt the 1960 Cannes Festival, Bu\u00f1uel was approached by the young director [[Carlos Saura]], whose film [[The Delinquents (1960 film)|''Los Golfos'']] had been entered officially to represent Spain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los Golfos|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/3299/year/1960.html|publisher=Festival de Cannes|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>  Two years earlier, Saura had partnered with [[Juan Antonio Bardem]] and [[Luis Garc\u00eda Berlanga]] to form a production company called UNINCI,<ref name=\"andrew whittaker\">{{cite book|last1=Whittaker|first1=Andrew|title=Speak the Culture: Spain: Be Fluent in Spanish Life and Culture|date=2008|publisher=Thorogood Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1854186058|page=225|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2rZS8SWMroUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref> and the group was keen to get Bu\u00f1uel to make a new film in his native country as part of their overall goal of creating a uniquely Spanish brand of cinema.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.190\u201391}} At the same time, Mexican actress [[Silvia Pinal]] was eager to work with Bu\u00f1uel and talked her producer-husband [[Gustavo Alatriste]] into providing additional funding for the project with the understanding that the director, who Pinal described as \"a man worshiped and idolized\", would be given \"absolute freedom\" in carrying out the work.<ref name=\"agustin de gracia\">{{cite news|last1=de Gracia|first1=Agust\u00edn|title=Recuerdan a Luis Bu\u00f1uel a 30 a\u00f1os de su fallecimiento|url=http://www.laopinion.com/entretenimientocine/article/20130731/Recuerdan-a-Luis-Bunuel-a-30-anos-de-su-fallecimiento&template=print|accessdate=4 October 2014|work=laopinion.com|date=31 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006094142/http://www.laopinion.com/entretenimientocine/article/20130731/Recuerdan-a-Luis-Bunuel-a-30-anos-de-su-fallecimiento%26template%3Dprint|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Finally, Bu\u00f1uel agreed to work again in Spain when further support was provided by producer [[Pere Portabella]]'s company ''Film 59''.<ref name=\"pere portabella\">{{cite web|title=Pere Portabella|url=http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/films/556|website=Film Exhibitions|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nBu\u00f1uel and his co-scenarist [[Julio Alejandro]] drafted a preliminary screenplay for ''[[Viridiana]]'', which critic [[Andrew Sarris]] has described as incorporating \"a plot which is almost too lurid to synopsize even in these enlightened times\",<ref name=\"sarris viridiana\">{{cite web|last1=Sarris|first1=Andrew|title=The Devil and the Nun|url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/film/movie/contents/the_devil_and_the_nun_sarris.pdf|website=warwick.ac.uk|publisher=University of Warwick|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> dealing with rape, incest, hints of necrophilia, animal cruelty and sacrilege, and dutifully submitted it to the Spanish censor, who, to the surprise of nearly everyone, approved it after requesting only minor modifications and one significant change to the ending.<ref name=\"d'lugo films of carlos saura\">{{cite book|last1=D'Lugo|first1=Marvin|title=The Films of Carlos Saura: The Practice of Seeing|date=1991|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton, NJ|isbn=978-0-691-03142-2|pages=42\u201343|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RUAks4YGLWAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Although Bu\u00f1uel accommodated the censor's demands, he came up with a final scene that was even more provocative than the scene it replaced: \"even more immoral\", as Bu\u00f1uel was later to observe.<ref name=\"ebert viridiana\">{{cite web|last1=Ebert|first1=Roger|title=Viridiana|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-viridiana-1961|website=The Great Movies|publisher=RogerEbert.com|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Since Bu\u00f1uel had more than adequate resources, top-flight technical and artistic crews, and experienced actors, filming of ''Viridiana'' (which took place on location and at Bardem's studios in Madrid) went smoothly and quickly.<ref name=Pavlovi>{{cite book|last=Pavlovi\u0107|first=Tatjana|title=100 Years of Spanish Cinema|year=2009|publisher=Wiley|location=New York|isbn=978-1-4051-8419-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PtFXpxyWMi4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|display-authors=etal}}</ref>{{rp|p. 98}}\n\nBu\u00f1uel submitted a cutting copy to the censors and then arranged for his son, Juan Luis, to smuggle the negatives to Paris for the final editing and mixing,<ref>{{cite web|title=Viridiana.50|url=http://www.viridiana50.com/uninci.php|website=viridiana50.com|publisher=Ministerio de Cultura de Espa\u00f1a|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> ensuring that the authorities would not have an opportunity to view the finished product before its planned submission as Spain's official entry to the 1961 Cannes Festival.<ref name=buache>{{cite book|last1=Buache|first1=Freddy|title=The Cinema of Luis Bu\u00f1uel|date=1973|publisher=Tantivy Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-498-01302-7|pages=117\u201320}}</ref> Spain's director general of cinematography Jos\u00e9 Munoz-Fontan presented the film on the last day of the festival and then, on the urging of Portabella and Bardem, appeared in person to accept the top prize, the [[Palme d'Or]], which the film shared with the French entry ''[[Une aussi longue absence]]'', directed by [[Henri Colpi]].<ref name=\"buache french edition\">{{cite book|last1=Buache|first1=Freddy|title=Bu\u00f1uel|date=1975|publisher=L'Age d'Homme| location=Lausanne| isbn=9782825133415| page=119| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tuo1JTpoxQAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Within days, ''[[l'Osservatore Romano]]'', the Vatican's official organ, denounced the film as an insult not only to Catholicism but to Christianity in general.<ref name=malcolm>{{cite news|last1=Malcolm|first1=Derek|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Viridiana|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/1999/apr/01/derekmalcolmscenturyoffilm.derekmalcolm|accessdate=5 October 2014|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=1 April 1999}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=Luis Bunuel's Case Study on Bourgeoisie Plight and its Underlining Causes|url=http://www.apotpourriofvestiges.com/2012/02/viridiana-1961-luis-bunuels-case-study.html|website=apotpourriofvestiges.com|publisher=A Potpourri of Vestiges|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>  Consequences to nearly all concerned were swift: Munoz-Fontan was cashiered from his government post,<ref name=\"buache french edition\" /> the film was banned in Spain for the next 17 years, all mention of it in the press was prohibited, and the two Spanish production companies UNINCI and ''Film 59'' were disbanded.<ref name=\"d'lugo films of carlos saura\" />\n\n[[File:Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re \u00e0 la BNF.jpg|thumb|right|270px|\"When today I amuse myself by making useless calculations, I realize that Bu\u00f1uel and I shared more than two thousand meals together and that on more than fifteen hundred occasions he knocked on my door, notes in hand, ready to begin work. I'm not even counting the walks, the drinks, the films we watched together, the film festivals.\"<ref name=\"carriere flickhead\">{{cite web|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel Remembered by Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re|url=http://home.comcast.net/~flickhead/Luis-Bunuel.html|website=Flickhead|publisher=Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> \u2013 Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re on his long-term collaboration with Bu\u00f1uel.]]\nBu\u00f1uel went on to make two more films in Mexico with Pinal and Alatriste, ''[[El \u00e1ngel exterminador]]'' (1962) and ''[[Sim\u00f3n del desierto]]'' (1965)\u2014 along with ''Viridiana'', they form the so-called \"Bu\u00f1uelian trilogy\" \u2014 and was later to say that Alatriste had been the one producer who gave him the most freedom in creative expression.<ref name=\"Rowman & Littlefield\">{{cite book|last1=Alfaro|first1=Eduardo de la Vega|title=\"The Decline of the Golden Age and the Making of the Crisis,\" in Mexico's Cinema: A Century of Film and Filmmakers, edited by Joanne Hershfield and David R. Maciel|date=1999|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0842026826|page=[https://archive.org/details/mexicoscinema00davi/page/189 189]|url=https://archive.org/details/mexicoscinema00davi/page/189}}</ref>\n\nIn 1963, actor [[Fernando Rey]], one of the stars of ''Viridiana'', introduced Bu\u00f1uel to producer [[Serge Silberman]], a Polish entrepreneur who had fled to Paris when his family died in the Holocaust<ref>{{cite news|title=Serge Silberman, productor de Luis Bu\u00f1uel y de Akira Kurosawa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2003/07/25/agenda/1059084008_850215.html|accessdate=13 October 2014|work=El Pais|agency=http://elpais.com/|date=25 July 2003}}</ref> and had worked with several renowned French directors, including [[Jean-Pierre Melville]], [[Jacques Becker]], [[Marcel Camus]] and [[Christian-Jaque]].<ref name=\"ronald bergan\">{{cite news|last1=Bergan|first1=Ronald|title=Serge Silberman: Flamboyant film producer prepared to go out on a limb|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2003/jul/28/guardianobituaries.filmnews|accessdate=13 October 2014|work=The Guardian|agency=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=27 July 2003}}</ref> Silberman proposed that the two make an adaptation of [[Octave Mirbeau]]'s [[The Diary of a Chambermaid (novel)|''Journal d'une femme de chambre'']], which Bu\u00f1uel had read several times.<ref name=\"gonzalez chambermaid\">{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=The Diary of a Chambermaid|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-diary-of-a-chambermaid|website=Slant Magazine.|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel wanted to do the filming in Mexico with Pinal, but Silberman insisted it be done in France.<ref name=\"gonzalez chambermaid\" />\n\nPinal was so determined to work again with Bu\u00f1uel that she was ready to move to France, learn the language and even work for nothing in order to get the part of [[C\u00e9lestine (Mirbeau)|C\u00e9lestine]], the title character.<ref name=\"rivera pinal\">{{cite journal|last1=Rivera J.|first1=H\u00e9ctor|title=Las experiencias de Silvia Pinal con Bu\u00f1uel y Gustavo Alatriste|journal=Proceso|date=13 July 1997|issue=n1080|page=62}}</ref> Silberman, however, wanted French actress [[Jeanne Moreau]] to play the role, so he put Pinal off by telling her that Moreau, too, was willing to act with no fee. Ultimately, Silberman got his way, leaving Pinal so disappointed that she was later to claim that Alatriste's failure to help her secure this part led to the breakup of their marriage.<ref name=\"rivera pinal\" /> When Bu\u00f1uel requested a French-speaking writer with whom to collaborate on the screenplay, Silberman suggested the 32-year-old [[Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re]], an actor whose previous screenwriting credits included only a few films for the comic star/director [[Pierre \u00c9taix]], but once Bu\u00f1uel learned that Carri\u00e8re was the scion of a wine-growing family, the newcomer was hired on the spot.<ref name=\"ronald bergan\" /> At first, Carri\u00e8re found it difficult to work with Bu\u00f1uel, because the young man was so deferential to the famous director that he never challenged any of Bu\u00f1uel's ideas, until, at Bu\u00f1uel's covert insistence, Silberman told Carri\u00e8re to stand up to Bu\u00f1uel now and then; as Carri\u00e8re was later to say: \"In a way, Bu\u00f1uel needed an opponent. He didn't need a secretary \u2013 he needed someone to contradict him and oppose him and to make suggestions.\"<ref name=\"tim grierson FilmCraft: Screenwriting\">{{cite book|last1=Grierson|first1=Tim|title=FilmCraft: Screenwriting|date=2013|publisher=Focal Press|location=Burlington MA|isbn=978-0240824864|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PHtiAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> The finished 1964 film, [[Diary of a Chambermaid (1964 film)|''Diary of a Chambermaid'']], became the first of several to be made by the team of Bu\u00f1uel, Carri\u00e8re and Silberman.  Carri\u00e8re was later to say: \"Without me and without Serge Silberman, the producer, perhaps Bu\u00f1uel would not have made so many films after he was 65. We really encouraged him to work. That's for sure.\"<ref name=Colville-Andersen>{{cite web|last1=Colville-Andersen|first1=Mikael|title=The Storytellers \u2013 Interview with Jean-Claude Carri\u00e9r\u00e9|url=http://zakka.dk/euroscreenwriters/screenwriters/jean-claude_carriere.htm|website=Zakkatography|publisher=Colville-Andersen.|accessdate=15 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331223043/http://zakka.dk/euroscreenwriters/screenwriters/jean-claude_carriere.htm|archive-date=31 March 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \nThis was the second attempt to film Mirbeau's novel, the first being [[The Diary of a Chambermaid (1946 film)|a 1946 Hollywood production]] directed by [[Jean Renoir]], which Bu\u00f1uel refused to view for fear of being influenced by the famous French director, whom he venerated.<ref name=\"david kalat\">{{cite web|last1=Kalat|first1=David|title=Diary of a Chambermaid|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/474221%7C474228/Diary-of-a-Chambermaid.html|website=Turner Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel's version, while admired by many, has often been compared unfavorably to Renoir's, with a number of critics claiming that Renoir's ''Diary'' fits better in Renoir's overall ''oeuvre'', while Bu\u00f1uel's ''Diary'' is not sufficiently \"Bu\u00f1uelian\".<ref name=\"Geoffrey T. Harris\">{{cite book|last1=Harris|first1=Geoffrey T.|title=On Translating French Literature and Film, Volume 1|date=1996|publisher=Rodopi|location=Amsterdam|isbn=978-90-5183-933-3|page=92|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wUbGJ8kozAoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 1964 release of ''Diary'', Bu\u00f1uel again tried to make a film of Matthew Lewis' ''[[The Monk]]'', a project on which he had worked, on and off, since 1938, according to producer [[Pierre Braunberger]].<ref name=gubern />{{rp|p.137}} He and Carri\u00e8re wrote a screenplay, but were unable to obtain funding for the project, which would be finally realized in 1973 under the direction of Bu\u00f1uel devotee [[Adonis A. Kyrou|Ado Kyrou]], with considerable assistance from both Bu\u00f1uel and Carri\u00e8re.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Aspley|first1=Keith|title=Historical Dictionary of Surrealism|date=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0810858473|page=284|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3KK7JHqNrRsC&pg=PA284&dq=bunuel+the+monk+lewis+carriere#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20the%20monk%20lewis%20carriere|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965, Bu\u00f1uel manage to work again with Sylvia Pinal in what would turn out to be his last Mexican feature, co-starring Claudio Brook, ''[[Sim\u00f3n del desierto]]''.<ref name=\"Rowman & Littlefield\"/> Pinal was keenly interested in continuing to work with Bu\u00f1uel, trusting him completely and frequently stating that he brought out the best in her; however, this would be their last collaboration.<ref name=\"La Jornada\">{{cite news|title=No he conocido a alguien que supere a Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Silvia Pinal|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2013/07/29/espectaculos/a12n1esp|accessdate=13 October 2014|work=La Jornada|agency=DEMOS, Desarrollo de Medios|date=29 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Catherine Deneuve 1969-2.jpg|thumb|195px|left|Catherine Deneuve starred in ''[[Belle de Jour (film)|Belle de Jour]]'' (1967), based on Joseph Kessel's novel, playing the role of a bored upper class Parisian housewife who spends her weekdays in a brothel.  She was re-united with Bu\u00f1uel again, starring in ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'' (1970), shot in [[Toledo, Spain]].  Deneuve is pictured here in 1968]]\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"Well, I think it was difficult for him, coping with his deafness. Some people said he was not that deaf, but I think, when you don't hear very well and when you're tired, everything sinks into a buzz, and it is very hard. French is not his language, so on ''Belle de Jour'', I'm sure that it was much more of an effort for him to have to explain. \".<ref name=zohn /> |source=Actress [[Catherine Deneuve]], star of ''Belle de Jour''}}\n\nIn 1966, Bu\u00f1uel was approached by [[Robert and Raymond Hakim|the Hakim brothers, Robert and Raymond]], Egyptian-French producers who specialized in sexy films directed by star filmmakers,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bernard|first1=Jami|title=The X-List: The National Society of Film Critics' Guide to the Movies that Turn Us On|date=2005|publisher=Da Capo Press|location=Cambridge MA|isbn=978-0306814457|page=40|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pWH97tY1KfMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> who offered him the opportunity to direct a film version of [[Joseph Kessel]]'s novel [[Belle de Jour (novel)|''Belle de Jour'']], a book about an affluent young woman who leads a double life as a prostitute, and that had caused a scandal upon its first publication in 1928.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boucharenc|first1=Myriam|title=L'\u00e9crivain-reporter au c\u0153ur des ann\u00e9es trente|date=2004|publisher=Presses Univ. Septentrion|location=Lille|isbn=978-2-85939-842-2|page=184|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2GShcPJaDg4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel did not like Kessel's novel, considering it \"a bit of a soap opera\",<ref name=\"Europe of Cultures\">{{cite web|last1=Durieux|first1=Christian|title=Conversation with Luis Bu\u00f1uel on Belle de jour|url=http://fresques.ina.fr/europe-des-cultures-en/fiche-media/Europe00048/conversation-with-luis-bunuel-on-belle-de-jour.html|website=Europe of Cultures|publisher=INA Institute|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> but he took on the challenge because: \"I found it interesting to try to turn something I didn't like into something I did.\"<ref name=\"levy belle de jour\">{{cite web|last1=Levy|first1=Emanuel|title=Belle de Jour (1967): Bunuel's Masterpiece Starring Catherine Deneuve|url=http://emanuellevy.com/pick-of-the-week/belle-de-jour-1967-bunuels-masterpiece-starring-catherine-deneuve/|website=Cinema 24/7|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> So he and Carri\u00e8re set out enthusiastically to interview women in the brothels of Madrid to learn about their sexual fantasies.<ref name=\"belle de jour tcm\">{{cite web|last=Landazuri|first=Margarita|title=Belle de jour|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article.html?id=628630%7C636738|website=TCM Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel also was not happy about the choice of the 22-year-old [[Catherine Deneuve]] for the title role, feeling that she had been foisted upon him by the Hakim brothers and Deneuve's lover at the time, director [[Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut]].<ref name=\"moma belle de jour\">{{cite web|last1=Silver|first1=Charles|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel's Belle de Jour|url=http://www.moma.org/explore/inside_out/2014/04/22/luis-bunuels-belle-de-jour/|website=Inside/Out|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> As a result, both actress and director found working together difficult, with Deneuve claiming, \"I felt they showed more of me than they'd said they were going to. There were moments when I felt totally used. I was very unhappy,\"<ref name=\"anderson belle\">{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Melissa|title=Belle de jour: Tough Love|url=https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/2121-belle-de-jour-tough-love|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> and Bu\u00f1uel deriding her prudery on the set and complaining that the hairdresser had to bind her breasts in order to assure her that they would not show on screen.<ref name=zohn>{{cite web|last1=Zohn|first1=Patricia|title=Belle de Jour: Catherine Deneuve and Her Shades of Grey |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/patricia-zohn/catherine-deneuve_b_1395172.html|website=HuffPost Arts and Culture| publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=29 October 2014|date=2 April 2012}}</ref> The resulting film has been described by film critic [[Roger Ebert]] as \"possibly the best-known erotic film of modern times, perhaps the best\",<ref>{{cite web| last1=Ebert| first1=Roger| title=Belle de Jour|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-belle-de-jour-1967|website=Great Movies|publisher=Roger Ebert.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> even though, as another critic has written, \"in terms of explicit sexual activity, there is little in ''Belle de jour'' we might not see in a [[Doris Day]] comedy from the same year\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Melville|first1=David|title=Who Let the Cats Out? Bu\u00f1uel, Deneuve and Belle de jour|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2013/cteq/who-let-the-cats-out-bunuel-deneuve-and-belle-de-jour/|website=Senses of Cinema|publisher=Film Victoria|accessdate=29 October 2014|date=9 September 2013}}</ref> It was Bu\u00f1uel's most successful film at the box office.<ref name=\"anderson belle\" />\n\nCritics have noted Bu\u00f1uel's habit of following up a commercial or critical success with a more personal, idiosyncratic film that might have less chance of popular esteem.<ref name=\"Polizzotti milky way\">{{cite web|last1=Polizzotti|first1=Mark| title=The Milky Way: Easy Striders|url=https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/611-the-milky-way-easy-striders|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter the worldwide success of his 1967 ''Belle de jour'', and upon viewing [[Jean-Luc Godard]]'s film ''La Chinoise'', Bu\u00f1uel, who had wanted to make a film about Catholic heresies for years, told Carri\u00e8re: \"If that is what today's cinema is like, then we can make a film about heresies.\"<ref name=\"supernal dreams\">{{cite web| last1=French| first1=Lawrence| title=Supernal Dreams: Jean-Claude Carriere on Luis Bunuel's Sublime Fantasy, \"The Milky Way\" | url=http://cinefantastiqueonline.com/2009/02/supernal-dreams-jean-claude-carriere-on-luis-bunuels-sublime-fantasy-the-milky-way/|website=Cinefantastique Online|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> The two spent months researching Catholic history and created the 1969 film [[The Milky Way (1969 film)|''The Milky Way'']], a \"picaresque road film\"<ref name=Nochimson>{{cite book|last1=Nochimson|first1=Martha|title=World on Film: An Introduction| date=2010| publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=New York|isbn=978-1405139793|page=294|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DXK5gkQwAs8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> that tells the story of two vagabonds on [[Camino de Santiago|pilgrimage to the tomb of the Apostle James]] at [[Santiago de Compostela]], during which they travel through time and space to take part in situations illustrating heresies that arose from the six major Catholic dogmas.<ref name=mazur>{{cite book|last1=Mazur|first1=Eric Michael|title=Encyclopedia of Religion and Film|date=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-0313330728|page=101|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JPNfox6H5qwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]], reviewing the film in the ''New York Times'', compared it to [[George Stevens]]' blockbuster ''[[The Greatest Story Ever Told]]'', in that Bu\u00f1uel had made a film about Jesus casting nearly all the famous French performers of the time in cameo roles.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Canby| first1=Vincent|title='The Milky Way':Bunuel Weaves Surreal Spiritual Journey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=990CE5D8123AE03BBC4F51DFB766838B669EDE|accessdate=11 December 2014|work=New York Times|date=27 January 1970}}</ref> ''The Milky Way'' was banned in Italy, only to have the Catholic Church intervene on its behalf.<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.152}}\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=A few great directors have the ability to draw us into their dream world, into their personalities and obsessions and fascinate us with them for a short time. This is the highest level of escapism the movies can provide for us \u2013 just as our elementary identification with a hero or a heroine was the lowest.<ref name=zohn /> |source=Film critic [[Roger Ebert]], on ''Tristana''<ref name=\"ebert tristana\">{{cite web|last1=Ebert|first1=Roger|title=Tristana|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/tristana-1970|website=Roger Ebert.com| publisher=Ebert Digital LLC|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nThe 1970 film ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'' is a film about a young woman who is seduced and manipulated by her guardian, who attempts to thwart her romance with a young artist and who eventually induces her to marry him after she loses one of her legs due to a tumor. It has been considered by scholar Beth Miller the least understood of Bu\u00f1uel's films, and consequently one of the most underrated, due to a \"consistent failure to apprehend its political and, especially, its socialist-feminist statement\".<ref name=\"beth miller\">{{cite book|last1=Miller|first1=Beth|title=\"From Mistress to Murderess,\" in Women in Hispanic Literature: Icons and Fallen Idols, edited by Beth Kurti Miller|date=1983|publisher=University of California Press| isbn=978-0520043671| pages=340\u201341|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8cCIcUaEznYC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel had wanted to make a film of [[Benito P\u00e9rez Gald\u00f3s]]' novel ''[[Tristana (novel)|Tristana]]'' as early as 1952, even though he considered Gald\u00f3s' book the author's weakest, in Bu\u00f1uel's words: \"of the 'I love you, my little pigeon' genre, very kitsch\".<ref name=fujiwara>{{cite web|last1=Fujiwara|first1=Chris|title=Tristana|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article.html?isPreview=&id=628630%7C449958&name=Tristana|website=TCM Summer Under the Stars|publisher=Turner Entertainment Network|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> After finishing ''Viridiana'' and in the wake of the scandal its release caused in 1962, the Spanish censor flatly turned down this project,<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.152}} and Bu\u00f1uel had to wait for 8 years before he could receive backing from the Spanish production company Epoca Films.<ref name=fujiwara /> The censors had threatened to deny permission for the film on the grounds that it encouraged duelling, so Bu\u00f1uel had to approach the subject matter very gingerly, in addition to making concessions to his French/Italian/Spanish producers, who insisted on casting two of the three primary roles with actors not of Bu\u00f1uel's choosing: [[Franco Nero]] and Catherine Deneuve.<ref name=\"faulkner literary adaptations\" />{{rp|p.128}} On this occasion, however, Deneuve and Bu\u00f1uel had a more mutually satisfactory working relationship, with Deneuve telling an interviewer, \"but in the end, you know, it was actually rather a wonderful shoot. ''Tristana'' is one of my favorite films. Personally, as an actress, I prefer ''Tristana'' to ''Belle de Jour''.\"<ref name=fujiwara />\n\nThe germ of the idea for their next film together, ''[[The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie]]'' (1972) came from Bu\u00f1uel and Serge Silberman discussing uncanny repetition in everyday life; Silberman told an anecdote about how he had invited some friends for dinner at his house, only to forget about it, so that, on the night of the dinner party, he was absent and his wife was in her nightclothes.<ref name=pinkos>{{cite web| last1=Pinkos| first1=Jefferey| title=Dinner Is Served| url=http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeoisie/| website=Lone Star Film Society| accessdate=12 December 2014| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223031928/http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeoisie/| archivedate=23 December 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film tells of a group of affluent friends who are continually stymied in their attempts to eat a meal together, a situation that a number of critics have contrasted to the opposite dilemma of the characters in ''[[The Exterminating Angel]]'', where guests of a dinner party are mysteriously unable to leave after having completed their meal.<ref name=lim /> For this film, Bu\u00f1uel, Silberman and Carri\u00e8re assembled a top-flight cast of European performers, \"a veritable rogues' gallery of French art-house cinema\", according to one critic.<ref name=\"budd wilkins\">{{cite web|last1=Wilkins|first1=Budd|title=The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeoisie-6699|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> For the first time, Bu\u00f1uel made use of a [[video monitors|video-playback monitor]], which allowed him to make much more extensive use of [[crane shot]]s and elaborate [[tracking shot]]s, and enabled him to cut the film in the camera and eliminate the need for [[Re-shoot|reshoots]].<ref name=pinkos /> Filming required only two months and Bu\u00f1uel claimed that editing took only one day.<ref name=pinkos /> When the film was released, Silberman decided to skip the Cannes Festival in order to concentrate on getting it nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]], which it won, leading Bu\u00f1uel to express his contempt for a process that relied on the judgment of, \"2500 idiots, including for example the assistant dress designer of the studio\".<ref name=pinkos />\n\nAs was his habit, Bu\u00f1uel took advantage of the popular success of ''Discreet Charm'' to make one of the \"puzzling, idiosyncratic films he ''really'' wanted to make\".<ref name=\"Polizzotti milky way\" /> In 1973, at the [[Monastery of El Paular|Monastery of Paular]] in the Spanish [[Somosierra]], he wrote the screenplay for ''[[The Phantom of Liberty]]''(1974) with Carri\u00e8re for production by Silberman and his Hollywood partners.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.249}} The resulting film is a series of 12 distinctive episodes with separate protagonists, linked together only by following a character from one episode to another in a relay-race manner.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lanzagorta|first1=Marco|title=The Phantom of Liberty| url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2002/cteq/phantom/|website=Senses of Cinema|publisher=Film Victoria, Australia|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel has stated that he made the film as a tribute to poet [[Benjamin P\u00e9ret]], a founding member of French Surrealism,<ref name=\"bill krohn\" />{{rp|p.170}} and called it his \"most Surrealist film\".<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.249}}\n\nBu\u00f1uel's final film was ''[[That Obscure Object of Desire]]'' (1977), adapted by Bu\u00f1uel and Carri\u00e8re from an 1898 novel by [[Pierre Lou\u00ffs]] called ''[[La Femme et le pantin]]'', which had already been used as the basis of films directed by [[Josef von Sternberg]] ([[The Devil is a Woman (1935 film)|''The Devil is a Woman'']], 1935) and [[Julien Duvivier]] (''[[La Femme et le Pantin]]'', 1959). The film, which tells the story of an older man who is obsessed by a young woman who continually evades his attempts to consummate a sexual relationship, starred the Spanish actor [[Fernando Rey]], appearing in his fourth Bu\u00f1uel film. Initially, the part of the young woman was to be played by [[Maria Schneider (actress)|Maria Schneider]], who had achieved international fame for her roles in ''[[Last Tango in Paris]]'' and [[The Passenger (1975 film)|''The Passenger'']],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grimes|first1=William|title=Maria Schneider, Actress in ''Last Tango'', Dies at 58|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/04/movies/04schneider.html|accessdate=16 December 2014|work=New York Times|date=4 February 2011}}</ref> but once shooting started, according to Carri\u00e8re, her drug usage resulted in a \"lackluster and dull\" performance that caused tempestuous arguments with Bu\u00f1uel on the set and her eventual dismissal.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Thomson|first1=David|title=David Thomson on Films: Remembering Maria Schneider|journal=New Republic|date=8 February 2011|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/books-and-arts/82975/david-thomson-films-remembering-maria-schneider|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref> Serge Silberman, the producer, decided to abandon the project at that point, but was convinced by Bu\u00f1uel to continue shooting with two different actresses, [[\u00c1ngela Molina]] and [[Carole Bouquet]] playing the same role in alternating sequences throughout the film. In his autobiography, Bu\u00f1uel claimed that this unusual casting decision was his own idea after drinking two dry martinis, saying: \"If I had to list all the benefits derived from alcohol, it would be endless\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pinkos|first1=Jefferey|title=Bu\u00f1uel's Pursuit of That Obscure Object|url=http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/that-obscure-object-of-desire/|website=Lone Star Film Society|accessdate=17 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223155848/http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/that-obscure-object-of-desire/|archivedate=23 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Others have reported that Carri\u00e8re had first broached the idea while developing the film's scenario, but had been brushed off by Bu\u00f1uel as \"the whim of a rainy day\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=That Obscure Object of Desire|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/that-obscure-object-of-desire|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Last years (1978\u20131983)===\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"Luis waited for death for a long time, like a good Spaniard, and when he died he was ready. His relationship with death was like that one has with a woman. He felt the love, hate, tenderness, ironical detachment of a long relationship, and he didn't want to miss the last encounter, the moment of union. \"I hope I will die alive,\" he told me. At the end it was as he had wished. His last words were 'I'm dying'.\"<ref name=\"carriere flickhead\" />  |source=Long-time friend and collaborator, [[Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re]]}}\nAfter the release of ''[[That Obscure Object of Desire]]'', Bu\u00f1uel retired from filmmaking.<ref name=\"McAdam\">{{cite web |last1=McAdam |first1=Conor |title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel is a Walking Contradiction |url=https://outtake.tribecashortlist.com/the-man-y-luis-bu%C3%B1uel-s-8260076236f0 |website=Outtake |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> In 1982, he wrote (along with Carri\u00e8re) his autobiography, ''Mon Dernier Soupir'' (''My Last Sigh''), which provides an account of his life, friends, and family as well as a representation of his eccentric personality. In it, he recounts dreams, encounters with many well-known writers, actors, and artists such as [[Pablo Picasso]] and [[Charlie Chaplin]] as well as antics, like dressing up as a nun and walking around town.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p. 83}}\n\nIn his seventies, Bu\u00f1uel once told his friend, novelist [[Carlos Fuentes]]: \"I'm not afraid of death. I'm afraid of dying alone in a hotel room, with my bags open and a shooting script on the night table. I must know whose fingers will close my eyes.\"<ref name=\"fuentes discreet charm\">{{cite web|last1=Fuentes|first1=Carlos|title=The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeosie|url=https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/109-the-discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeosie|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel died in Mexico City in 1983 of [[cirrhosis of the liver]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1983/07/30/surrealist-spanish-filmmaker-luis-bunuel-83/ca199f00-ca7c-4925-92da-2db4fdff7adf/|title=Surrealist Spanish Filmmaker Luis Bunuel, 83|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> Fuentes has recounted that Bu\u00f1uel spent his last week in hospital discussing theology with the Jesuit brother Julian Pablo, a long time friend.<ref name=\"fuentes milky way\">{{cite web|last1=Fuentes|first1=Carlos|title=The Milky Way: The Heretic's Progress|url=https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/610-the-milky-way-the-heretic-s-progress|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> His funeral was very private, involving only family and close friends, among them poets [[Octavio Paz]] and [[Homero Aridjis]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aridjis |first1=Homero |title=Octavio Paz: The Poet in His Labyrinth |url=http://www.log24.com/log08/saved/080419-Paz.html |website=Log24.com |publisher=Journal Archives of Steven H. Cullinane |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Dead man laughing\">{{cite news |last1=Tuckman |first1=Jo |title=Dead man laughing |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/dec/29/art |accessdate=22 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited |date=28 Dec 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Technique and influences==\n{{main|Filmmaking technique of Luis Bu\u00f1uel}}\n[[File:SilviaPinalStatue.JPG|thumb|Silvia Pinal was one of Bu\u00f1uel's \"stock company\" of actors and was his preferred choice for the lead in his film ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'', a part which finally went to [[Catherine Deneuve]]<ref name=\"faulkner literary adaptations\">{{cite book|last1=Faulkner|first1=Sally|title=Literary Adaptations in Spanish Cinema|date=2004|publisher=Tamesis|location=London|isbn=978-1855660984|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yeMgJsea3-8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref> ]]\nBu\u00f1uel's technique of filmmaking was strongly influenced by mise-en-scene, sound editing and use of music. The influences on his filmmaking have included a positive relationship to surrealism and a critical approach to atheism and religion. Bu\u00f1uel's style of directing was extremely economical; he shot films in a few weeks, rarely deviating from his script (the scene in ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'' where [[Catherine Deneuve]] exposes her breasts to Saturno \u2013 but not the audience \u2013 being a noted exception) and shooting as much as possible in order to minimize editing time.<ref>{{cite book|last=Alexander|first=Sean|title=\"Luis Bu\u00f1uel\", in The Scarecrow Video Movie Guide|year=2004|publisher=Sasquatch Books|location=Seattle WA|isbn=978-1-57061-415-6|pages=31|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qiQLs-6SocC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>   He remained true throughout his working life to an operating philosophy that he articulated at the beginning of his career in 1928:  \"The guiding idea, the silent procession of images that are concrete, decisive, measured in space and time\u2014in a word, the film\u2014was first projected inside the brain of the filmmaker\".<ref name=\"an unspeakable betrayal\" />{{rp|p.135}}  In this, Bu\u00f1uel has been compared with [[Alfred Hitchcock]], another director famous for precision, efficiency and preplanning, for whom actually shooting the film was an anticlimax, since each man would know, in Bu\u00f1uel's words, \"exactly how each scene will be shot and what the final montage will be\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Stam|first=Robert|title=\"Hitchcock and Bu\u00f1uel: Authority, Desire and the Absurd\", in Hitchcock's Rereleased Films: From Rope to Vertigo, ed. by Walter Raubicheck and Walter Srebnick|year=1991|publisher=Wayne State University Press|location=Detroit|isbn=978-0-8143-2326-7|pages=117|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CfVeQ5BaPVsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  According to actress [[Jeanne Moreau]]:  \"He was the only director I know who never threw away a shot. He had the film in his mind. When he said 'action' and 'cut,' you knew that what was in between the two would be printed.\"<ref name=yakir>{{cite web|last1=Yakir|first1=Dan|title=Two Old Masters: Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://www.filmcomment.com/article/luis-bunuel-remembered|website=Film Comment|publisher=Film Society of Lincoln Center|accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Tributes==\n[[File:Instituto IES Luis Bu\u00f1uel.jpg|thumb|left|Instituto de Educaci\u00f3n Secundaria (IES) Luis Bu\u00f1uel, Zaragoza, Spain]]\n* In 1994, a retrospective of Bu\u00f1uel's works was organized by the [[Kunst- und Ausstellungshalle der Bundesrepublik Deutschland|Kunst- und Ausstellungshalle]] in Bonn, as homage to one of the most internationally revered figures in world cinema.<ref name=\"d'lugo\">{{cite book|last=D'Lugo|first=Marvin|title=\"Bu\u00f1uel in the Cathedral of Culture\" in Marsha Kinder (ed.), Luis Bu\u00f1uel's The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie|year=1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, New York|isbn=978-0-521-56831-9|pages=108}}</ref> {{rp|p.101}}  This was followed in the summer of 1996 by a commemoration of the centenary of the birth of cinema held by the [[Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof\u00eda]] in Madrid, which included a unique retrospective, jointly sponsored by the King of Spain and the President of Mexico, called ''\u00bfBu\u00f1uel!. La mirada del siglo'', honoring his special status as Spanish cinema's most emblematic figure.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u00bfBu\u00f1uel!. La mirada del siglo|url=http://www.museoreinasofia.es/publicaciones/catalogo.html?idPub=326|website=Cat\u00e1logo de publicaciones|publisher=Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof\u00eda|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref>[[File:Liceo Espa\u00f1ol Luis Bu\u00f1uel.jpg|thumb|[[Liceo Espa\u00f1ol Luis Bu\u00f1uel]]]]\n* A secondary school in [[Zaragoza]], Spain has been named for Bu\u00f1uel: Instituto de Educaci\u00f3n Secundaria Ies Luis Bu\u00f1uel.<ref>{{cite web|title=IES Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://iesluisbunuel.com/|publisher=iesluisbunuel.com/|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref> [[Liceo Espa\u00f1ol Luis Bu\u00f1uel]], a Spanish international school, is in [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], [[France]], near Paris.<ref>{{cite web|title=Historia del Liceo Espa\u00f1ol|url=http://www.educacion.gob.es/exterior/centros/luisbunuel/es/secretaria/historia.shtml|website=Liceo Espa\u00f1ol Luis Bu\u00f1uel|publisher=Gobierno de Espana. Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n* In [[Calanda, Spain]] a bust of the head of Luis Bu\u00f1uel is on display at the [[Centro Bu\u00f1uel Calanda]] (CBC), a museum devoted to the director.<ref>{{cite book|last=Simonis|first=Damien|title=Spain \u2013 ebook edition. 7th Edition|year=2009|publisher=Lonely Planet|location=Oakland, CA|isbn=978-1-74179-000-9|pages=467|url=https://books.google.com/?id=B1pFbOvxN1wC&pg=PA467&lpg=PA467&dq=Head+of+Luis+Bu%C3%B1uel+in+Centro+Bu%C3%B1uel+Calanda.#v=onepage}}</ref>  The mission of the CBC is to serve as a reference center both for connoisseurs of Bu\u00f1uel and for anyone interested in the arts of [[Aragon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=el CBC|url=http://www.cbcvirtual.com/menu.jsp|publisher=cbcvirtual.com|accessdate=9 August 2012}}</ref>\n* One of the main theatres at the [[Palais des Festivals et des Congr\u00e8s]], where the [[Cannes Film Festival]] is held, is named after him: ''Salle Bu\u00f1uel''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Acc\u00e8s aux projections|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/fr/festivalServices/festivalGuideTheatres.html|publisher=Festival de Cannes|accessdate=26 July 2012}}</ref>\n* To mark the centenary of his birth, in 2000 the Cannes festival partnered with the Spanish film industry, to pay tribute to Luis Bu\u00f1uel.  This tribute consisted of three events: (1) the inauguration, for Cannes 2000, of the Palace's new Luis Bu\u00f1uel room, (2) an original exhibition organized by L'Instituto de la Cinematograf\u00eda y de las Artes Audiovisuales entitled \"The Secret World of Bu\u00f1uel\", and (3) an exceptional projection of ''Viridiana'', the Palme d'Or winner in 1961, in the presence of specially invited artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tribute to Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/archives/evenementPresentation/id/76/title/evenementHommages/year/2000.html|website=Around the selection 2000|publisher=Festival de Cannes|accessdate=26 July 2012}}</ref>\n* The Luis Bu\u00f1uel Film Institute (LBFI) is housed in the [[The Downtown Independent|Downtown Independent Theatre]], Los Angeles, and has as its mission: \"to form the vital and innovative arena for the promotion of the work of Luis Bu\u00f1uel, and a seminal resource for the development of new research, knowledge and scholarship on his life and work, extending across his body of films and writings\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel Film Institute|url=http://www.luisbunuelfilminstitute.com/about.php|publisher=Luis Bu\u00f1uel Film Institute|accessdate=16 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921084950/http://luisbunuelfilminstitute.com/about.php|archive-date=21 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Characterizations==\nBu\u00f1uel has been portrayed as a character in many films and television productions.  A portion of the television mini-series ''Lorca, muerte de un poeta'' (1987\u20131988), directed by [[Juan Antonio Bardem]] recreates the student years of Bu\u00f1uel, Lorca and Dal\u00ed, with Fernando Valverde portraying Bu\u00f1uel in two episodes.<ref>{{cite web|last=Selas|first=Alejandro Reche|title=La Hispalense rendir\u00e1 homenaje a Bu\u00f1uel en marco del Festival de Cine|url=http://www.diariodesevilla.es/article/ocio/496982/la/hispalense/rendira/homenaje/bunuel/marco/festival/cine.html|website=Diario de Sevilla|publisher=[[Joly Digital]]|accessdate=7 August 2012}}</ref>  He was played by Dimiter Guerasimof in the 1991 biopic ''Dal\u00ed'', directed by [[Antoni Ribas]], despite the fact that Dal\u00ed and his attorney had written to Ribas objecting to the project in its early stages in 1985.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dal\u00ed se opone a un proyecto de pel\u00edcula de Antoni Ribas sobre el pintor|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1985/01/18/cultura/474850803_850215.html|accessdate=7 August 2012|newspaper=El Pais|date=18 January 1985}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel appeared as a character in Alejandro Pelayo's 1993 film ''Miroslava'', based on the life of actress [[Miroslava (actress)|Miroslava Stern]], who committed suicide after appearing in ''Ensayo de un crimen'' (1955).<ref>{{cite book|last=Montes Garces|first=Elizabeth|title=Relocating Identities in Latin American Cultures|year=2007|publisher=University of Calgary Press|location=Calgary|isbn=978-1-55238-209-7|pages=139\u2013140|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l0KA5n4Gm9UC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel was played by three actors, [[El Gran Wyoming]] (old age), Pere Arquillu\u00e9 (young adult) and Juan Carlos Jim\u00e9nez Mar\u00edn (child), in [[Carlos Saura]]'s 2001 fantasy, ''Bu\u00f1uel y la mesa del rey Salom\u00f3n'', which tells of Bu\u00f1uel, Lorca and Dal\u00ed setting out in search of the mythical table of King Salom\u00f3n, which is thought to have the power to see into the past, the present and the future.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bu\u00f1uel y la mesa del Rey Salom\u00f3n|url=http://www.clubcultura.com/clubcine/bunuel_saura/bunuel_saura1.htm|website=Noticias|publisher=ClubCine|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel was a character in a 2001 television miniseries ''[[Severo Ochoa]]: La conquista de un Nobel'', on the life of the Spanish [[\u00e9migr\u00e9]] and [[Nobel Prize]] winner in medicine, who was also at the Residencia de Estudiantes during Bu\u00f1uel's time there.<ref>{{cite web|title=Residencia de Estudiantes \u2013 History|url=http://www.residencia.csic.es/en/info/history.htm|publisher=Residencia de Estudiantes|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> [[Matt Lucas]] portrayed Bu\u00f1uel in Richard Curson Smith's 2002 TV movie ''Surrealissimo: The Scandalous Success of Salvador Dal\u00ed'', a comedy depicting Dal\u00ed's \"trial\" by the Surrealists in 1934 for his pro-Hitler sympathies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rojas|first=Carlos|title=Salvador Dal\u00ed, Or The Art of Spitting on Your Mother's Portrait|year=1993|publisher=Penn State Press|location=University Park PA|isbn=978-0-271-00842-4|pages=98|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MWF5s2yfFqwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  A 2005 short called ''[[The Death of Salvador Dali]]'', directed by Delaney Bishop, contains sequences in which Bu\u00f1uel appears, played by Alejandro Cardenas.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Death of Salvador Dali \u2013 Press release|url=http://www.dalimovie.com/Press.html|publisher=dalimovie.com|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> [[Paul Morrison (director)|Paul Morrison]]'s ''[[Little Ashes]]'' hypothesizes a love affair between Dal\u00ed and Lorca, with Bu\u00f1uel (played by [[Matthew McNulty]]) looking on suspiciously.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=David|title=Were Spain's two artistic legends secret gay lovers?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/oct/28/spain.books|accessdate=8 August 2012|newspaper=The Observer|date=27 October 2007|location=London}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel, played by Adrien de Van, is one of many notable personalities encountered by [[Woody Allen]]'s protagonist in ''[[Midnight in Paris]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite news|last=Berger|first=Joseph|title=Decoding Woody Allen's ''Midnight in Paris''|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/28/movies/midnight-in-paris-a-historical-view.html|accessdate=8 August 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=27 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nBu\u00f1uel was given the Career Golden Lion in 1982 by the [[Venice Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Golden Lion for Career Achievement |url=http://www.carnivalofvenice.com/the-city/events-in-venice/venice-film-festival/awards-and-acknowledgements/golden-lion/golden-lion-for-career-achievement?lang=en |website=Portale di Venezia |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> and the [[International Federation of Film Critics|FIPRESCI Prize]] \u2013 Honorable Mention in 1969 by the [[Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Berlinale - International Film Festival Berlin |url=https://www.inter-film.org/festivals/berlinale-international-film-festival-berlin |website=inter-film |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> In 1977, he received the [[National Prize for Arts and Sciences]] for Fine Arts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Salazar |first1=David |title=Famed Mexican Auteur Arturo Ripstein's 'Bleak Street' Gets US Run |url=https://www.latinpost.com/articles/104216/20151223/famed-mexican-auteur-arturo-ripsteins-bleak-street-gets-run.htm |website=Latin Post |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> At the [[11th Moscow International Film Festival]] in 1979, he was awarded the Honorable Prize for his contribution to cinema.<ref name=\"Moscow1979\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1979 |title=11th Moscow International Film Festival (1979) |accessdate=20 January 2013 |website=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403102012/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1979 |archivedate=3 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{main|Luis Bu\u00f1uel filmography}}\n\n=== Documentaries about Bu\u00f1uel ===\n* ''Dans l'oeil de Luis Bu\u00f1uel''. France, 2013, 54 min., book and director: Fran\u00e7ois L\u00e9vy-Kuentz, Producer: KUIV Productions, arte France.\n* ''El \u00faltimo gui\u00f3n \u2013 Bu\u00f1uel en la memoria''. Spain, Germany, France, 2008, 45 min., Book and director: Javier Espada und Gaizka Urresti, Producer: Imval Producciones\n* ''Tras Nazar\u00edn (Following Nazar\u00edn)''.  Spain/Mexico, 2015. Directed by Javier Espada. Ircania Producciones. Utilizes still photos taken by Bu\u00f1uel and [[Manuel \u00c1lvarez Bravo]] to link the images of the film to the Mexican countryside. Includes interviews with Jean Claude Carri\u00e8re,  [[Ignacio L\u00f3pez Tarso]],  Silvia Pinal, [[Arturo Ripstein]] and [[Carlos Reygadas]], along with critics and film scholars.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tras Nazar\u00edn (Following Nazar\u00edn) |url=https://www.moma.org/calendar/events/6633 |website=MoMA |publisher=Museum of Modern Art}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Luis Bu\u00f1uel}}\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|onlinebooks=yes|about=yes|wikititle=Luis Bu\u00f1uel}}\n\n{{Portal|Film}}\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Art film]]\n* [[Cinema of Mexico]]\n* [[Cinema of Spain]]\n* [[Experimental film]]\n* [[Generation of '27]]\n* [[List of atheists in film, radio, television and theater]]\n* [[List of banned films]]\n* [[Satire]]\n* [[Surrealism]]\n* [[Surrealist cinema]]\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{See also|Luis Bu\u00f1uel bibliography}}\n* J. Francisco Aranda ''Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Biografia Critica'' (Spanish Edition) Paperback: 479 pages. Publisher: Lumen; Nueva ed. rev. y aumentada edition (1975) . Language: Spanish . {{ISBN|8426410553}}. {{ISBN|978-8426410559}}.\n*Robert Bresson and Luis Bu\u00f1uel. ''La politica de los autores/ The Politics of Authors'' (La Memoria Del Cine) (Spanish Edition) Paidos Iberica Ediciones S a (April 2003), 189 pages, {{ISBN|8449314143}}\n* Luis Bu\u00f1uel, ''Mi Ultimo Suspiro'' (English translation ''My Last Sigh'' [[Alfred A. Knopf]], 1983).\n*{{cite book|last=Bu\u00f1uel|first=Luis|title=An Unspeakable Betrayal: Selected Writings of Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tK3KPgv34U8C|date=1 March 2002|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-23423-9}}\n* Luis Bu\u00f1uel, Manuel Lopez Villegas. ''Escritos de Luis Bunuel (Fundidos En Negro / Fused in Black)'' (Spanish Edition), Editorial Paginas de Espuma; Paperback, February 2, 2000, 296 pp,{{ISBN|8493124303}}\n* Luis Bu\u00f1uel, Raf\u00e6l Bu\u00f1uel, Juan Luis Bu\u00f1uel (Afterword). ''An Unspeakable Betrayal: Selected Writings of Luis Bu\u00f1uel.'' Publisher: University of California Press; First edition (April 6, 2000), pp 277, {{ISBN|0520208404}}\n* [https://www.amazon.es/Luis-Bunuel-1929-1939-Wisconsin-Studies/dp/0299284743 ''Luis Bu\u00f1uel: The Red Years, 1929\u20131939'' (Wisconsin Film Studies).]\n*Luis Bu\u00f1uel. ''El discreto encanto de la burguesia (Coleccion Voz imagen'', Serie cine ; 26) (Spanish Edition) Paperback \u2013 159 pages, Publisher: Ayma; 1. ed edition (1973), {{ISBN|8420912646}}\n*Luis Bu\u00f1uel. ''El fantasma de la libertad'' (Serie cine) (Spanish Edition) Serie cine Paperback,  Publisher: Ayma; 1. ed edition (1975) 148 pages, {{ISBN|8420912840}}\n*Luis Bu\u00f1uel. ''Obra literaria'' (Spanish Edition) Publisher: Heraldo de Aragon (1982),291 pages, {{ISBN|8485492749}}\n*Luis Bu\u00f1uel. ''L'Age d'or: Correspondance Luis Bunuel-Charles de Noailles : lettres et documents (1929\u20131976'') (Les Cahiers du Musee national d'art moderne)  Centre Georges Pompidou (publ), 1993, pp 190, {{ISBN|2858507457}}\n* Froylan Enciso, ''En defensa del poeta Bu\u00f1uel, en Andar fronteras. El servicio diplom\u00e1tico de Octavio Paz en Francia (1946\u20131951)'', Siglo XXI, 2008, pp.&nbsp;130\u2013134 y 353\u2013357.\n*{{cite book|last=Durgnat|first=Raymond|title=Luis Bunuel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_lbzZWIbgwkC|year=1977|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-03424-2}}\n* Javier Espada y Elena Cervera, ''M\u00e9xico fotografiado por Luis Bu\u00f1uel''.\n* Javier Espada y Elena Cervera, ''Bu\u00f1uel. Entre 2 Mundos''.\n* Javier Espada y Asier Mensuro, ''Album fotografico de la familia Bu\u00f1uel''.\n*{{cite book|last1=Gubern|first1=Rom\u00e1n|last2=Hammond|first2=Paul|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: The Red Years, 1929\u20131939|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=elueEkeLL_oC|date=4 January 2012|publisher=University of Wisconsin Pres|isbn=978-0-299-28474-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Higginbotham|first=Virginia|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WalZAAAAMAAJ|year=1979|publisher=Twayne Publishers|isbn=978-0-8057-9261-4}}\n* Michael Koller [https://web.archive.org/web/20101225061923/http://archive.sensesofcinema.com/contents/cteq/01/12/chien.html \"Un Chien Andalou\", ''Senses of Cinema'' January 2001] Retrieved on 26 July 2006.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = L\u00f3pez | first1 = Ignacio Javier | year = 2001 | title = The Old Age of William Tell: A Study of Bu\u00f1uel's '\"Tristana\"' | url = | journal = [[Modern Language Notes|MLN]] | volume = 116 | issue = 2| pages = 295\u2013314 | doi=10.1353/mln.2001.0023}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = L\u00f3pez | first1 = Ignacio Javier | year = 2003 | title = Film, Freud and Paranoia: Dal\u00ed and the Representation of Male Desire in ''An Andalusian Dog'' | url = | journal = [[Diacritics (journal)|Diacritics]] | volume = 31 | issue = 2| pages = 35\u201348 | doi = 10.1353/dia.2003.0010 }}\n*{{cite book|last1=Santaolalla|first1=Isabel|last2=Evans|first2=Peter William|title=Luis Bunuel: New Readings| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lH2GAAAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=British Film Institute|isbn=978-1-84457-003-4}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{External links|section|date=May 2017}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000320|Luis Bu\u00f1uel}}\n* [http://www.luisbunuelfilminstitute.com/ The Luis Bu\u00f1uel Film Institute]\n* [http://www.sensesofcinema.com/2005/great-directors/bunuel/ Senses of Cinema: Great Directors Critical Database]\n* [http://www.theyshootpictures.com/bunuelluis.htm They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?]\n* ''La furia umana'', n\u00b06, multilanguage dossier (texts by Gilberto Perez, Adrian Martin, Toni D'Angela, Alberto Abruzzese and others) * * \n* [http://www.lafuriaumana.it/index.php/archive/53-la-furia-umana-nd-6-autumn-2010- ''La furia umana'']\n* [http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/MRC/Bunuelbib.html Bunuel Bibliography (via UC Berkeley)]\n* [http://www.1worldfilms.com/luis_bunuel.htm Bu\u00f1uel biography]\n\n{{Luis Bu\u00f1uel}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Luis Bu\u00f1uel\n| list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestForeignLanguageFilm 1961\u20131980}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Screenplay}}\n{{Prix de la mise en scene 1946\u20131959}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Director}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Director}}\n}}\n{{Surrealism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bunuel, Luis}}\n[[Category:Luis Bu\u00f1uel| ]]\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:Anti-Catholicism in Spain]]\n[[Category:Aragonese film directors]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Foreign Language Film Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Director Ariel Award winners]]\n[[Category:Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Director winners]]\n[[Category:Complutense University of Madrid alumni]]\n[[Category:Critics of religions]]\n[[Category:Directors of Palme d'Or winners]]\n[[Category:Directors of Golden Lion winners]]\n[[Category:Exiles of the Spanish Civil War in Mexico]]\n[[Category:French atheists]]\n[[Category:French experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:French film directors]]\n[[Category:Golden Ariel Award winners]]\n[[Category:Mexican atheists]]\n[[Category:Mexican experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Mexican film directors]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Mexico]]\n[[Category:People from Calanda]]\n[[Category:Silent film directors]]\n[[Category:Spanish atheists]]\n[[Category:Spanish experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Spanish film directors]]\n[[Category:Spanish Marxists]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of the Spanish Civil War (Republican faction)]]\n[[Category:Spanish surrealist artists]]\n[[Category:Surrealist filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cirrhosis]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish film director}}\n{{spanish name|Bu\u00f1uel|Portol\u00e9s}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Luis Bu\u00f1uel\n|image        = Luis Bu\u00f1uel.JPG\n|caption      = Bu\u00f1uel, 1968\n|birth_name   = Luis Bu\u00f1uel Portol\u00e9s\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1900|2|22|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Calanda, Spain|Calanda]], [[Aragon]], Spain\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1983|7|29|1900|2|22|df=y}}\n|death_place  = [[Mexico City]], Mexico\n|citizenship  = {{ubl|Spain (renounced in 1949)|Mexico (since 1949)<ref name=\"Harvard.edu\">{{cite web |title=Bu\u00f1uel's Mexico |url=http://hcl.harvard.edu/hfa/films/2012julsep/bunuel.html |website=Harvard Film Archive |publisher=Fine Arts Library of the Harvard College Library |access-date=10 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304114616/http://hcl.harvard.edu/hfa/films/2012julsep/bunuel.html |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n|alma_mater   = [[Complutense University of Madrid|University of Madrid]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|[[Jeanne Rucar]]|1934}}\n|years_active = 1929\u20131977\n|occupation   = Filmmaker\n}}\n\n'''Luis Bu\u00f1uel Portol\u00e9s''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8lwis \u03b2u\u02c8\u0272wel po\u027eto\u02c8les}}; 22 February 1900 \u2013 29 July 1983) was a Spanish [[filmmaker]], naturalised Mexican in 1949,<ref name =\"Harvard.edu\" /> who worked in France, Mexico and Spain.<ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\">{{cite web|last=Kyrou|first=Ado|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Luis-Bunuel|website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen Bu\u00f1uel died at age 83, his [[obituary]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' called him \"an [[iconoclast]], moralist, and revolutionary who was a leader of [[avant-garde]] [[surrealism]] in his youth and a dominant international movie director half a century later\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last=Flint|first=Peter B.|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel Dies at 83; Filmmaker for 50 Years|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/07/30/obituaries/luis-bunuel-dies-at-83-film-maker-for-50-years.html|access-date=6 August 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=30 July 1983}}</ref>  His first picture, ''[[Un Chien Andalou]]''\u2014made in the [[silent film|silent era]]\u2014was called \"the most famous short film ever made\" by critic [[Roger Ebert]],<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=Un Chien Andalou Movie Review (1928)|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-un-chien-andalou-1928|work=Great Movies: The First 100|publisher=RogerEbert.com|access-date=9 October 2017|date=16 April 2000}}</ref> and his last film, ''[[That Obscure Object of Desire]]''\u2014made 48 years later\u2014won him Best Director awards from the [[National Board of Review]] and the [[National Society of Film Critics]].<ref name=\"Ramirez Berg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.austinfilm.org/essential-cinema/program-notes-that-obscure-object-of-desire |title=Program Notes: THAT OBSCURE OBJECT OF DESIRE |last=Berg |first=Charles Ram\u00edrez |publisher=Austin Film Society |access-date=9 October 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610201718/http://www.austinfilm.org/essential-cinema/program-notes-that-obscure-object-of-desire |archivedate=10 June 2015 }}</ref>  Writer [[Octavio Paz]] called Bu\u00f1uel's work \"the marriage of the film image to the poetic image, creating a new reality...scandalous and subversive\".<ref name=paz>{{cite book|last=Paz|first=Octavio|title=On Poets and Others|year=1986|publisher=Arcade Publishing|location=New York|isbn=978-1-55970-139-6|pages=152|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qoiEQ4FiuFsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>\n\nOften associated with the [[surrealist movement]] of the 1920s, Bu\u00f1uel created films from the 1920s through the 1970s. His work spans two continents, three languages, and an array of genres, including [[experimental film]], [[Documentary film|documentary]], [[Melodrama#Film|melodrama]], [[satire]], [[Musical film|musical]], [[Sex in film|erotica]], [[Comedy film|comedy]], [[Romance film|romance]], [[costume drama]]s, [[Fantasy film|fantasy]], [[crime film]], [[Adventure film|adventure]], and [[Western (genre)#Film|western]]. Despite this variety, filmmaker [[John Huston]] believed that, regardless of genre, a Bu\u00f1uel film is so distinctive as to be instantly recognizable,<ref>{{cite book|last=Sinyard|first=Neil|title=\"The Discreet Charm of Houston and Bu\u00f1uel: Notes on a Cinematic Odd Couple\", in John Huston: Essays on a Restless Director, ed. Tony Tracy and Roddy Flynn|year=2010|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson NC|isbn=978-0-7864-5853-0|pages=73|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xhfl7DdYTMQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> or, as [[Ingmar Bergman]] put it, \"Bu\u00f1uel nearly always made Bu\u00f1uel films\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bergmanorama.webs.com/bergman_on_directors.htm |title=Commentary: Bergman on Filmmakers |publisher=Berganorama |accessdate=9 October 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090624023319/http://bergmanorama.webs.com/bergman_on_directors.htm |archivedate=24 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSeven of Bu\u00f1uel's films are included in ''[[Sight & Sound]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 2012 critics' poll of the top 250 films of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thependragonsociety.com/sight-sound-2012-critics-top-250-films/|title=Sight & Sound 2012 critics top 250 films|last=Pendragon|first=The|date=2018-04-26|website=The Pendragon Society|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Critics' Top 250 Films |url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/sightandsoundpolls/2012/critics |website=Sight and Sound |publisher=British Film Institute |access-date=18 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026034922/http://explore.bfi.org.uk/sightandsoundpolls/2012/critics |archivedate=26 October 2013 }}</ref> Fifteen of his films are included in the ''They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?'' list of the 1,000 greatest films of all time, for which he ranks second only to [[Jean-Luc Godard]], with sixteen,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_all1000films_table.php|title=The 1,000 Greatest Films|publisher=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?}}</ref> and he ranks number 13 on their list of the top 250 directors.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Top 250 Directors|url=http://www.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_top250directors.htm|publisher=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?|access-date=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\n[[File:Vista parcial de Calanda. Foto Jos\u00e9 Antonio Bielsa.JPG|thumb|right|Calanda, Spain|[[Calanda, Spain|Calanda]], Spain]]\nBu\u00f1uel was born in [[Calanda, Spain|Calanda]], a small town in the [[Teruel (province)|province of Teruel]], in the [[Aragon]] region of Spain, to Leonardo Bu\u00f1uel, the cultivated scion of an established Aragonese family, and Mar\u00eda Portol\u00e9s, many years younger than her husband, with wealth and family connections of her own.<ref name=Alcala>{{cite book|last=Alcal\u00e1|first=Manuel|title=Bu\u00f1uel (Cine e ideologia)|year=1973|publisher=Edicusa|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-229-0101-3}}</ref>{{rp|pp.16\u201317}} He would later describe his birthplace by saying that in Calanda, \"the [[Middle Ages]] lasted until [[World War&nbsp;I]]\".<ref>Bu\u00f1uel, Luis. ''My Last Sigh''. Trans. Abigail Israel. Minneapolis: [[University of Minnesota Press]], 2003. {{ISBN|0-8166-4387-3}}. page 8.</ref> The oldest of seven children, Luis had two brothers, Alfonso and Leonardo, and four sisters: Alicia, Concepci\u00f3n, Margarita and Mar\u00eda.<ref name=schwarze>{{cite book|last=Schwarze|first=Michael|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|year=1988|publisher=Plaza & Janes|location=Barcelona|isbn=978-84-01-45079-2|pages=9}}</ref>\n\nWhen Bu\u00f1uel was four and a half months old, the family moved to [[Zaragoza]], where they were one of the wealthiest families in town.<ref name=Alcala />{{rp|p.22}} In Zaragoza, Bu\u00f1uel received a strict [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] education at the private Colegio del Salvador.<ref name=Alcala />{{rp|pp.23\u201336}} After being kicked and insulted by the study hall proctor before a final exam, Bu\u00f1uel refused to return to the school.<ref name=\"directors guide\" />  He told his mother he had been expelled, which was not true; in fact, he had received the highest marks on his world history exam.<ref>Bu\u00f1uel, Luis. ''My Last Sigh''. Trans. Abigail Israel. Minneapolis: University of Minnesota Press, 2003. {{ISBN|0-8166-4387-3}}. page 30.</ref> Bu\u00f1uel finished the last two years of his high school education at the local public school.<ref name=\"directors guide\">{{cite web|title=Luis Bunuel|url=http://www.greatestdirectors.com/buneul.html|website=The Directors Guide|publisher=Website Creations|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref>  Even as a child, Bu\u00f1uel was something of a cinematic showman; friends from that period described productions in which Bu\u00f1uel would project shadows on a screen using a [[magic lantern]] and a bedsheet.<ref name=\"A Proposito de Bunuel\">{{cite web|last=Gobierno de Aragon|title=A Proposito de Bunuel \u2013 Screenplay|url=http://www.american-buddha.com/bunuel.screenplay.htm|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> He also excelled at boxing and playing the violin.<ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\" />\n\n[[File:Salvador Dal\u00ed 1939.jpg|thumb|left|[[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]]]\n\nIn his youth, Bu\u00f1uel was deeply religious, serving at Mass and taking Communion every day, until, at the age of 16, he grew disgusted with what he perceived as the illogicality of the Church, along with its power and wealth.<ref name=brandon>{{cite book|last=Brandon|first=Ruth|title=Surreal Lives: The Surrealists 1917\u20131945|year=1999|publisher=Macmillan|location=London|isbn=978-0-8021-3727-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9_Z0rVDhNGsC&pg=PA291&lpg=PA291&dq=bunuel+agronomy#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20agronomy}}</ref>{{rp|p.292}}\n\nIn 1917, he attended the [[Complutense University of Madrid|University of Madrid]], first studying [[agronomy]] then [[industrial engineering]] and finally switching to [[philosophy]].<ref name=\"smith celebrities\">{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Warren Allen|title=Celebrities in Hell|year=2002|publisher=Barricade Books|location=Fort Lee, NJ|isbn=978-1-56980-214-4|pages=25|url=https://books.google.com/?id=x73FqQgvzgQC&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=luis+bunuel+agronomy#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20agronomy}}</ref>  He developed a very close relationship with painter [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]] and poet [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]], among other important Spanish creative artists living in the [[Residencia de Estudiantes]], with the three friends forming the nucleus of the Spanish Surrealist [[avant-garde]],<ref name=delgado>{{cite book|last=Delgado|first=Manuel and Alice J. Poust|title=Lorca, Bu\u0146uel, Dal\u00ed: Art and Theory|year=2001|publisher=Associated University Presses|location=Cranbury NJ|isbn=978-0-8387-5508-2|pages=passim|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fOJRnesy3x8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  and becoming known as members of \"[[Generation of '27|La Generaci\u00f3n del 27]]\".<ref name=poets.org>{{cite web|title=La Generacion del 27: Dal\u00ed, Bu\u00f1uel, and Lorca|url=http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/5944|publisher=Poets.org|accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel was especially taken with Lorca, later writing in his autobiography: \"We liked each other instantly.  Although we seemed to have little in common\u2014I was a redneck from Aragon, and he an elegant Andalusian\u2014we spent most of our time together... We used to sit on the grass in the evenings behind the Residencia (at that time, there were vast open spaces reaching to the horizon), and he would read me his poems. He read slowly and beautifully, and through him I began to discover a wholly new world.\"<ref name=\"my last sigh\">{{cite book|last=Bu\u00f1uel|first=Luis|title=My last sigh|url=https://archive.org/details/mylastsigh0000buue|url-access=registration|year=1983|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-394-52854-0}}</ref>{{rp|p.62}} Bu\u00f1uel's relationship with Dal\u00ed was somewhat more troubled, being tinged with jealousy over the growing intimacy between Dal\u00ed and Lorca and resentment over Dal\u00ed's early success as an artist.<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.300}}\n\n[[File:Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca. Huerta de San Vicente, Granada.jpg|thumb|[[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]]]]\n\nSince he was 17, he steadily dated the future poet and dramatist [[Concha M\u00e9ndez]], with whom he vacationed every summer at [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]]. He introduced her to his friends at the Residencia as his fianc\u00e9e.<ref name=bellver>{{cite book|last=Bellver|first=Catherine Gullo|title=Absence and Presence: Spanish Women Poets of the Twenties and Thirties|year=2001|publisher=Bucknell University Press|location=Lewisburg, PA|isbn=978-0-8387-5463-4|pages=232}}</ref><ref name=wilcox>{{cite book|last=Wilcox|first=John Chapman|title=Women Poets of Spain, 1860\u20131990: Toward a Gynocentric Vision|year=1997|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana and Chicago| isbn=978-0-252-06559-0|pages=125|url=https://books.google.com/?id=i8RlmBiUl68C&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125&dq=concha+mendez+bunuel#v=onepage&q=concha%20mendez%20bunuel}}</ref>   After five years, she broke off the relationship, citing Bu\u00f1uel's \"insufferable character\".<ref name=agonia.net>{{cite web|title=Biografia Concha Mendez Cuesta|url=http://portugues.agonia.net/index.php/author/0028634/index.html|publisher=Agonia.Net|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring his student years, Bu\u00f1uel became an accomplished hypnotist. He claimed that once, while calming a hysterical prostitute through [[hypnosis|hypnotic]] suggestion, he inadvertently put one of the several bystanders into a trance as well.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.67}} He was often to insist that watching movies was a form of hypnosis:  \"This kind of cinematographic hypnosis is no doubt due to the darkness of the theatre and to the rapidly changing scenes, lights, and camera movements, which weaken the spectator's critical intelligence and exercise over him a kind of fascination.\"<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.69}}\n\nBu\u00f1uel's interest in films was intensified by a viewing of [[Fritz Lang]]'s ''[[Destiny (1921 film)|Der m\u00fcde Tod]]'': \"I came out of the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Vieux-Colombier|Vieux Colombier]] [theater] completely transformed. Images could and did become for me the true means of expression. I decided to devote myself to the cinema\".<ref name=\"Buffalo Film Seminars 1\">{{cite web|last=Christian|first=Diane, and Bruce Jackson|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel That Obscure Object of Desire/ Cet obscur oject du d\u00e9sir 1977|url=http://csac.buffalo.edu/desire.pdf|website=Buffalo Film Seminars|publisher=Market Arcade Film & Arts Center and State University of New York at Buffalo|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref>  At age 72, Bu\u00f1uel had not lost his enthusiasm for this film, asking the octogenarian Lang for his autograph.<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.301}}\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early French period  (1925\u20131930)===\n[[File:Jean epstein 1920.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Jean Epstein]], Bu\u00f1uel's first film collaborator]]\nIn 1925 Bu\u00f1uel moved to Paris, where he began work as a secretary in an organization called the International Society of Intellectual Cooperation.<ref name=\"bfi vol 3\">{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Paul|title=\"L'Age d'Or\" in British Film Institute Film Classics, Volume 3|year=2003|publisher=Taylor and Francis|location=New York|isbn=978-1-57958-328-6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=V96tee1l2q8C&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&dq=bunuel+intellectual+cooperation#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20intellectual%20cooperation}}</ref>{{rp|p.124}} He also became actively involved in cinema and theater, going to the movies as often as three times a day.<ref name=williams>{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Alan Larson|title=Republic of Images: A History of French Filmmaking|year=1992|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-674-76267-1|pages=152|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ESVZOghoi6kC&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=jean+epstein+luis+bunuel#v=onepage&q=jean%20epstein%20luis%20bunuel}}</ref> Through these interests, he met a number of influential people, including the pianist [[Ricardo Vi\u00f1es]], who was instrumental in securing Bu\u00f1uel's selection as artistic director of the Dutch premiere of [[Manuel de Falla]]'s puppet-opera ''[[El retablo de maese Pedro]]'' in 1926.<ref name=talens>{{cite book|last=Tal\u00e9ns|first=Jenaro|title=The Branded Eye: Bu\u00f1uel's Un Chien Andalou|year=1993|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-2046-3|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5209-5Ai_ZwC&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=bunuel+abel+gance#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20abel%20gance}}</ref>{{rp|p.29}}\n\nHe decided to enter the film industry and enrolled in a private film school run by [[Jean Epstein]] and some associates.<ref name=williams />  At that time, Epstein was one of the most celebrated commercial directors working in France, his films being hailed as \"the triumph of [[impressionism]] in motion, but also the triumph of the modern spirit\".<ref name=sadoul>{{cite book|last=Sadoul|first=Georges|title=Dictionary of Film Makers|year=1972|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley & Los Angeles|isbn=978-0-520-02151-8|pages=77|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PvsZikRu-hAC&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=jean+epstein+reputation#v=onepage&q=jean%20epstein%20reputation}}</ref>   Before long, Bu\u00f1uel was working for Epstein as an assistant director on ''[[Mauprat (film)|Mauprat]]'' (1926) and ''[[The Fall of the House of Usher (1928 French film)|La chute de la maison Usher]]'' (1928),<ref name=edwards>{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Gwynne|title=A Companion to Lu\u00eds Bu\u00f1uel|year=2005|publisher=Tamesis|location=Woodbridge|isbn=978-1-85566-108-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=r5_VlQTnbD0C&pg=PA21&lpg=PA21&dq=bunuel+epstein#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20baker}}</ref> and also for [[Mario Nalpas]] on ''La Sir\u00e8ne des Tropiques'' (1927), starring [[Josephine Baker]].<ref name=fandor>{{cite web|title=Siren of the Tropics|url=http://www.fandor.com/films/siren_of_the_tropics|website=fandor|publisher=Our Film Festival, Inc.|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref>  He appeared on screen in a small part as a smuggler in [[Jacques Feyder]]'s ''[[Carmen (1926 film)|Carmen]]'' (1926).<ref name=\"brain juice\">{{cite web|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://www.brain-juice.com/cgi-bin/show_bio.cgi?p_id=136|website=brain-juice|publisher=Brain-Juice.Com, Inc.|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhen Bu\u00f1uel somewhat derisively refused to acquiesce to Epstein's demand that he assist Epstein's mentor, [[Abel Gance]], who was at the time working on the film ''[[Napol\u00e9on (1927 film)|Napol\u00e9on]]'', Epstein dismissed him angrily, saying \"How can a little asshole like you dare to talk that way about a great director like Gance?\"<ref name=talens />{{rp|p.30}} then added \"You seem rather surrealist. Beware of surrealists, they are crazy people.\"<ref name=\"de la colina\">{{cite book|last=De La Colina|first=Jose|title=Objects of Desire: Conversations with Luis Bunuel|year=1994|publisher=Marsilio Publishers|isbn=978-0-941419-69-7|pages=80}}</ref>\n\nAfter parting with Epstein, Bu\u00f1uel worked as film critic for ''La Gaceta Literaria'' (1927) and ''Les Cahiers d'Art'' (1928).<ref name=talens />{{rp|p.30}} In the periodicals ''L'Amic de les Arts'' and ''La gaseta de les Arts'', he and Dal\u00ed carried on a series of \"call and response\" essays on cinema and theater, debating such technical issues as segmentation, [[Cut-up technique|d\u00e9coupage]], \"photogenia\" (founded on the [[Insert (filmmaking)|insert shot]]) and [[Film editing|rhythmic editing]].<ref name=\"dali collected writings\">{{cite book|last=Dal\u00ed|first=Salvador|title=The Collected Writings of Salvador Dal\u00ed|year=1998|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-56027-6|url=http://www.paolocirio.net/work/amazon-noir/amazon-noir-books/AMAZON-NOIR--The_Collected_Writings_of_Salvador_Dal%C3%AD--By--Salvador_Dali_Haim_N_Finkelstein--0521560276.pdf}}</ref>  He also collaborated with the celebrated writer [[Ram\u00f3n G\u00f3mez de la Serna]] on the script for what he hoped would be his first film, \"a story in six scenes\" called ''Los caprichos''.<ref name=talens />{{rp|pp.30\u201331}}  Through his involvement with ''Gaceta Literaria'', he helped establish Madrid's first cine-club and served as its inaugural chairman.<ref name=\"gomez mesa\">{{cite journal|last=G\u00f3mez Mesa|first=Luis.|title=La generaci\u00f3n cinematogr\u00e1fica del '27|journal=Cinema 2002|year=1978|issue= 37|pages=52\u201358}}</ref>\n\nIt was during this time that he met his future wife, Jeanne Rucar Lefebvre,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.redaragon.com/trebede/feb2000/articulo2.asp |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085450/http://www.redaragon.com/trebede/feb2000/articulo2.asp |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://elpais.com/diario/1994/11/07/agenda/784162802_850215.html</ref> a [[gymnastics]] teacher who had won a bronze medal at the 1924 Paris Olympics.<ref name=\"edwards 2009\">{{cite book |last1=Edwards |first1=Gwynne |title=Lorca, Bu\u00f1uel, Dal\u00ed: Forbidden Pleasures and Connected Lives |date=2009 |publisher=I.B. Tauris |location=London |isbn=978-1848850071 |page=86 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=CA34AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT72&lpg=PT72&dq=Olympic+bronze+medal+jeanne+rucar#v=onepage&q=Olympic%20bronze%20medal%20jeanne%20rucar&f=false |accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"max aub 2017\">{{cite book |last1=Aub |first1=Max |title=Conversations with Bunuel: Interviews with the Filmmaker, Family Members, Friends and Collaborators |date=2017 |publisher=McFarland |location=Jefferson, NC |isbn=978-1476668222 |page=154 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=1sm4DgAAQBAJ&pg=PA154&lpg=PA154&dq=Olympic+bronze+medal+jeanne+rucar#v=onepage&q=Olympic%20bronze%20medal%20jeanne%20rucar&f=false}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel courted her in a formal Aragonese manner, complete with a chaperone,<ref name=\"bbc world service\">{{cite web|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: In The Directors' Chair|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/arts/highlights/000919_bunuel.shtml|publisher=BBC World Service|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>  and they married in 1934<ref name=\"brain juice\" /> despite a warning by Jean Epstein when Bu\u00f1uel first proposed in 1930:  \"Jeanne, you are making a mistake... It's not right for you, don't marry him.\"<ref name=\"jeanne rucar\">{{cite book|last=Rucar de Bu\u00f1uel|first=Jeanne|title=Memoirs of a Woman Without a Piano: My Life with Luis Bu\u00f1uel|year=2010|publisher=Five Ties Publishing|location=Brooklyn|isbn=978-0-9794727-6-3|pages=43}}</ref> The two remained married throughout his life and had two sons, [[Juan Luis Bu\u00f1uel|Juan Luis]] and Rafael.<ref name=\"Centro Virtual Cervantes\">{{cite web|title=Rafael Bunuel, Escultor|url=http://cvc.cervantes.es/actcult/bunuel/entrevistas/r_bunuel.htm|website=Centro Virtual Cervantes|publisher=Instituto Cervantes|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> [[Diego Bu\u00f1uel]], filmmaker and host of the [[National Geographic Channel]]'s ''[[Don't Tell My Mother]]'' series, is their grandson.<ref name=\"nat geo\">{{cite web|title=Nat Geo Adventure|url=http://natgeoadventure.tv/int/user.aspx?userid=10703|publisher=NGC-UK Partnership|accessdate=23 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813071957/http://natgeoadventure.tv/int/User.aspx?userId=10703|archivedate=13 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====''Un Chien Andalou'' (1929)====\nAfter this apprenticeship, Bu\u00f1uel shot \nand directed a 16-minute short, ''[[Un Chien Andalou]]'', with [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. The film, financed by Bu\u00f1uel's mother,<ref name=\"brain juice andalusian dog\">{{cite web|title=Un chien Andalou (An Andalusian Dog, 1929) |url=http://www.brain-juice.com/cgi-bin/show_wok.cgi?p_id=136&w_id=391 |publisher=Brain-Juice.Com |accessdate=23 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061205212607/http://www.brain-juice.com/cgi-bin/show_wok.cgi?p_id=136&w_id=391 |archivedate=5 December 2006 }}</ref> consists of a series of startling images of a [[Freudian]] nature,<ref name=mansfield>{{cite book|last=Mansfield|first=Nick|title=Subjectivity: Theories of the Self from Freud to Haraway|year=2000|publisher=New York University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8147-5650-8|pages=36|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qBVh5gVTlC4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  starting with a woman's eyeball being sliced open with a razor blade. ''Un Chien Andalou'' was enthusiastically received by the burgeoning French [[surrealism|surrealist]] movement of the time<ref name=richardson>{{cite book|last=Richardson|first=Michael|title=Surrealism and Cinema|year=2006|publisher=Berg|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-84520-225-5|pages=27|url=https://books.google.com/?id=v1C6E_zJi6UC&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=chien+andalou+reception+surrealist#v=onepage&q=chien%20andalou%20reception%20surrealist}}</ref> and continues to be shown regularly in [[Film society|film societies]] to this day.<ref name=mathijs>{{cite book|last=Mathijs|first=Ernest|title=Cult Cinema|year=2011|publisher=Blackwell|location=West Sussex|isbn=978-1-4051-7374-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uPtuaV7IAt0C&pg=PT194&lpg=PT194&dq=chien+andalou+film+societies#v=onepage&q=chien%20andalou%20film%20societies}}</ref>\n\nThe script was written in six days at Dal\u00ed's home in [[Cadaqu\u00e9s]]. In a letter to a friend written in February 1929, Bu\u00f1uel described the writing process: \"We had to look for the plot line. Dal\u00ed said to me, 'I dreamed last night of ants swarming around in my hands', and I said, 'Good Lord, and I dreamed that I had sliced somebody or other's eye. There's the film, let's go and make it.'\"<ref name=etherington-smith>{{cite book|last=Etherington-Smith|first=Meredith|title=The Persistence of Memory: A Biography of Dal\u00ed|year=1995|publisher=Da Capo Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-306-80662-9|pages=94|url=https://books.google.com/?id=soncxLrkYX0C&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=We+had+to+look+for+the+plot+line.+Dal%C3%AD+said+to+me,+%22I+dreamed+last+night+of+ants+swarming+around+in+my+hands%27,+and+I+said,+%22Good+Lord,+and+I+dreamed+that+I+had+sliced+somebody+or+other%27s+eye.+There%27s+the+film,+let%27s+go+and+make+it.#v=onepage&q=We%20had%20to%20look%20for%20the%20plot%20line.%20Dal%C3%AD%20said%20to%20me%2C%20%22I%20dreamed%20last%20night%20of%20ants%20swarming%20around%20in%20my%20hands%27%2C%20and%20I%20said%2C%20%22Good%20Lord%2C%20and%20I%20dreamed%20that%20I%20had%20sliced%20somebody%20or%20other%27s%20eye.%20There%27s%20the%20film%2C%20let%27s%20go%20and%20make%20it.}}</ref>  In deliberate contrast to the approach taken by Jean Epstein and his peers, which was to never leave anything in their work to chance, with every aesthetic decision having a rational explanation and fitting clearly into the whole,<ref name=\"o'donoghue\">{{cite magazine|last=O'Donoghue|first=Darragh|title=On Some Motifs in Poe: Jean Epstein's La Chute de la maison Usher|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2004/feature-articles/la_chute_de_la_maison_usher/#b4|magazine=Senses of Cinema|accessdate=27 July 2012|date=12 February 2004}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel and Dal\u00ed made a cardinal point of eliminating all logical\nassociations.<ref name=Adamowicz>{{cite book|last=Adamowicz|first=Elza|title=Un Chien Andalou: (Luis Bu\u00f1uel and Salvador Dal\u00ed, 1929)|year=2010|publisher=I.B.Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1-84885-056-9|pages=8|url=http://www.ibtauris.com/Books/The%20arts/Film%20TV%20%20radio/Films%20cinema/Film%20guides%20%20reviews/~/media/Files/Extracts/Visual%20Culture/9781848850569.ashx}}</ref>   In Bu\u00f1uel's words: \"Our only rule was very simple: no idea or image that might lend itself to a rational explanation of any kind would be accepted. We had to open all doors to the irrational and keep only those images that surprised us, without trying to explain why\".<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.104}}\n[[File:Andr\u00e9 Breton 1924.jpg|thumb|right|190px|Andr\u00e9 Breton 1924<br/>Breton defined Surrealism as: \"Pure psychic automatism through which it is intended to express, either orally or in writing, or in any other way, the actual way thought works.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Breton|first=Andre|title=Manifestoes of Surrealism|year=1969|publisher=University of Michigan Press|location=Ann Arbor|isbn=978-0-472-06182-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/manifestoesofsur0000bret/page/3 3]|title-link=Manifestoes of Surrealism}}</ref>]]\nIt was Bu\u00f1uel's intention to shock and insult the intellectual bourgeoisie of his youth, later saying:  \"Historically the film represents a violent reaction against what in those days was called 'avant-garde,' which was aimed exclusively at artistic sensibility and the audience's reason.\"<ref name=\"art in cinema\">{{cite book|last=Bu\u00f1uel|first=Luis|title=\"Notes on the Making of Un Chien Andalou\", in Art in Cinema : documents toward a history of the film society|year=2006|publisher=Temple University Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=978-1-59213-425-0|pages=101\u2013102|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/32547313/Art-in-Cinema}}</ref>  Against his hopes and expectations, the film was a huge success amongst the French bourgeoisie,<ref name=koller>{{cite web|last=Koller|first=Michael|title=Un Chien Andalou|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2001/cteq/chien/|website=Senses of Cinema|publisher=Film Victoria|accessdate=23 July 2012|date=9 June 2011}}</ref> leading Bu\u00f1uel to exclaim in exasperation, \"What can I do about the people who adore all that is new, even when it goes against their deepest convictions, or about the insincere, corrupt press, and the inane herd that saw beauty or poetry in something which was basically no more than a desperate impassioned call for murder?\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bu\u00f1uel|first=Luis|title=Preface to the script for Un Chien Andalou|journal=La R\u00e9volution Surr\u00e9aliste|date=12 December 1929|volume=no. 12}}</ref>\n\nAlthough ''Un Chien Andalou'' is a [[silent film]], during the original screening (attended by the elite of the Parisian art world),  Bu\u00f1uel played a sequence of phonograph records which he switched manually while keeping his pockets full of stones with which to pelt anticipated hecklers.<ref name=\"maverick arts\">{{cite web|title=Un Chien Andalou|url=http://www.maverick-arts.com/cgi-bin/MAVERICK?&issue=340|publisher=Maverick Arts Magazine|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> After the premiere, Bu\u00f1uel and Dal\u00ed were granted formal admittance to the tight-knit community of Surrealists, led by poet [[Andr\u00e9 Breton]].<ref name=hoberman />\n\n====''L'Age d'Or'' (1930)====\nLate in 1929, on the strength of ''Un Chien Andalou'', Bu\u00f1uel and Dal\u00ed were commissioned to make another short film by [[Marie-Laure de Noailles|Marie-Laurie]] and [[Charles de Noailles]], owners of a private cinema on the [[Place des \u00c9tats-Unis]] and financial supporters of productions by Jacques Manuel, [[Man Ray]] and [[Pierre Chenal]].<ref name=\"bfi vol 3\" />{{rp|p.124}}  At first, the intent was that the new film be around the same length as ''Un Chien'', only this time with sound. But by mid-1930, the film had grown segmentally to an hour's duration.<ref name=\"bfi vol 3\" />{{rp|p.116}} Anxious that it was over twice as long as planned and at double the budget, Bu\u00f1uel offered to trim the film and cease production, but Noailles gave him the go-ahead to continue the project.<ref name=\"bfi vol 3\" />{{rp|p.116}}\n\nThe film, entitled ''[[L'Age d'Or]]'', was begun as a second collaboration with Dal\u00ed, but, while working on the scenario, the two had a falling out;  Bu\u00f1uel, who at the time had strong leftist sympathies,<ref name=gubern>{{cite book|last=Gubern|first=Rom\u00e1n and Paul Hammond|title=Luis Bunuel: The Red Years, 1929\u20131939|year=2012|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison|isbn=978-0-299-28474-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=elueEkeLL_oC&pg=PA427&lpg=PA427&dq=bunuel+espana+1936#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20espana%201936}}</ref> desired a deliberate undermining of all bourgeois institutions, while Dal\u00ed, who eventually supported the Spanish fascist [[Francisco Franco]] and various figures of the European aristocracy, wanted merely to cause a scandal through the use of various [[Scatology|scatological]] and anti-Catholic images.<ref name=\"film reference\">{{cite web|title=Marxism \u2013 European Cinema Before and After World War II|url=http://www.filmreference.com/encyclopedia/Independent-Film-Road-Movies/Marxism-EUROPEAN-CINEMA-BEFORE-AND-AFTER-WORLD-WAR-II.html|website=film reference|publisher=Advameg, Inc.|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> The friction between them was exacerbated when, at a dinner party in Cadaqu\u00e9s, Bu\u00f1uel tried to throttle Dal\u00ed's girlfriend, [[Gala Dal\u00ed|Gala]], the wife of Surrealist poet [[Paul \u00c9luard]].<ref name=thurlow>{{cite book|last=Thurlow|first=Clifford|title=Making Short Films: The Complete Guide from Script to Screen, 2nd ed|year=2008|publisher=Berg|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-84520-803-5|pages=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HX8XcfTw6KIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  In consequence, Dal\u00ed had nothing to do with the actual shooting of the film.<ref name=dali>{{cite book|last=Dal\u00ed|first=Salvador|title=The Secret Life of Salvador Dali|year=1942|publisher=Dial Press|location=New York}}</ref>{{rp|pp.276\u2013277}}   During the course of production, Bu\u00f1uel worked around his technical ignorance by filming mostly in sequence and using nearly every foot of film that he shot. Bu\u00f1uel invited friends and acquaintances to appear, gratis, in the film; for example, anyone who owned a tuxedo or a party frock got a part in the salon scene.<ref name=\"bfi vol 3\" />{{rp|p.116}}\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=left|width=25%|quote=\"A film called ''L'Age d'or'', whose non-existent artistic quality is an insult to any kind of technical standard, combines, as a public spectacle, the most obscene, disgusting and tasteless incidents. Country, family, and religion are dragged through the mud\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Bodin|first=Richard Pierre|title=Review of \"L'age d'Or\"|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=7 December 1930}}</ref> |source=Excerpt from Richard Pierre Bodin's review in ''[[Le Figaro]]'', 7 December 1930.}} ''L'Age d'Or'' was publicly proclaimed by Dal\u00ed as a deliberate attack on Catholicism, and this precipitated a much larger scandal than ''Un Chien Andalou''.<ref name=fanes>{{cite book|last=Fan\u00e9s|first=F\u00e8lix|title=Salvador Dali: The Construction of the Image|year=2007|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven|isbn=978-0-300-09179-3|pages=171|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bDpziok_K7gC&pg=PA171&lpg=PA171&dq=l%27age+d%27or+dali+dispute+bunuel#v=onepage&q=l%27age%20d%27or%20dali%20dispute%20bunuel}}</ref>  One early screening was taken over by members of the fascist [[Ligue des Patriotes|League of Patriots]] and the Anti-Jewish Youth Group, who hurled purple ink at the screen<ref name=\"ado kyrou\">{{cite book|last=Kyrou|first=Ado|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: an introduction|year=1963|publisher=Simon and Schuster|location=New York|pages=30}}</ref> and then vandalised the adjacent art gallery, destroying a number of valuable surrealist paintings.<ref name=moria>{{cite web|last=Scheib|first=Richard|title=L'Age d'Or|url=http://www.moria.co.nz/fantasy/lagedor.htm|publisher=Moria \u2013 The Science Fiction, Horror and Fantasy Film Review|accessdate=23 July 2012|date=15 December 2005}}</ref>  The film was banned by the Parisian police \"in the name of public order\".<ref name=\"Instituto Cervantes\">{{cite book|last=Instituto Cervantes|title=Bu\u00f1uel, 100 a\u00f1o: es peligroso asomarse al Interior/ Bu\u00f1uel, 100 Years: It' s Dangerous to Look Inside|year=2001|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8109-6219-4|pages=62}}</ref>  The de Noailles, both Catholics, were threatened with [[Excommunication#Roman Catholic Church|excommunication]] by [[Holy See|The Vatican]] because of the film's blasphemous final scene (which visually links [[Jesus Christ]] with the writings of the [[Marquis de Sade]]), so they made the decision in 1934 to withdraw all prints from circulation, and ''L'Age d'Or'' was not seen again until 1979, after their deaths,<ref name=laufer>{{cite web|last=Laufer|first=Laura|title=L'\u00c2ge d'or\" de Luis Bunuel|url=http://adagio.over-blog.fr/article-25951854.html|publisher=Le Centre Georges-Pompidou|accessdate=23 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615233326/http://adagio.over-blog.fr/article-25951854.html|archivedate=15 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> although a print was smuggled to England for private viewing.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lim|first1=Dennis|title=The Village Voice Film Guide: 50 Years of Movies from Classics to Cult Hits|date=2006|publisher=Wiley|location=New York|isbn=978-0471787815|page=7|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yHcIp0sa6MkC&pg=PA7&dq=l%27age+d%27or+banned#v=onepage&q=l'age%20d'or%20banned|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>  The furor was so great that the premiere of another film financed by the de Noailles, [[Jean Cocteau]]'s ''[[The Blood of a Poet]]'', had to be delayed for over two years until outrage over ''L'Age d'Or'' had died down.<ref name=burke>{{cite book|last=Burke|first=Carolyn|title=Lee Miller: A Life|year=2005|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-375-40147-3|pages=114|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PVmJOWev0p8C&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113&dq=Noailles+excommunication#v=onepage&q=Noailles%20excommunication}}</ref> To make matters worse, Charles de Noailles was forced to withdraw his membership from the [[Jockey-Club de Paris|Jockey Club]].<ref name=teitelbaum>{{cite book|last=Teitelbaum|first=Mo Amelia|title=The Stylemakers: Minimalism and Classic-Modernism 1915\u201345|year=2010|publisher=Philip Willson|location=London|isbn=978-0-85667-703-8|pages=102|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CuT3JqcH8hcC&pg=PA102&lpg=PA102&dq=charles+de+noailles+jockey+club#v=onepage&q=charles%20de%20noailles%20jockey%20club}}</ref>\n\nConcurrent with the ''[[succ\u00e8s de scandale]]'', both Bu\u00f1uel and the film's leading lady, [[Lya Lys]], received offers of interest from [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] and traveled to Hollywood at the studio's expense.<ref name=durgnat>{{cite book|last=Durgnat|first=Raymond|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|year=1968|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley}}</ref> While in the United States, Bu\u00f1uel associated with other celebrity expatriates including [[Sergei Eisenstein]], [[Josef Von Sternberg]], Jacques Feyder, [[Charles Chaplin]] and [[Bertolt Brecht]].<ref name=\"brain juice\" />  All that was required of Bu\u00f1uel by his loose-ended contract with MGM was that he \"learn some good American technical skills\",<ref name=walters>{{cite book|last=Walters|first=Rob|title=Spread Spectrum: Hedy Lamarr And the Mobile Phone|year=2006|publisher=BookSurge Publishing|location=Great Britain|isbn=978-1-4196-2129-1|pages=65|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ciuJ0UTCnmQC&pg=PA65&lpg=PA65&dq=luis+bunuel+MGM#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20MGM}}</ref> but, after being ushered off the first set he visited because the star, [[Greta Garbo]], did not welcome intruders, he decided to stay at home most of the time and only show up to collect his paycheck.<ref name=Doniol-Valcroze>{{cite journal|last=Doniol-Valcroze|first=Jacques|author2=Andr\u00e9 Bazin|title=Entretien avec Luis Bu\u00f1uel|journal=Cahiers du Cinema|date=July 1954|issue=37|pages=44\u201348}}</ref>  His only enduring contribution to MGM came when he served as an extra in ''La Fruta Amarga'', a Spanish-language remake of ''[[Min and Bill]]''.<ref name=jarvinen>{{cite book|last=Jarvinen|first=Lisa|title=The Rise of Spanish-Language Filmmaking: Out from Hollywood's Shadow, 1929\u20131939|year=2012|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=Piscataway NJ|isbn=978-0-8135-5328-3|pages=58|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W10o8udrUakC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>   When, after a few months at the studio, he was asked to watch [[Dailies|rushes]] of [[Lili Damita]] to gauge her Spanish accent, he refused and sent a message to studio boss [[Irving Thalberg]] stating that he was there as a Frenchman, not a Spaniard, and he \"didn't have time to waste listening to one of the whores\".<ref name=bazin>{{cite book|last=Bazin|first=Andre|title=Bu\u0146uel, Dreyer, Welles|year=1991|publisher=Editorial Fundamentos|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-245-0521-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=S4mCa7JzhI8C&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=luis+bunuel+damita#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20damita}}</ref>{{rp|p.18}}  He was back in Spain shortly thereafter.<ref name=durgnat />\n\n===Spain (1931\u20131937)===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Screen capture of classroom scene from Las Hurdas, Tierra Sin Pan.jpeg|299px|thumb|The classroom scene from ''Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan'' is an ironic statement of Bu\u00f1uel's Marxist sympathies.<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.59}}]]  -->\nSpain in the early 1930s was a time of political and social turbulence, a period of intense and bloody upheaval.<ref name=blinkhorn>{{cite book|last=Blinkhorn|first=Martin|title=Democracy And Civil War in Spain 1931\u20131939|year=1988|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-0-415-00699-6|pages=3\u201331|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CnJawWYdjNUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=spain+1931+upheaval#v=onepage&q=spain%201931%20upheaval}}</ref> Anarchists and [[Radical Socialist Republican Party|Radical Socialists]] sacked [[Monarchism|monarchist]] headquarters in [[Madrid]] and proceeded to set afire or otherwise wreck more than a dozen churches in the capital while similar revolutionary acts occurred in a score of other cities in southern and eastern Spain, in most cases with the acquiescence and occasionally with the assistance of the official Republican authorities.<ref name=payne>{{cite book|last=Payne|first=Stanley G.|title=A History of Spain and Portugal, V. 2|year=1976|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison|isbn=978-0-299-06284-2|pages=630|url=http://libro.uca.edu/payne2/payne25.htm}}</ref>\n\nBu\u00f1uel's future wife, Jeanne Rucar, recalled that during that period, \"he got very excited about politics and the ideas that were everywhere in pre-Civil War Spain\".<ref name=\"rucar de bunuel espanol\">{{cite book|last=Rucar de Bu\u00f1uel|first=Jeanne|title=Memorias de un mujer sin piano|year=1990|publisher=Alianza Editorial|location=Madrid|isbn=978-9683903907|pages=58}}</ref> In the first flush of his enthusiasm, Bu\u00f1uel joined the [[Communist Party of Spain]] (PCE) in 1931<ref name=gubern />{{rp|pp.85\u2013114}} though later in life he denied becoming a Communist.<ref name=aub>{{cite book|last=Aub|first=Max|title=Conversaciones con Bu\u00f1uel: Seguidas de 45 entrevistas con familiares, amigos y colaboradores del cineasta aragon\u00e9s |year=1985|publisher=Aguilar|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-03-09195-5}}</ref>{{rp|p.72}}\n\n[[File:Screen capture from Las Hurdas, Tierra Sin Pan.jpeg|left|thumb|269px|An early scene from ''Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan'' depicts a local wedding custom where the bridegroom tears the head off a rooster suspended by its feet from a scaffold above the main street of town.<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.57}}]] \nIn 1932, Bu\u00f1uel was invited to serve as film documentarian for the celebrated ''Mission Dakar-Djibouti'', the first large-scale French anthropological field expedition, which, led by [[Marcel Griaule]], unearthed some 3,500 African artifacts for the new [[Mus\u00e9e de l'Homme]].<ref name=ruoff-45>{{cite journal|last=Ruoff|first=Jeffrey|title=An Ethnographic Surrealist Film: Luis Bu\u00f1uel's Land Without Bread|url=https://www.dartmouth.edu/~jruoff/Articles/EthnographicSurrealist.htm|journal=Visual Anthropology Review|date=Spring\u2013Summer 1998|volume=14|issue=1|pages=45\u201357|accessdate=10 January 2016|doi=10.1525/var.1998.14.1.45}}</ref> Although he declined, the project piqued his interest in [[ethnography]]. After reading the academic study, ''Las Jurdes: \u00e9tude de g\u00e9ographie humaine'' (1927) by Maurice Legendre, he decided to make a film focused on [[peasant]] life in [[Extremadura]], one of Spain's poorest states.<ref name=margulies>{{cite book|last=Margulies|first=Ivone|title=Rites of Realism: Essays on Corporeal Cinema|year=2003|publisher=Duke University Press|location=Durham, NC|isbn=978-0-8223-3078-3|pages=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UP3Gf8KfsXwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  The film, called ''[[Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan]]'' (1933), was financed on a budget of 20,000 pesetas donated by a working-class [[anarchist]] friend named [[Ram\u00f3n Ac\u00edn]], who had won the money in a lottery.<ref name=weir>{{cite book|last=Weir|first=David|title=Anarchy & Culture: The Aesthetic Politics of Modernism|year=1997|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|location=Amherst| isbn=978-1-55849-083-3| pages=253 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=fRR8eWzRhbYC&pg=PA253&lpg=PA253&dq=las+hurdes+acin#v=onepage&q=las%20hurdes%20acin}}</ref> In the film, Bu\u00f1uel matches scenes of deplorable social conditions with narration that resembles travelogue commentary delivered by a detached-sounding announcer,<ref name=\"Harvard Film Archive\">{{cite web|title=Bu\u00f1uel: The Beginning and the End|url=http://hcl.harvard.edu/hfa/films/2011aprjun/bunuel.html|publisher=Harvard Film Archive|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> while the soundtrack thunders inappropriate music by [[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]].<ref name=\"Sloniowski\">{{cite journal |last1=Sloniowski |first1=Jeannette |title=\"Las Hurdes\" and the political efficacy of the grotesque |journal=Revue Canadienne d'\u00c9tudes cin\u00e9matographiques / Canadian Journal of Film Studies |date=Fall 1998 |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=30\u201348 |jstor=24402254 |doi=10.3138/cjfs.7.2.30 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"Though the material is organized with masterly skill, the very conception of 'art' here seems irrelevant.  It is the most profoundly disturbing film I have ever seen.\"<ref name=\"tony richardson\">{{cite book|last=Richardson|first=Tony|title=\"The Films of Luis Bu\u00f1uel,\" in The World of Luis Bu\u00f1uel, ed. Joan Mellen|year=1978|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-502398-5|pages=[https://archive.org/details/worldofluisbunue00luis/page/129 129]|url=https://archive.org/details/worldofluisbunue00luis/page/129}}</ref>  |source=Award-winning film director [[Tony Richardson]] on ''Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan''}}\n\n''Las Hurdes'' was banned by three successive Republican governments, definitively by [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] when he came to power.<ref name=Russell>{{cite web|last=Russell|first=Dominique|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2005/great-directors/bunuel/|website=Great Directors, Issue 35|publisher=Senses of Cinema|accessdate=31 July 2012|date=15 April 2005}}</ref> It is a film which continues to perplex viewers and resists easy categorization by film historians.<ref name=juhasz>{{cite book|last=Juhasz |first=Alexandra|title=F Is For Phony: Fake Documentary And Truth's Undoing|year=2006|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4251-9|pages=101|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TXaFokB-qx4C&dq=bunuel+las+hurdes+reading+ethnographic}}</ref>  ''Las Hurdes'' has been called one of the first examples of [[mockumentary]],<ref name=mockumentary>{{cite web|title=Week 16: Mockumentary|url=http://www.documentarysite.com/?p=101|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130121172356/http://www.documentarysite.com/?p=101|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 January 2013|website=Documentary film and video course syllabus.|publisher=Documentary Site|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref>  and has been labeled a \"surrealist documentary\", a term defined by critic Merc\u00e8 Ibarz as \"A multi-layered and unnerving use of sound, the juxtaposition of narrative forms already learnt from the written press, travelogues and new pedagogic methods, as well as a subversive use of photographed and filmed documents understood as a basis for contemporary propaganda for the masses\".<ref name=ibarz>{{cite book|last=Ibarz|first=Merc\u00e8|title=\"A Serious Experiment: Land Without Bread, 1933\", in Luis Bu\u00f1uel: New Readings. ed. Isabel Santaolalla and Peter William Evans|year=2004|publisher=British Film Institute|location=London|isbn=978-1-84457-003-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/luisbunuelnewrea0000unse/page/28 28]|url=https://archive.org/details/luisbunuelnewrea0000unse/page/28}}</ref> Catherine Russell has stated that in ''Las Hurdes'', Bu\u00f1uel was able to reconcile his political philosophy with his surrealist aesthetic, with surrealism becoming \"a means of awakening a marxist materialism in danger of becoming a stale orthodoxy\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Russell|first=Catherine|title=\"Surrealist Ethnography: Las Hurdes and the Documentary Unconscious\", in F Is for Phony: Fake Documentary And Truth's Undoing, edited by Alexandra Juhasz and Jesse Lerner|year=2006|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4251-9|page=112|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TXaFokB-qx4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Las Hurdes'' in 1933, Bu\u00f1uel worked in Paris in the [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbing]] department of [[Paramount Pictures]], but following his marriage in 1934, he switched to [[Warner Brothers]] because they operated dubbing studios in Madrid.<ref name=acevedo-munoz>{{cite book|last=Acevedo-Mu\u00f1oz|first=Ernesto R.|title=Bu\u00f1uel and Mexico: The Crisis of National Cinema|year=2003|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles| isbn=978-0-520-23952-4| url=https://books.google.com/?id=M-Q1iOxo00wC&dq=bunuel+filmofono}}</ref>{{rp|p.39}} A friend, Ricardo Urgoiti, who owned the commercial film company Film\u00f3fono, invited Bu\u00f1uel to [[Film producer|produce]] films for a mass audience. He accepted the offer, viewing it as an \"experiment\" as he knew the film industry in Spain was still far behind the technical level of Hollywood or Paris.<ref name=higginbotham>{{cite book|last=Higginbotham|first=Virginia|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|year=1979|publisher=Twayne Publishers|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8057-9261-4}}</ref>{{rp|p.56}} According to film historian Manuel Rotellar's interviews with members of the cast and crew of the Film\u00f3fono studios, Bu\u00f1uel's only condition was that his involvement with these pictures be completely anonymous, apparently for fear of damaging his reputation as a surrealist.<ref name=rotellar>{{cite journal|last=Rotellar|first=Manuel|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel en Film\u00f3fono|journal=Cinema 2002|year=1978|issue= 37|pages=36\u201340}}</ref> Rotellar insists, however, \"the truth is that it was Luis Bu\u00f1uel who directed the Film\u00f3fono productions\".<ref name=rotellar />{{rp|p.37}} [[Jos\u00e9 Luis S\u00e1enz de Heredia]], the titular director of two of the films created during Bu\u00f1uel's years as \"executive producer\" at Film\u00f3fono, recounted that it was Bu\u00f1uel who \"explained to me every morning what he wanted...We looked at the takes together and it was Bu\u00f1uel who chose the shots, and in editing, I wasn't even allowed to be present.\"<ref name=rotellar />{{rp|p.39}} Of the 18 films produced by Bu\u00f1uel during his years at Film\u00f3fono, the four that are believed by critical consensus to have been directed by him<ref name=mortimore>{{cite journal|last=Mortimore|first=Roger|title=Bu\u00f1uel, S\u00e1enz de Heredia, and Film\u00f3fono|journal=Sight and Sound|date=Summer 1975|volume=44|pages=180\u2013182}}</ref> are:\n<blockquote>\n* ''Don Quint\u00edn el amargao'' (Don Quintin the Sourpuss), 1935 \u2013 a musical based on a play by [[Carlos Arniches]],<ref name=\"fuentes, victor\">{{cite book|last=Fuentes|first=Victor|title=Los mundos de Bu\u00f1uel|year=2000|publisher=[[Ediciones Akal]]|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-460-1450-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Mdz1N3xs24IC&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57&dq=Don+Quint%C3%ADn+el+amargao+arniches+bunuel#v=onepage&q=Don%20Quint%C3%ADn%20el%20amargao%20arniches%20bunuel}}</ref> the first ''[[zarzuela]]'' (a type of Spanish opera) filmed in sound.<ref>{{cite web|title=Don Quint\u00edn el Amargao on AllMovie Don Quint\u00edn el Amargao (1935)|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/don-quint%C3%ADn-el-amargao-v235543|website=allmovie.com|publisher=AllMovie, a division of All Media Network|accessdate=2 November 2013}}</ref> \n* ''[[La hija de Juan Sim\u00f3n]]'' (Juan Sim\u00f3n's Daughter), 1935 \u2013 another musical and a major commercial success<ref name=bentley>{{cite book|last=Bentley|first=Bernard P. E.|title=A Companion to Spanish Cinema|year=2008|publisher=Tamesis|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|isbn=978-1-85566-176-9|pages=61|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M6kRqqwNMm0C&pg=PA61#v=onepage}}</ref>\n* ''\u00bfQui\u00e9n me quiere a m\u00ed?'' (Who Loves Me?), 1936 \u2013 a sentimental comedy that Bu\u00f1uel called \"my only commercial failure, and a pretty dismal one at that\".<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.144}}\n* ''\u00a1Centinela, alerta!'', (Sentry, Keep Watch!), 1937 \u2013 a comedy and Film\u00f3fono's biggest box-office hit.<ref name=bentley />\n</blockquote>\n\nDuring the [[Spanish Civil War]] (1936\u20131939), Bu\u00f1uel placed himself at the disposal of the Republican government.<ref name=\"an unspeakable betrayal\">{{cite book|last=Bu\u00f1uel|first=Luis|title=An Unspeakable Betrayal: Selected Writings of Luis Bu\u00f1uel|year=2002|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles|isbn=978-0-520-23423-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tK3KPgv34U8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.255}} The minister for foreign affairs sent him first to [[Geneva]] {{when|date=January 2016}} and then to Paris<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=elueEkeLL_oC&pg=PA260&lpg=PA260&dq=luis+bunuel+in+geneva#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20in%20geneva&f=false|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: The Red Years, 1929\u20131939, p.260|last=Gubern|first=Rom\u00e1n|last2=Hammond|first2=Paul|date=2012-01-04|publisher=University of Wisconsin Pres|isbn=9780299284732|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>{{when|date=January 2016}} for two years, with official responsibility for cataloging Republican propaganda films.<ref name=edwards />{{rp|p.6}} Besides the cataloguing, Bu\u00f1uel took left-wing tracts to Spain, did some occasional spying, acted as a bodyguard, and supervised the making of a documentary, entitled ''[[Espa\u00f1a 1936 (film)|Espa\u00f1a 1936]]''  in France and ''Espana leal, \u00a1en armas!'' in Spain, that covered the elections, the parades, the riots, and the war.<ref name=\"del olmo\">{{cite journal|last=del Olmo|first=F. Javier Ruiz|title=Language and Collective Identity in Bu\u00f1uel. Propaganda in the Film \"Espa\u00f1a 1936\" |journal=Comunicar| year=2010|volume=XVIII|issue=35|pages=69\u201376|doi=10.3916/C35-2010-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Espana leal, en armas|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b712e8a58|website=BFI Film Forever|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=6 August 2012}}</ref> In August 1936, [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]] was shot and killed by Nationalist militia.<ref name=beevor>{{cite book|last=Beevor|first=Antony|title=The Battle for Spain. The Spanish Civil War 1936\u20131939|year=2006|publisher=Penguin Books|location=London|isbn=978-0-14-303765-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/battleforspainsp00anto/page/100 100]|url=https://archive.org/details/battleforspainsp00anto/page/100}}</ref> According to his son, [[Juan Luis Bu\u00f1uel|Juan Luis]], Bu\u00f1uel rarely talked about Lorca but mourned the poet's untimely death throughout his life.<ref name=ehrlich>{{cite magazine|last=Ehrlich|first=Linda C.|title=A Bu\u00f1uel Scrapbook: The Last Script: Remembering Luis Bu\u00f1uel (1) and Calanda: 40 Years Later| url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2009/feature-articles/last-script-bunuel-calanda/|magazine=Senses of Cinema|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=9 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nBu\u00f1uel essentially functioned as the coordinator of film propaganda for the Republic, which meant that he was in a position to examine all film shot in the country and decide what sequences could be developed and distributed abroad.<ref name=faber>{{cite web|last=Faber|first=Sebastiaan|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel, chameleon: Revelations from the \"Red Decade\" |url=http://www.albavolunteer.org/2011/12/luis-bunuel-chameleon-revelations-from-the-%E2%80%9Cred-decade%E2%80%9D/|website=The Volunteer|publisher=Abraham Lincoln Brigade Archives (ALBA)|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> The Spanish Ambassador suggested that Bu\u00f1uel revisit Hollywood where he could give technical advice on films being made there about the Spanish Civil War,<ref name=edwards />{{rp|p.6}} so in 1938, he and his family traveled to the United States using funds obtained from his old patrons, the Noailles.<ref name=hoberman>{{cite journal|last=Hoberman|first=J.|title=A Charismatic Chameleon: On Luis Bu\u00f1uel|journal=The Nation|date=14 May 2012|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/167559/charismatic-chameleon-luis-bunuel#|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> Almost immediately upon his arrival in America, however, the war ended and the [[Motion Picture Association of America|Motion Picture Producers and Distributors Association of America]] discontinued making films on the Spanish conflict.<ref name=\"robert cole\">{{cite book|last=Cole|first=Robert|title=Propaganda, Censorship And Irish Neutrality in the Second World War|year=2006|publisher=Edinburgh University Press |location=Edinburgh|  isbn=978-0-7486-2277-1|pages=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wu_bOQiXGs4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> According to Bu\u00f1uel's wife, returning to Spain was impossible since the Fascists had seized power,<ref name=\"rucar de bunuel espanol\" />{{rp|p.63\u201364}} so Bu\u00f1uel decided to stay in the U.S. indefinitely, stating that he was \"immensely attracted by the American naturalness and sociability\".<ref name=\"an unspeakable betrayal\" />{{rp|p.255}}\n\n===United States (1938\u20131945)===\n[[File:Museum of modern art airways to peace exhibition 1943.jpg|295px|thumb|Museum of Modern Art, 1943]]\nReturning to Hollywood in 1938, he was befriended by Frank Davis, an MGM producer and member of the [[Communist Party USA]],<ref name=gubern />{{rp|p.349}} who placed Bu\u00f1uel on the payroll of ''Cargo of Innocence'', a film about Spanish refugee mothers and children fleeing from [[Bilbao]] to the USSR.<ref name=\"edwards - lorca etc.\">{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Gwynne|title=Lorca, Bu\u00f1uel, Dal\u00ed: forbidden pleasures and connected lives|year=2009|publisher=I. B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1-84885-007-1|pages=194}}</ref>  The project was shelved precipitately when another Hollywood film about the Spanish Civil War, ''[[Blockade (1938 film)|Blockade]]'', was met with disfavor by the [[National Legion of Decency|Catholic League of Decency]].<ref name=manchel>{{cite book|last=Manchel|first=Frank|title=Film Study: An Analytical Bibliography, Volume 1|year=1990|publisher=Associated University Presses|location=Cranbury NJ|isbn=978-0-8386-3186-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/filmstudyanalyti0000manc/page/219 219\u2013220]|url=https://archive.org/details/filmstudyanalyti0000manc/page/219}}</ref>  In the words of biographer Ruth Brandon, Bu\u00f1uel and his family \"lived from one unsatisfactory crumb of work to another\" because he \"had none of the arrogance and pushiness essential for survival in Hollywood\".<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.358}}  He just wasn't flamboyant enough to capture the attention of Hollywood decision makers, in the opinion of film composer [[George Antheil]]: \"Inasmuch as [Bu\u00f1uel], his wife and his little boy seemed to be such absolutely normal, solid persons, as totally un-Surrealist in the Dal\u00ed tradition as one could possibly imagine.\"<ref name=baxter>{{cite book|last=Baxter|first=John|title=Bu\u00f1uel|year=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7867-0619-8}}</ref>{{rp|p.172}} For the most part, he was snubbed by many of the people in the film community whom he met during his first trip to America,<ref>{{cite news|title=A documentary shows the most bitter of Bu\u00f1uel and intimate portrait|url=http://www.deltaworld.org/cinema/A-documentary-shows-the-most-bitter-of-Bu-uel-and-intimate-portrait/|accessdate=8 August 2012|newspaper=The Delta World.|date=13 July 2012}}</ref> although he was able to sell some gags to Chaplin for his film ''[[The Great Dictator]]''.<ref name=taylor />{{rp|p.213}}\n\nIn desperation, to market himself to independent producers, he composed a 21-page autobiography, a section of which, headed \"My Present Plans\", outlined proposals for two documentary films:\n* \"The Primitive Man\", which would depict \"the terrible struggle of primitive man against a hostile universe, how the world appeared, ''how they saw it'', what ideas they had on love, on death, on fraternity, how and why religion is born\", [italics in original]\n* \"Psycho-Pathology\", which would \"expose the origin and development of different psychopathic diseases... Such a documental film, apart from its great scientific interest, could depict on screen a ''New Form of Terror'' or its synonym ''Humour''.\" [italics in original]<ref name=\"an unspeakable betrayal\" />{{rp|p.257}}\n\nNobody showed any interest and Bu\u00f1uel realized that staying in Los Angeles was futile, so he traveled to New York to see if he could change his fortunes.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.174}}\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=left|width=25%|quote=\"Luis Bu\u00f1uel was there, with his thyroid eyes, the moles on his chin which I remember from so long ago when we first saw the surrealist films in the [[Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que Fran\u00e7aise|Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que]],... and as he talked I remember thinking that his paleness was most appropriate for someone who spent his life in dark projection rooms... He has a sharp humor, a bitter sarcasm, and at the same time towards women a gentle, special smile\".<ref name=Nin>{{cite book|last=Nin|first=Anais|title=Diary of Ana\u00efs Nin Volume 3 1939\u20131944: Vol. 3 (1939\u20131944)|year=1969|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|location=New York|isbn=978-0-15-626027-5|pages=109|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=igytZ9t8jsAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>   |source=[[Ana\u00efs Nin]], in her diary entry on encountering Bu\u00f1uel when he was working at MoMA}}\nIn New York, Antheil introduced Bu\u00f1uel to [[Iris Barry]], chief curator of film at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA).<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.360}}  Barry talked Bu\u00f1uel into joining a committee formed to help educate those within the U.S. government who might not have appreciated fully the effectiveness of film as a medium of propaganda. Bu\u00f1uel was hired to produce a shortened version of [[Leni Riefenstahl]]'s ''[[Triumph of the Will]]'' (1935) as a demonstration project.<ref name=trimborn>{{cite book|last=Trimborn|first=J\u00fcrgen|title=Leni Riefenstahl: A Life|year=2007|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|location=New York|isbn=978-0-374-18493-3|pages=123\u2013124|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4IFvjEArNg8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> The finished product was a compilation of scenes from Riefenstahl's [[Nazism|Nazi]] epic with [[Hans Bertram]]'s ''Feuertaufe''.<ref name=higginbotham />{{rp|p.58}} Bu\u00f1uel stayed at MoMA to work for the [[Office of the Coordinator of Inter-American Affairs]] (OCIAA) as part of a production team that would gather, review and edit films intended as anti-fascist propaganda to be distributed in [[Latin America]] by American embassies.<ref name=schreiber>{{cite book|last=Schreiber|first=Rebecca M.|title=Cold War Exiles in Mexico: U.S. Dissidents and the Culture of Critical Resistance|year=2008|publisher=Univ of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4308-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4O1AElNqAZYC&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72&dq=bunuel+museum+of+modern+art#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20museum%20of%20modern%20art}}</ref>{{rp|p.72}}  While being vetted for the job at the OCIAA, upon being asked if he was a Communist, he replied: \"I am a Republican,\" and, apparently, the interviewer did not realize that Bu\u00f1uel was referring to the Spanish socialist coalition government, not the American political party.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.180}}  Describing Bu\u00f1uel's work at MoMA, his friend, composer Gustavo Pittaluga, stated: \"Luis created maybe 2,000 remarkable works.  We were sent anodyne documentaries, often extremely feeble primary materials, which the Museum team turned into marvellous films.  And not just Spanish versions, but also Portuguese, French and English... He would ''create'' a good documentary through editing.\" [italics in original]<ref name=aranda>{{cite book|last=Aranda|first=Francisco|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: A Critical Biography|year=1976|publisher=Da Capo Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-306-70754-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/luisbunuelcritic0000aran}}</ref>{{rp|p.124}}\n\nIn 1942, Bu\u00f1uel applied for American citizenship, because he anticipated that MoMA would soon be put under federal control.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.183}}  But that same year, Dal\u00ed published his autobiography, ''[[The Secret Life of Salvador Dal\u00ed]]'', in which he made it clear that he had split with Bu\u00f1uel because the latter was a Communist and an [[atheist]].<ref name=navarro>{{cite book|last=Navarro|first=Vicente|title=\"The Jackboot of Dada\", in Serpents in the Garden: Liaisons with Culture & Sex, ed. Alexander Cockburn and Jeffery St. Clair|year=2004|publisher=AK Press|location=Oakland, CA|isbn=978-1-902593-94-4|pages=148\u2013149|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ShbksjUcH5YC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> News of this reached [[Francis Spellman|Archbishop Spellman]], who angrily confronted Barry with the question: \"Are you aware that you are harbouring in this Museum the Antichrist, the man who made a blasphemous film ''L'Age d'Or''?\"<ref name=taylor>{{cite book|last=Taylor|first=John Russell|title=Strangers in paradise: the Hollywood \u00e9migr\u00e9s, 1933\u20131950|year=1983|publisher=Holt, Rinehart & Winston|location=New York|isbn=978-0-03-061944-1|url=https://archive.org/details/strangersinparad00tayl}}</ref>{{rp|p.214}}  At the same time, a campaign on the part of Hollywood, through its industry trade paper, the ''[[Motion Picture Herald]]'', to undermine the MoMA film unit resulted in a 66% reduction in the department's budget and Bu\u00f1uel felt himself compelled to resign.<ref name=\"robert sitton\">{{cite book|last1=Sitton|first1=Robert|title=Lady in the Dark: Iris Barry and the Art of Film|date=2014|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0231165785|page=317|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fyMZBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=16 January 2015}}</ref>  In 1944, he returned to Hollywood for the third time, this time as Spanish Dubbing Producer for [[Warner Brothers]].<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.190}} Before leaving New York, he confronted Dal\u00ed at his hotel, the [[Sherry Netherland Hotel|Sherry Netherland]], to tell the painter about the damage his book had done and then shoot him in the knee.<ref name=\"don harrison\">{{cite web|last=Harrison|first=Don|title=15 Footnotes on the Moustache of Bunuel \u2013 Episodes of Luis|url=http://www.naderlibrary.com/bunuel15footnotesmoustache.htm|publisher=American Buddha|accessdate=21 August 2012}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel did not carry out the violent part of his plan. Dal\u00ed explained himself by saying: \"I did not write my book to put YOU on a pedestal. I wrote it to put ME on a pedestal\".<ref name=\"don harrison\" />\n\n[[File:Man Ray 1934.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Man Ray \u2013 a friend from Bu\u00f1uel's surrealist period and collaborator on unrealized Hollywood projects]]\nBu\u00f1uel's first dubbing assignment on returning to Hollywood was ''[[My Reputation]]'', a [[Barbara Stanwyck]] picture which became ''El Que Diran'' in Bu\u00f1uel's hands.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.190}}  In addition to his dubbing work, Bu\u00f1uel attempted to develop a number of independent projects:\n* In collaboration with an old friend from his Surrealist days, [[Man Ray]], he worked on a scenario called ''The Sewers of Los Angeles'', which took place on a mountain of excrement close to a highway and a dust basin.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.129}}\n* With his friend, [[Jos\u00e9 Rubia Barcia]], he co-wrote a screenplay called ''La novia de medianoche'' (The Midnight Bride), a gothic thriller, which lay dormant until it was filmed by Antonio Sim\u00f3n in 1997.<ref>{{cite book|last=Barcia|first=Jos\u00e9 Rubia|title=Con Luis Bu\u00f1uel en Hollywood y despu\u00e9s|year=1992|publisher=Edici\u00f3s do Castro|location=Sada, A Coru\u00f1a|isbn=978-84-7492-582-1|pages=105\u2013160}}</ref>\n* He continued working on a screenplay called \"Goya and the Duchess of Alba\", a treatment he had started as early as 1927, with the actor/producer [[Flori\u00e1n Rey]] and cameraman [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Beltr\u00e1n]], and then resuscitated in 1937 as a project for Paramount.<ref>{{cite book|last=S\u00e1nchez Vidal|first=Agust\u00edn|title=G\u00f3ngora, Bu\u00f1uel, Spanish Avant-Garde and Centenary of Goya's Death, in The Spanish Avant-Garde, ed. Derek Harris|year=1995|publisher=Manchester University Press|location=Manchester|isbn=978-0-7190-4342-0|pages=117|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cQbpAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>\n* In his 1982 autobiography ''Mon Dernier soupir'' (''My Last Sigh'', 1983, ''My Last Breath'', 1994), Bu\u00f1uel wrote that at the request of director [[Robert Florey]], he submitted a treatment of a scene about a disembodied hand, which was later included in the movie ''[[The Beast with Five Fingers]]'' (1946), starring [[Peter Lorre]], without acknowledgement of Bu\u00f1uel's contribution or payment of any compensation.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.189}}  However, Brian Taves, film scholar and archivist with the [[Library of Congress]], has challenged the truth of this claim.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Taves|first=Brian|title=Whose Hand? Correcting a Bu\u00f1uel myth|journal=Sight and Sound|date=Summer 1987|volume=56|issue=3|pages=210\u2013211}}</ref>\n\nIn 1945, Bu\u00f1uel's contract with Warner Brothers expired, and he decided not to renew it in order, as he put it: \"to realize my life's ambition for a year: to do nothing\".<ref name=\"bazin cinema of cruelty\">{{cite book|last=Bazin|first=Andr\u00e9|title=The cinema of cruelty: from Bu\u00f1uel to Hitchcock|year=1982|publisher=Seaver Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0-86579-018-6|pages=89}}</ref>  While his family enjoyed themselves at the beach, Bu\u00f1uel spent much of his time in [[Antelope Valley]] with new acquaintances writer [[Aldous Huxley]] and sculptor [[Alexander Calder]], from whom he rented a house.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.130}}\n\nIn his autobiography, in a chapter about his second spell in America, Bu\u00f1uel states that \"[o]n several occasions, both American and European producers have suggested that I tackle a film version of [[Malcolm Lowry]]'s ''[[Under the Volcano]]''\",  but that after reading the book many times as well as eight different screenplays he was unable to come up with a solution for the cinema.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.194}} [[Under the Volcano (film)|The movie]] was eventually made in 1984 by [[John Huston]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Maslin |first1=Janet |title=Under the Volcano |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/06/13/movies/film-huston-s-under-the-volcano.html |website=New York Times |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Intermediate years (1946\u20131961)===\n\n====Mexico (1946\u20131953)====\n\nThe following year, an old friend, producer [[Denise Batcheff|Denise Tual]], the widow of [[Pierre Batcheff]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Pallister|first=Janis L.|title=French-Speaking Women Film Directors: A Guide|year=1997|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|location=Madison NJ|isbn=978-0-8386-3736-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/frenchspeakingwo0000pall/page/93 93]|url=https://archive.org/details/frenchspeakingwo0000pall/page/93}}</ref>  the [[leading man]] in ''Un Chien Andalou'', proposed that she and Bu\u00f1uel adapt Lorca's play ''[[The House of Bernarda Alba|La casa de Bernarda Alba]]'' for production in Paris.<ref name=camacho>{{cite book|last=Camacho|first=Enrique, Javier P\u00e9rez Bazo and Manuel Rodr\u00edguez Blanco|title=Bu\u00f1uel, 100 a\u00f1os : es peligroso asomarse al interior = Bu\u00f1uel, 100 years : it's dangerous to look inside|year=2001|publisher=Instituto Cervantes / The Museum of Modern Art|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8109-6219-4|pages=83}}</ref>  As it turned out, though, before they could both make their way to Europe, they encountered problems in securing the rights from Lorca's family.<ref name=bazin />{{rp|p.21}}  While in Mexico City, on a stopover, they had asked \u00d3scar Dancigers, a Russian \u00e9migr\u00e9 producer active in Mexico, for financing.<ref name=camacho />  Dancigers ran an independent production company that specialized in assisting U.S. film studios with on-location shooting in Mexico, but following World War&nbsp;II, he had lost his connection with Hollywood due to his being blacklisted as a Communist.<ref name=schreiber />{{rp|p.73}}  Although Dancigers wasn't enthusiastic about the Lorca project, he did want to work with Bu\u00f1uel and persuaded the Spanish director to make a film for him.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.197}}\n\n[[File:Libertad Lamarque.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Libertad Lamarque, star of Bu\u00f1uel's first Mexican film. Bu\u00f1uel was said to have held a long-time grudge against Lamarque because the actress was able to bring him to tears when he viewed a \"corny melodrama\" which she had made in Argentina: \"How could I let myself cry over such an absurd, grotesque, ridiculous scene?\"<ref name=\"bill krohn\">{{cite book|last1=Krohn|first1=Bill and Paul Duncan|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Cinema 1900\u20131983|date=2005|publisher=Taschen|location=Cologne|isbn=978-3822833759}}</ref>{{rp|p.147}}]]\nThe  [[Golden Age of Mexican cinema]] was peaking in the mid-to-late 1940s, at just the time Bu\u00f1uel was connecting with Dancigers.<ref name=fein>{{cite journal|last=Fein|first=Seth|title=Hollywood, U.S.-Mexican Relations, and the Devolution of the \"Golden Age\" of Mexican Cinema|journal=Film-Historia|year=1994|volume=IV|issue=2|pages=103\u2013135|url=http://161.116.18.149/bibliotecaDigital/cinema/filmhistoria/Art.Fein.pdf|accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref>  Movies represented Mexico's third largest industry by 1947, employing 32,000 workers, with 72 film producers who invested 66 million pesos (approximately U.S. $13 million) per year, four active studios with 40 million pesos of invested capital, and approximately 1,500 theaters throughout the nation, with about 200 in Mexico City alone.<ref name=huer>{{cite book|last=Huer|first=Federico|title=La industria cinematogr\u00e1fica mexicana|year=1964|publisher=Policrom\u00eda|location=M\u00e9xico. DF|pages=48\u201369}}</ref>  For their first project, the two men selected what seemed like a sure-fire success, ''[[Gran Casino]]'', a musical [[period piece]] set in [[Tampico]] during the boom years of oil exploitation, starring two of the most popular entertainers in Latin America: [[Libertad Lamarque]], an Argentine actress and singer, and [[Jorge Negrete]], a Mexican singer and leading man in [[Charro#Other uses|\"charro\" films]].<ref name=\"Mira Nouselles\">{{cite book|last=Mira Nouselles|first=Alberto|title=Historical Dictionary of Spanish Cinema|year=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0-8108-5957-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iZm8wWNXeioC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.64}} Bu\u00f1uel recalled:  \"I kept them singing all the time\u2014a competition, a championship\".<ref name=aranda />{{rp|pp.130\u2013131}}\n\nThe film was not successful at the box office, with some even calling it a fiasco.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Est\u00e8ve|first=Michel|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|journal=Etudes Cin\u00e9matographiques|year=1963|issue=20\u201321|pages=82}}</ref> Different reasons have been given for its failure with the public; for some, Bu\u00f1uel was forced to make concessions to the bad taste of his stars, particularly Negrete,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mart\u00ednez Herranz|first=Amparo|title=Gran Casino de Luis Bu\u00f1uel|journal=Artigrama|year=2002|issue=17|pages=525}}</ref> others cite Bu\u00f1uel's rusty technical skills<ref name=\"fuentes discourse\">{{cite journal|last=Fuentes|first=V\u00edctor|title=Bu\u00f1uel's Cinematic Narrative and the Latin American New Novel|journal=Discourse|date=Winter\u2013Spring 2004  |volume=26|issue=1 & 2|pages=92}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Garc\u00eda Riera|first=Emilio|title=Historia documental del cine mexicano. Vol. 3|year=1969|publisher=Era|location=Mexico|isbn=978-968-895-343-3|pages=90}}</ref>  and lack of confidence after so many years out of the director's chair,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Charity|first=Tom|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Two-Disc Collector's Edition|journal=Sight and Sound|date=December 2007|volume=17|issue=12|pages=105}}</ref> while still others speculate that Mexican audiences were tiring of genre movies, called \"churros\", that were perceived as being cheaply and hastily made.<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.48}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mraz|first=John|title=Mexican Cinema: Of churros and charros|journal=Jump Cut|date=February 1984|issue=29|pages=23|url=http://www.ejumpcut.org/archive/onlinessays/JC29folder/MexFilmBook.html}}</ref>\n\nThe failure of ''Gran Casino'' sidelined Bu\u00f1uel, and it was over two years before he had the chance to direct another picture.<ref>{{cite book|last=Paranagu\u00e1|first=Paulo Antonio|title=Mexican Cinema|year=1995|publisher=British Film Institute|location=London|isbn=978-0-85170-516-3|pages=202|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U7wuAAAAYAAJ&q=bunuel+gran+casino+failure&dq=bunuel+gran+casino+failure}}</ref>  According to Bu\u00f1uel, he spent this time \"scratching my nose, watching flies and living off my mother's money\",<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.199}} but he was actually somewhat more industrious than that may sound.  With the husband/wife team of Janet and [[Luis Alcoriza]], he wrote the scenario for ''Si usted no puede, yo s\u00ed'', which was filmed in 1950 by [[Juli\u00e1n Soler]].<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.203}} He also continued developing the idea for a surrealistic film called ''Ilegible, hijo de flauta'', with the poet [[Juan Larrea (poet)|Juan Larrea]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gurney|first=Robert|title=\"Juan Larrea and the Film Bu\u00f1uel Did Not Make\", in Companion to Spanish Surrealism, ed. Robert Havard|year=2004|publisher=Tamesis Books|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|isbn=978-1-85566-104-2|pages=49|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jYOIwLxBLfMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> Dancigers pointed out to him that there was currently a vogue for films about street urchins, so Bu\u00f1uel scoured the back streets and slums of Mexico City in search of material, interviewing social workers about street gang warfare and murdered children.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|pp.203\u2013204}}\n\nDuring this period, Dancigers was busy producing films for the actor/director [[Fernando Soler]], one of the most durable of Mexican film personalities, having been referred to as the \"national paterfamilias\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Stock|first=Ann Marie|title=Framing Latin American Cinema: Contemporary Critical Perspectives|year=1997|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-2972-5|pages=213|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2VFTpFmrV5cC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>   Although Soler typically preferred to direct his own films, for their latest collaboration, ''[[El Gran Calavera]]'', based on a play by Adolfo Torrado, he decided that doing both jobs would be too much trouble, so he asked Dancigers to find someone who could be trusted to handle the technical aspects of the directorial duties.<ref name=\"cine mexicano\">{{cite web|title=El gran calavera (1949)|url=http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/gran_calavera.html|website=M\u00e1s de Cien A\u00f1os de Cine Mexicano|publisher=Cine Club \u2013 Cine Mexicano|accessdate=16 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421140309/http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/gran_calavera.html|archive-date=21 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel welcomed the opportunity, stating that: \"I amused myself with the montage, the constructions, the angles... All of that interested me because I was still an apprentice in so-called 'normal' cinema.\"<ref name=\"cine mexicano\" />  As a result of his work on this film, he developed a technique for making films cheaply and quickly by limiting them to 125 shots.<ref name=schreiber />{{rp|p.73}} ''El Gran Calavera'' was completed in 16 days at a cost of 400,000 pesos (approximately $46,000 US at 1948 exchange rates).<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.52}}  The picture has been described as \"a hilarious screwball send-up of the Mexican [[nouveau riche]]... a wild roller coaster of mistaken identity, sham marriages and misfired suicides\",<ref name =\"Harvard.edu\" /> and it was a big hit at the box office in Mexico.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dent|first=David W.|title=Encyclopedia of Modern Mexico|year=2002|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0-8108-4291-5|pages=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HkiJlXXbAy4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  In 2013, the picture was re-made by Mexican director Gary Alazraki under the title ''[[The Noble Family]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=de las Carreras|first1=Mar\u00eda Elena|title=El gran calavera (The Great Madcap, 1949), directed by Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=https://www.laconservancy.org/sites/default/files/files/GranCalavera_EssayDeLasCarreras.pdf|publisher=The Los Angeles Conservancy|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>  In 1949, Bu\u00f1uel renounced his Spanish citizenship to become a naturalized Mexican.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pulver|first=Andrew|title=A short history of Spanish cinema|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2011/mar/29/short-history-spanish-cinema|work=newEurope|publisher=Guardian News and Media|accessdate=1 September 2012|location=London|date=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe commercial success of ''El Gran Calavera'' enabled Bu\u00f1uel to redeem a promise he had extracted from Dancigers, which was that if Bu\u00f1uel could deliver a money-maker, Dancigers would guarantee \"a degree of freedom\" on the next film project.<ref name=Doniol-Valcroze />  Knowing that Dancigers was uncomfortable with experimentalism, especially when it might affect the bottom line, Bu\u00f1uel proposed a commercial project titled ''\u00a1Mi huerfanito jefe!'', about a juvenile street vendor who can't sell his final lottery ticket, which ends up being the winner and making him rich.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los olvidados (1950)|url=http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/olvidados.html|website=Las 100 mejores pel\u00edculas del cine mexicano: 2|publisher=Cine Club \u2013 Cine Mexicano|accessdate=20 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717025021/http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/olvidados.html|archive-date=17 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Dancigers was open to the idea, but instead of a \"''[[feuilleton]]''\", he suggested making \"something rather more serious\".<ref name=\"ibanez and palacio\">{{cite book|last=Iba\u00f1ez|first=Juan Carlos and Manuel Palacio|title=\"Los Olvidados/The Young and the Damned\", in The Cinema of Latin America, ed. Alberto Elena and Marina D\u00edaz L\u00f3pez|year=2003|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-1-903364-84-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hx5VfnjrGLUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.60}}  During his recent researches through the slums of Mexico City, Bu\u00f1uel had read a newspaper account of a twelve-year-old boy's body being found on a garbage dump, and this became the inspiration, and final scene, for the film, called ''[[Los olvidados]]''.<ref name=\"de la colina\" />{{rp|pp.53\u201354}}\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"The world doesn't work like Hollywood told us it does, and Bu\u00f1uel knew well that poverty's truths could not be window-dressed in any way. This film continues to provoke reactions for its unapologetic portrayal of life without hope or trust. It stands out among Bu\u00f1uel's works as the moment when he broke surface and bellowed, before sinking back into the world of the privileged where his surreal view most loved to play.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pierre|first=DBC|title=The lost boys|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/feb/17/film|work=The Guardian, 16 February 2007|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|accessdate=20 August 2012|location=London|date=16 February 2007}}</ref>  |source=[[Booker Prize]] winning author [[DBC Pierre]] on ''Los olvidados''}}\nThe film tells the story of a street gang of children who terrorize their impoverished neighborhood, at one point brutalizing a blind man<ref>{{cite book|last=Villarreal|first=Rachel Kram|title=Gladiolas for the Children of Sanchez: Ernesto P. Uruchurtu's Mexico City, 1950\u20141968|year=2008|location=Ann Arbor MI|pages=31|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LlRhRyTNbqMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|isbn=9781109029550}}</ref> and at another assaulting a legless man who moves around on a dolly, which they toss down a hill.<ref name=\"ed gonzalez\">{{cite magazine|last=Gonzalez|first=Ed|title=Los Olvidados ****|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/los-olvidados/208|magazine=Slant Magazine|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref>  Film historian Carl J. Mora has said of ''Los olvidados'' that the director: \"visualized poverty in a radically different way from the traditional forms of Mexican melodrama.  Bu\u00f1uel's street children are not 'ennobled' by their desperate struggle for survival; they are in fact ruthless predators who are not better than their equally unromanticized victims\".<ref name=mora>{{cite book|last=Mora|first=Carl J.|title=Mexican Cinema: Reflections of a Society|year=1982|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles|isbn=978-0-520-04304-6|url=https://archive.org/details/mexicancinemaref00mora}}</ref>{{rp|p.91}}  The film was made quickly (18 days) and cheaply (450,000 pesos), with Bu\u00f1uel's fee being the equivalent of $2,000.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|pp.210\u2013211}}  During filming, a number of members of the crew resisted the production in a variety of ways:  one technician confronted Bu\u00f1uel and asked why he didn't make a \"real\" Mexican movie \"rather than a miserable picture like this one\",<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p.200}} the film's hairdresser quit on the spot over a scene in which the protagonist's mother refuses to give him food (\"In Mexico, no mother would say that to her son.\"),<ref name=\"mraz nacho lopez\">{{cite book|last=Mraz|first=John|title=Nacho Lopez, Mexican Photographer|year=2003|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4047-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e4f6kkFbbJQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.99}} another staff member urged Bu\u00f1uel to abandon shooting on a \"garbage heap\", noting that there were many \"lovely residential neighborhoods like [[Lomas de Chapultepec|Las Lomas]]\" that were available,<ref name=\"mraz nacho lopez\" />{{rp|p.99}} while Pedro de Urdimalas, one of the scriptwriters, refused to allow his name in the credits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pedro de Urdimalas|url=http://www.sacm.org.mx/archivos/biografias.asp?txtSocio=08285&offset=0|publisher=Sociedad de Autores y Compositores de M\u00e9xico (SACM)|accessdate=21 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506103309/http://www.sacm.org.mx/archivos/biografias.asp?txtSocio=08285&offset=0|archivedate=6 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Paz0.jpg|thumb|left|133px|Octavio Paz, ardent champion of ''Los olvidados'' and close friend during Bu\u00f1uel's exile in Mexico<ref>{{cite book|last=Caistor|first=Nick|title=Octavio Paz|year=2007|publisher=Reaktion Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-86189-303-1|page=36|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OkPr_MWp2wMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>]]\nThis hostility was also felt by those who attended the movie's premi\u00e8re in Mexico City on 9 November 1950, when ''Los olvidados'' was taken by many as an insult to Mexican sensibilities and to the Mexican nation.<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.67}}  At one point, the audience shrieked in shock as one of the characters looked straight into the camera and hurled a rotten egg at it, leaving a gelatinous, opaque ooze on the lens for a few moments.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Faber|first=Sebastiaan|title=Bu\u00f1uel's Impure Modernism|journal=Modernist Cultures|year=2012|volume=7|issue=1|pages=56\u201376|doi=10.3366/mod.2012.0028}}</ref>  In his memoir, Bu\u00f1uel recalled that after the initial screening, painter [[Diego Rivera]]'s wife refused to speak to him, while poet [[Le\u00f3n Felipe]]'s wife had to be restrained physically from attacking him.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|pp.200\u2013201}}  There were even calls to have Bu\u00f1uel's Mexican citizenship revoked.<ref name=\"de la colina\" />{{rp|p.61}}  Dancigers, panicked by what he feared would be a complete debacle, quickly commissioned an alternate \"happy\" ending to the film,<ref name=unesco>{{cite web|title=Nomination Form, Memory of the World Register|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/fileadmin/MULTIMEDIA/HQ/CI/CI/pdf/mow/nomination_forms/los_olvidados.pdf|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> and also tacked on a preface showing stock footage of the skylines of New York, London and Paris with voice-over commentary to the effect that behind the wealth of all the great cities of the world can be found poverty and malnourished children, and that Mexico City \"that large modern city, is no exception\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=John|title=El Monstruo: Dread and Redemption in Mexico City|year=2009|publisher=Nation Books|location=New York|isbn=978-1-56858-424-9|pages=203|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=psHQERn0VMcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  Regardless, attendance was so poor that Dancigers withdrew the film after only three days in theaters.<ref name=\"berg los olvidados\">{{cite web|last=Berg|first=Charles Ram\u00edrez|title=Los Olvidados (1950)|url=http://www.austinfilm.org/page.aspx?pid=1692|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130414101344/http://www.austinfilm.org/page.aspx?pid=1692|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 April 2013|website=Essential Cinema|publisher=Austin Film Society|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>\n \nThrough the determined efforts of future Nobel Prize winner for Literature [[Octavio Paz]], who at the time was in Mexico's diplomatic service, ''Los olvidados'' was chosen to represent Mexico at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] of 1951, and Paz promoted the film assiduously by distributing a supportive manifesto<ref>{{cite news|last=Paz|first=Octavio|title=Cannes, 1951. Los olvidados|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1983/09/29/opinion/433638005_850215.html|accessdate=30 August 2012|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|date=29 September 1983}}</ref> and parading outside the cinema with a placard.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=Jason|title=Octavio Paz, a Study of His Poetics|year=1979|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-22306-5|pages=25|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6wk4AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  Opinion in general was enthusiastic, with the Surrealists (Breton and poet [[Jacques Prevert]]) and other artistic intellectuals (painter [[Marc Chagall]] and poet/dramatist/filmmaker [[Jean Cocteau]]) laudatory, but the communists objected to what they saw as the film's \"bourgeois morality\" for containing a scene in which the police stop a pederast from assaulting a child.<ref>{{cite web|last=Garmendia|first=Arturo|title=La batalla por \"Los Olvidados\" de Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://www.cineforever.com/2010/01/27/la-batalla-por-los-olvidados-de-bunuel/|publisher=Cineforever|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=27 January 2010}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel won the Best Director prize that year at Cannes, and also won the [[International Federation of Film Critics|FIPRESCI International Critics' Award]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Steffen|first=James|title=Los Olvidados|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/93547%7C0/Los-Olvidados.html|website=Turner Classic Movies Film Article|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks}}</ref>  After receiving these accolades, the film was reissued in Mexico where it ran for two months to much greater acceptance and profit.<ref>{{cite book|last=Faber|first=Sebastiaan|title=Exile and Cultural Hegemony: Spanish Intellectuals in Mexico, 1939\u20131975|year=2002|publisher=Vanderbilt University Press|location=Nashville|isbn=978-0-8265-1422-6|pages=xiv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WAY693mPUWsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  ''Los olvidados'' and its triumph at Cannes made Bu\u00f1uel an instant world celebrity and the most important Spanish-speaking film director in the world.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gazetas|first=Aristides|title=An Introduction to World Cinema|year=2008|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson NC|isbn=978-0-7864-3907-2|pages=198|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CPuZ-2UtVRwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  In 2003, ''Los olvidados'' was recommended by [[UNESCO]] for inclusion in the [[Memory of the World Programme#Memory of the World Register|Memory of the World Register]], calling it: \"the most important document in Spanish about the marginal lives of children in contemporary large cities\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Los olvidados|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/communication-and-information/flagship-project-activities/memory-of-the-world/register/full-list-of-registered-heritage/registered-heritage-page-5/los-olvidados/|website=Memory of the World|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"Here in Mexico, I have become a professional in the film world.  Until I came here I made a film the way a writer makes a book, and on my friends' money at that.  I am very grateful and happy to have lived in Mexico, and I have been able to make my films here in a way I could not have in any other country in the world.  It is quite true that in the beginning, caught up by necessity, I was forced to make cheap films. But I never made a film which went against my conscience or my convictions.  I have never made a superficial, uninteresting film.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=Interview with Wilfried Berghahn|journal=Filmkritik|date=1963|issue= 5}}</ref>  |source= \u2013 Luis Bu\u00f1uel on his mid-century career in Mexico. }}\nBu\u00f1uel remained in Mexico for the rest of his life, although he spent periods of time filming in France and Spain. In Mexico, he filmed 21 films during an 18-year period.  For many critics, although there were occasional widely acknowledged masterpieces like ''Los olvidados'' and [[\u00c9l (film)|''\u00c9l'']] (1953), the majority of his output consisted of generic fare which was adapted to the norms of the national film industry, frequently adopting melodramatic conventions that appealed to local tastes.<ref name=lim>{{cite news|last1=Lim|first1=Dennis|title=Mexican-era Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/08/entertainment/ca-secondlook8|accessdate=20 September 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=8 February 2009}}</ref>  Other commentators, however, have written of the deceptive complexity and intensity of many of these films, arguing that, collectively, they, \"bring a philosophical depth and power to his cinema, together offering a sustained meditation on ideas of religion, class inequity, violence and desire\".<ref name =\"Harvard.edu\" /> Although Bu\u00f1uel usually had little choice regarding the selection of these projects,<ref name=Delmas>{{cite journal|last1=Delmas|first1=Jean|title=Bu\u00f1uel, Citizen of Mexico|journal=Jeune Cinema|date=February 1966|issue= 12}}</ref> they often deal with themes that were central to his lifelong concerns:<ref name=adler>{{cite news|last1=Adler|first1=Renata|title=Screen: Bunuel's Relentless 'Nazarin':Film Set in the Mexico of Porfirio Diaz|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C02E1D7163AE134BC4951DFB0668383679EDE|accessdate=27 September 2014|work=New York Times|agency=The New York Times Company|date=21 June 1968}}</ref> \n* sexual pathology:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gutierrez-Albill|first1=Julian Daniel|title=Queering Bu\u00f1uel: Sexual Dissidence and Psychoanalysis in His Mexican and Spanish Cinema|date=2008|publisher=I.B.Tauris|location=London|isbn=9781845116682|pages=59\u201362|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E38AAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>  ''\u00c9l'' (1953), ''[[Ensayo de un crimen]]'' (1955), and ''[[Wuthering Heights (1954 film)|Abismos de pasi\u00f3n]]'' (1954)\n*the destructive effects of rampant [[machismo]]:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Evans|first1=Peter William|title=The Films of Luis Bu\u00f1uel. Subjectivity and Desire|date=1995|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0198159063|page=143}}</ref> ''[[El Bruto]]'', (1953), ''[[El r\u00edo y la muerte]]'', (1955); \n*the blurring of fantasy and reality:<ref>{{cite web|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel's Cinema of Entrapment in the Age of Cowardice: The Search for a Greater Truth|url=http://users.hal-pc.org/~questers/JAVA/fire/Bunuel.html|publisher=Gregory and Maria Pearse|accessdate=27 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402034318/http://users.hal-pc.org/~questers/JAVA/fire/Bunuel.html|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[Subida al cielo]]'' (1952), ''[[La ilusi\u00f3n viaja en tranv\u00eda]]'' (1954); \n*the disruptive status of women in a male-dominated culture:<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mu\u00f1oz|first1=Sara|title=La construcci\u00f3n femenina en el discurso cinematogr\u00e1fico de Bu\u00f1uel: la femme fatale|url=http://www.hispanetjournal.com/4Surrealfemme-EDITADO.pdf|website=Hispanet Journal 2|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> ''[[Susana (film)|Susana]]'' (1951), ''[[La hija del enga\u00f1o]]'' (1951\u2014a remake of the Film\u00f3fono production ''Don Quint\u00edn el amargao'' of 16 years earlier),<ref>{{cite web|title=La hija del enga\u00f1o (1951)|url=http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/hija_enganio.html|website=M\u00e1s de Cien A\u00f1os de Cine Mexicano|publisher=Maximiliano Maza|accessdate=1 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012084702/http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/hija_enganio.html|archive-date=12 October 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[Una mujer sin amor]]'' (1952); and\n*the absurdity of the religious life:<ref name=edwards />{{rp|pp.118\u201319}} ''[[Nazar\u00edn]]'' (1959) and ''Sim\u00f3n del desierto'' (1965).\n\nAs busy as he was during the 1950s and early 1960s, there were still many film projects that Bu\u00f1uel had to abandon due to lack of financing or studio support, including a cherished plan to film Mexican novelist [[Juan Rulfo]]'s ''[[Pedro P\u00e1ramo]]'', of which he said how much he enjoyed \"the crossing from the mysterious to the real, almost without transition.  I really like this mixture of reality and fantasy,  but I don't know how to bring it to the screen.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Poniatowska|first=Elena|title=Palabras cruzadas|year=1961|publisher=Ediciones Era|location=Mexico City|pages=191}}</ref>  Other unrealized projects during his lifetime included adaptations of [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]]'s ''Les caves du Vatican''; [[Benito P\u00e9rez Gald\u00f3s]]'s ''[[Fortunata y Jacinta]]'', ''[[Do\u00f1a Perfecta]]'', and ''\u00c1ngel Guerra''; [[Evelyn Waugh]]'s ''[[The Loved One]]''; [[William Golding]]'s ''[[Lord of the Flies]]''; [[Dalton Trumbo]]'s ''[[Johnny Got His Gun]]''; [[J. K. Huysmans]]' ''[[L\u00e0-bas (novel)|L\u00e0-Bas]]''; [[Matthew Lewis (writer)|Matthew Lewis]]'s ''[[The Monk]]''; [[Jos\u00e9 Donoso]]'s ''[[Hell Has No Limits|Lugar sin l\u00edmites]]''; a film of four stories based on [[Carlos Fuentes]]'s ''[[Aura (Fuentes)|Aura]]''; and [[Julio Cort\u00e1zar]]'s ''[[Final del juego|Las m\u00e9nades]]''.<ref name=\"fuentes discourse\" />{{rp|p.96}}\n\n====Mexico and beyond: return to international filmmaking (1954\u20131960)====\n[[File:S.Kragujevic, G\u00e9rard Philipe 1955.JPG|thumb|175px|[[G\u00e9rard Philipe]], popular French star of Bu\u00f1uel's ''[[La Fi\u00e8vre Monte \u00e0 El Pao]]''. At one point during the filming, Bu\u00f1uel asked Philipe, who was visibly dying of cancer, why the actor was making this film, and Philipe responded by asking the director the same question, to which both said they didn't know.<ref name=hagopian>{{cite web|last1=Hagopian|first1=Kevin|title=Fever Mounts in El Pao|url=http://www.albany.edu/writers-inst/webpages4/filmnotes/fnf02n11.html|website=New York State Writers Institute|publisher=Writers Institute|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>]]\nAs much as he welcomed steady employment in the Mexican film industry, Bu\u00f1uel was quick to seize opportunities to re-emerge onto the international film scene and to engage with themes that were not necessarily focused on Mexican preoccupations.<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.144}}  His first chance came in 1954, when Dancigers partnered with Henry F. Ehrlich, of [[United Artists]], to co-produce a film version of [[Daniel Defoe]]'s ''[[Robinson Crusoe]]'', using a script developed by the Canadian writer [[Hugo Butler]].  The film was produced by George Pepper, the former executive secretary of the Hollywood Democratic Committee.  Both Butler and Pepper were emigres from Hollywood who had run afoul of authorities seeking out communists.<ref name=schreiber />{{rp|p.75}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsdefrance.com/review/the-young-one-1960.html|title=Review of the film The Young One (1960)|first=James|last=Travers|date=27 October 2017|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref>  The result, ''[[Adventures of Robinson Crusoe]]'', was Bu\u00f1uel's first color film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=The Adventures of Robinson Crusoe|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-adventures-of-robinson-crusoe|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel was given much more time than usual for the filming (three months), which was accomplished on location in Manzanillo, a Pacific seaport with a lush jungle interior, and was shot simultaneously in English and Spanish.<ref name=\"axmaker robinson crusoe\">{{cite web|last1=Axmaker|first1=Sean|title=Adventures of Robinson Crusoe (1954)|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/66823/Adventures-of-Robinson-Crusoe/articles.html|website=Turner Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>  When the film was released in the United States, its young star [[Dan O'Herlihy]] used his own money to fund a Los Angeles run for the film and gave free admission to all members of the [[Screen Actors Guild]], who in turn rewarded the little-known actor with his only [[Oscar award|Oscar]] nomination.<ref name=\"axmaker robinson crusoe\" />\n\nIn the mid-1950s, Bu\u00f1uel got the chance to work again in France on international co-productions.  The result was what critic [[Raymond Durgnat]] has called the director's \"revolutionary triptych\", in that each of the three films is \"openly, or by implication, a study in the morality and tactics of armed revolution against a right-wing dictatorship\".<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.100}}  The first, ''[[Cela s'appelle l'aurore]]'' (Franco-Italian, 1956) required Bu\u00f1uel and the [['Pataphysics|\"pataphysical\"]] writer [[Jean Ferry]] to adapt a novel by [[Emmanuel Robl\u00e8s]] after the celebrated writer [[Jean Genet]] failed to deliver a script after having been paid in full.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.100}}  The second film was [[Death in the Garden|''La Mort en ce jardin'']] (Franco-Mexican, 1956), which was adapted by Bu\u00f1uel and his frequent collaborator [[Luis Alcoriza]] from a novel by the Belgian writer [[Jos\u00e9-Andr\u00e9 Lacour]].  The final part of the \"triptych\" was ''[[La Fi\u00e8vre Monte \u00e0 El Pao]]'' (Franco-Mexican, 1959), the last film of the popular French star [[G\u00e9rard Philipe]], who died in the final stages of the production.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Canby|first1=Vincent|title=Film: From Bunuel, 'Los Ambiciosos,' at the Public|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/12/movies/film-from-bunuel-los-ambiciosos-at-the-public.html|accessdate=30 September 2014|agency=New York Times|date=12 February 1988}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel was later to explain that he was so strapped for cash that he, \"took everything that was offered to me, as long as it wasn't humiliating\".<ref name=hagopian />\n\nIn 1960, Bu\u00f1uel re-teamed with scenarist Hugo Butler and organizer George Pepper, allegedly his favorite producer,  to make his second English-language film, a US/Mexico co-production called ''[[The Young One]]'', based on a short story by writer and former CIA-agent [[Peter Matthiessen]].<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=hZuzxKQfhYUC&pg=PA191&lpg=PA191&dq=george+pepper+Bu\u00f1uel#v=onepage&q=pepper | title=My Last Sigh: The Autobiography of Luis Bunuel| isbn=9780345803719| last1=Bunuel| first1=Luis| date=2013-03-26}}</ref>  This film has been called \"a surprisingly uncompromising study of racism and sexual desire, set on a remote island in the Deep South\"<ref name =\"Harvard.edu\" /> and has been described by critic Ed Gonzalez as, \"salacious enough to make [[Elia Kazan]]'s [[Baby Doll]] and [[Louis Malle|Luis Malle's]] [[Pretty Baby (1978 film)|''Pretty Baby'']] blush\".<ref name=\"The Young One 4 out of 4\">{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=The Young One 4 out of 4|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-young-one|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>  Although the film won a special award at the Cannes Film Festival for its treatment of racial discrimination,<ref name=bentley />{{rp|p.151}} the US critics were so hostile upon its release that Bu\u00f1uel was later to say that, \"a Harlem newspaper even wrote that I should be hung upside down from a lamppost on Fifth Avenue....I made this film with love, but it never had a chance.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rosenbaum|first1=Jonathan|title=The Young One: Bu\u00f1uel's Neglected Masterpiece|url=http://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/2009/07/22909/|website=jonathanrosenbaum.net|accessdate=30 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006084401/http://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/2009/07/22909/|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In the words of film historian Peter Harcourt: \"if ''The Young One'' must still be considered a 'bad' film by conventional standards, then it is one of the most subtle, most challenging and most distinguished bad films ever made.\"<ref name=\"peter harcourt\">{{cite journal|last1=Harcourt|first1=Peter|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Spaniard and Surrealist|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1967|volume=20|issue=3|page=12|url=http://www.austinlibrary.com:2138/stable/pdfplus/1210106.pdf?acceptTC=true&jpdConfirm=true|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Late international period (1961\u20131977)===\nAt the 1960 Cannes Festival, Bu\u00f1uel was approached by the young director [[Carlos Saura]], whose film [[The Delinquents (1960 film)|''Los Golfos'']] had been entered officially to represent Spain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los Golfos|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/3299/year/1960.html|publisher=Festival de Cannes|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>  Two years earlier, Saura had partnered with [[Juan Antonio Bardem]] and [[Luis Garc\u00eda Berlanga]] to form a production company called UNINCI,<ref name=\"andrew whittaker\">{{cite book|last1=Whittaker|first1=Andrew|title=Speak the Culture: Spain: Be Fluent in Spanish Life and Culture|date=2008|publisher=Thorogood Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1854186058|page=225|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2rZS8SWMroUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref> and the group was keen to get Bu\u00f1uel to make a new film in his native country as part of their overall goal of creating a uniquely Spanish brand of cinema.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.190\u201391}} At the same time, Mexican actress [[Silvia Pinal]] was eager to work with Bu\u00f1uel and talked her producer-husband [[Gustavo Alatriste]] into providing additional funding for the project with the understanding that the director, who Pinal described as \"a man worshiped and idolized\", would be given \"absolute freedom\" in carrying out the work.<ref name=\"agustin de gracia\">{{cite news|last1=de Gracia|first1=Agust\u00edn|title=Recuerdan a Luis Bu\u00f1uel a 30 a\u00f1os de su fallecimiento|url=http://www.laopinion.com/entretenimientocine/article/20130731/Recuerdan-a-Luis-Bunuel-a-30-anos-de-su-fallecimiento&template=print|accessdate=4 October 2014|work=laopinion.com|date=31 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006094142/http://www.laopinion.com/entretenimientocine/article/20130731/Recuerdan-a-Luis-Bunuel-a-30-anos-de-su-fallecimiento%26template%3Dprint|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Finally, Bu\u00f1uel agreed to work again in Spain when further support was provided by producer [[Pere Portabella]]'s company ''Film 59''.<ref name=\"pere portabella\">{{cite web|title=Pere Portabella|url=http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/films/556|website=Film Exhibitions|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nBu\u00f1uel and his co-scenarist [[Julio Alejandro]] drafted a preliminary screenplay for ''[[Viridiana]]'', which critic [[Andrew Sarris]] has described as incorporating \"a plot which is almost too lurid to synopsize even in these enlightened times\",<ref name=\"sarris viridiana\">{{cite web|last1=Sarris|first1=Andrew|title=The Devil and the Nun|url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/film/movie/contents/the_devil_and_the_nun_sarris.pdf|website=warwick.ac.uk|publisher=University of Warwick|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> dealing with rape, incest, hints of necrophilia, animal cruelty and sacrilege, and dutifully submitted it to the Spanish censor, who, to the surprise of nearly everyone, approved it after requesting only minor modifications and one significant change to the ending.<ref name=\"d'lugo films of carlos saura\">{{cite book|last1=D'Lugo|first1=Marvin|title=The Films of Carlos Saura: The Practice of Seeing|date=1991|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton, NJ|isbn=978-0-691-03142-2|pages=42\u201343|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RUAks4YGLWAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Although Bu\u00f1uel accommodated the censor's demands, he came up with a final scene that was even more provocative than the scene it replaced: \"even more immoral\", as Bu\u00f1uel was later to observe.<ref name=\"ebert viridiana\">{{cite web|last1=Ebert|first1=Roger|title=Viridiana|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-viridiana-1961|website=The Great Movies|publisher=RogerEbert.com|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Since Bu\u00f1uel had more than adequate resources, top-flight technical and artistic crews, and experienced actors, filming of ''Viridiana'' (which took place on location and at Bardem's studios in Madrid) went smoothly and quickly.<ref name=Pavlovi>{{cite book|last=Pavlovi\u0107|first=Tatjana|title=100 Years of Spanish Cinema|year=2009|publisher=Wiley|location=New York|isbn=978-1-4051-8419-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PtFXpxyWMi4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|display-authors=etal}}</ref>{{rp|p. 98}}\n\nBu\u00f1uel submitted a cutting copy to the censors and then arranged for his son, Juan Luis, to smuggle the negatives to Paris for the final editing and mixing,<ref>{{cite web|title=Viridiana.50|url=http://www.viridiana50.com/uninci.php|website=viridiana50.com|publisher=Ministerio de Cultura de Espa\u00f1a|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> ensuring that the authorities would not have an opportunity to view the finished product before its planned submission as Spain's official entry to the 1961 Cannes Festival.<ref name=buache>{{cite book|last1=Buache|first1=Freddy|title=The Cinema of Luis Bu\u00f1uel|date=1973|publisher=Tantivy Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-498-01302-7|pages=117\u201320}}</ref> Spain's director general of cinematography Jos\u00e9 Munoz-Fontan presented the film on the last day of the festival and then, on the urging of Portabella and Bardem, appeared in person to accept the top prize, the [[Palme d'Or]], which the film shared with the French entry ''[[Une aussi longue absence]]'', directed by [[Henri Colpi]].<ref name=\"buache french edition\">{{cite book|last1=Buache|first1=Freddy|title=Bu\u00f1uel|date=1975|publisher=L'Age d'Homme| location=Lausanne| isbn=9782825133415| page=119| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tuo1JTpoxQAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Within days, ''[[l'Osservatore Romano]]'', the Vatican's official organ, denounced the film as an insult not only to Catholicism but to Christianity in general.<ref name=malcolm>{{cite news|last1=Malcolm|first1=Derek|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Viridiana|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/1999/apr/01/derekmalcolmscenturyoffilm.derekmalcolm|accessdate=5 October 2014|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=1 April 1999}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=Luis Bunuel's Case Study on Bourgeoisie Plight and its Underlining Causes|url=http://www.apotpourriofvestiges.com/2012/02/viridiana-1961-luis-bunuels-case-study.html|website=apotpourriofvestiges.com|publisher=A Potpourri of Vestiges|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>  Consequences to nearly all concerned were swift: Munoz-Fontan was cashiered from his government post,<ref name=\"buache french edition\" /> the film was banned in Spain for the next 17 years, all mention of it in the press was prohibited, and the two Spanish production companies UNINCI and ''Film 59'' were disbanded.<ref name=\"d'lugo films of carlos saura\" />\n\n[[File:Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re \u00e0 la BNF.jpg|thumb|right|270px|\"When today I amuse myself by making useless calculations, I realize that Bu\u00f1uel and I shared more than two thousand meals together and that on more than fifteen hundred occasions he knocked on my door, notes in hand, ready to begin work. I'm not even counting the walks, the drinks, the films we watched together, the film festivals.\"<ref name=\"carriere flickhead\">{{cite web|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel Remembered by Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re|url=http://home.comcast.net/~flickhead/Luis-Bunuel.html|website=Flickhead|publisher=Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> \u2013 Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re on his long-term collaboration with Bu\u00f1uel.]]\nBu\u00f1uel went on to make two more films in Mexico with Pinal and Alatriste, ''[[El \u00e1ngel exterminador]]'' (1962) and ''[[Sim\u00f3n del desierto]]'' (1965)\u2014 along with ''Viridiana'', they form the so-called \"Bu\u00f1uelian trilogy\" \u2014 and was later to say that Alatriste had been the one producer who gave him the most freedom in creative expression.<ref name=\"Rowman & Littlefield\">{{cite book|last1=Alfaro|first1=Eduardo de la Vega|title=\"The Decline of the Golden Age and the Making of the Crisis,\" in Mexico's Cinema: A Century of Film and Filmmakers, edited by Joanne Hershfield and David R. Maciel|date=1999|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0842026826|page=[https://archive.org/details/mexicoscinema00davi/page/189 189]|url=https://archive.org/details/mexicoscinema00davi/page/189}}</ref>\n\nIn 1963, actor [[Fernando Rey]], one of the stars of ''Viridiana'', introduced Bu\u00f1uel to producer [[Serge Silberman]], a Polish entrepreneur who had fled to Paris when his family died in the Holocaust<ref>{{cite news|title=Serge Silberman, productor de Luis Bu\u00f1uel y de Akira Kurosawa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2003/07/25/agenda/1059084008_850215.html|accessdate=13 October 2014|work=El Pais|agency=http://elpais.com/|date=25 July 2003}}</ref> and had worked with several renowned French directors, including [[Jean-Pierre Melville]], [[Jacques Becker]], [[Marcel Camus]] and [[Christian-Jaque]].<ref name=\"ronald bergan\">{{cite news|last1=Bergan|first1=Ronald|title=Serge Silberman: Flamboyant film producer prepared to go out on a limb|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2003/jul/28/guardianobituaries.filmnews|accessdate=13 October 2014|work=The Guardian|agency=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=27 July 2003}}</ref> Silberman proposed that the two make an adaptation of [[Octave Mirbeau]]'s [[The Diary of a Chambermaid (novel)|''Journal d'une femme de chambre'']], which Bu\u00f1uel had read several times.<ref name=\"gonzalez chambermaid\">{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=The Diary of a Chambermaid|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-diary-of-a-chambermaid|website=Slant Magazine.|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel wanted to do the filming in Mexico with Pinal, but Silberman insisted it be done in France.<ref name=\"gonzalez chambermaid\" />\n\nPinal was so determined to work again with Bu\u00f1uel that she was ready to move to France, learn the language and even work for nothing in order to get the part of [[C\u00e9lestine (Mirbeau)|C\u00e9lestine]], the title character.<ref name=\"rivera pinal\">{{cite journal|last1=Rivera J.|first1=H\u00e9ctor|title=Las experiencias de Silvia Pinal con Bu\u00f1uel y Gustavo Alatriste|journal=Proceso|date=13 July 1997|issue=n1080|page=62}}</ref> Silberman, however, wanted French actress [[Jeanne Moreau]] to play the role, so he put Pinal off by telling her that Moreau, too, was willing to act with no fee. Ultimately, Silberman got his way, leaving Pinal so disappointed that she was later to claim that Alatriste's failure to help her secure this part led to the breakup of their marriage.<ref name=\"rivera pinal\" /> When Bu\u00f1uel requested a French-speaking writer with whom to collaborate on the screenplay, Silberman suggested the 32-year-old [[Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re]], an actor whose previous screenwriting credits included only a few films for the comic star/director [[Pierre \u00c9taix]], but once Bu\u00f1uel learned that Carri\u00e8re was the scion of a wine-growing family, the newcomer was hired on the spot.<ref name=\"ronald bergan\" /> At first, Carri\u00e8re found it difficult to work with Bu\u00f1uel, because the young man was so deferential to the famous director that he never challenged any of Bu\u00f1uel's ideas, until, at Bu\u00f1uel's covert insistence, Silberman told Carri\u00e8re to stand up to Bu\u00f1uel now and then; as Carri\u00e8re was later to say: \"In a way, Bu\u00f1uel needed an opponent. He didn't need a secretary \u2013 he needed someone to contradict him and oppose him and to make suggestions.\"<ref name=\"tim grierson FilmCraft: Screenwriting\">{{cite book|last1=Grierson|first1=Tim|title=FilmCraft: Screenwriting|date=2013|publisher=Focal Press|location=Burlington MA|isbn=978-0240824864|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PHtiAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> The finished 1964 film, [[Diary of a Chambermaid (1964 film)|''Diary of a Chambermaid'']], became the first of several to be made by the team of Bu\u00f1uel, Carri\u00e8re and Silberman.  Carri\u00e8re was later to say: \"Without me and without Serge Silberman, the producer, perhaps Bu\u00f1uel would not have made so many films after he was 65. We really encouraged him to work. That's for sure.\"<ref name=Colville-Andersen>{{cite web|last1=Colville-Andersen|first1=Mikael|title=The Storytellers \u2013 Interview with Jean-Claude Carri\u00e9r\u00e9|url=http://zakka.dk/euroscreenwriters/screenwriters/jean-claude_carriere.htm|website=Zakkatography|publisher=Colville-Andersen.|accessdate=15 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331223043/http://zakka.dk/euroscreenwriters/screenwriters/jean-claude_carriere.htm|archive-date=31 March 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \nThis was the second attempt to film Mirbeau's novel, the first being [[The Diary of a Chambermaid (1946 film)|a 1946 Hollywood production]] directed by [[Jean Renoir]], which Bu\u00f1uel refused to view for fear of being influenced by the famous French director, whom he venerated.<ref name=\"david kalat\">{{cite web|last1=Kalat|first1=David|title=Diary of a Chambermaid|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/474221%7C474228/Diary-of-a-Chambermaid.html|website=Turner Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel's version, while admired by many, has often been compared unfavorably to Renoir's, with a number of critics claiming that Renoir's ''Diary'' fits better in Renoir's overall ''oeuvre'', while Bu\u00f1uel's ''Diary'' is not sufficiently \"Bu\u00f1uelian\".<ref name=\"Geoffrey T. Harris\">{{cite book|last1=Harris|first1=Geoffrey T.|title=On Translating French Literature and Film, Volume 1|date=1996|publisher=Rodopi|location=Amsterdam|isbn=978-90-5183-933-3|page=92|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wUbGJ8kozAoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 1964 release of ''Diary'', Bu\u00f1uel again tried to make a film of Matthew Lewis' ''[[The Monk]]'', a project on which he had worked, on and off, since 1938, according to producer [[Pierre Braunberger]].<ref name=gubern />{{rp|p.137}} He and Carri\u00e8re wrote a screenplay, but were unable to obtain funding for the project, which would be finally realized in 1973 under the direction of Bu\u00f1uel devotee [[Adonis A. Kyrou|Ado Kyrou]], with considerable assistance from both Bu\u00f1uel and Carri\u00e8re.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Aspley|first1=Keith|title=Historical Dictionary of Surrealism|date=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0810858473|page=284|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3KK7JHqNrRsC&pg=PA284&dq=bunuel+the+monk+lewis+carriere#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20the%20monk%20lewis%20carriere|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965, Bu\u00f1uel manage to work again with Sylvia Pinal in what would turn out to be his last Mexican feature, co-starring Claudio Brook, ''[[Sim\u00f3n del desierto]]''.<ref name=\"Rowman & Littlefield\"/> Pinal was keenly interested in continuing to work with Bu\u00f1uel, trusting him completely and frequently stating that he brought out the best in her; however, this would be their last collaboration.<ref name=\"La Jornada\">{{cite news|title=No he conocido a alguien que supere a Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Silvia Pinal|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2013/07/29/espectaculos/a12n1esp|accessdate=13 October 2014|work=La Jornada|agency=DEMOS, Desarrollo de Medios|date=29 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Catherine Deneuve 1969-2.jpg|thumb|195px|left|Catherine Deneuve starred in ''[[Belle de Jour (film)|Belle de Jour]]'' (1967), based on Joseph Kessel's novel, playing the role of a bored upper class Parisian housewife who spends her weekdays in a brothel.  She was re-united with Bu\u00f1uel again, starring in ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'' (1970), shot in [[Toledo, Spain]].  Deneuve is pictured here in 1968]]\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"Well, I think it was difficult for him, coping with his deafness. Some people said he was not that deaf, but I think, when you don't hear very well and when you're tired, everything sinks into a buzz, and it is very hard. French is not his language, so on ''Belle de Jour'', I'm sure that it was much more of an effort for him to have to explain. \".<ref name=zohn /> |source=Actress [[Catherine Deneuve]], star of ''Belle de Jour''}}\n\nIn 1966, Bu\u00f1uel was approached by [[Robert and Raymond Hakim|the Hakim brothers, Robert and Raymond]], Egyptian-French producers who specialized in sexy films directed by star filmmakers,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bernard|first1=Jami|title=The X-List: The National Society of Film Critics' Guide to the Movies that Turn Us On|date=2005|publisher=Da Capo Press|location=Cambridge MA|isbn=978-0306814457|page=40|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pWH97tY1KfMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> who offered him the opportunity to direct a film version of [[Joseph Kessel]]'s novel [[Belle de Jour (novel)|''Belle de Jour'']], a book about an affluent young woman who leads a double life as a prostitute, and that had caused a scandal upon its first publication in 1928.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boucharenc|first1=Myriam|title=L'\u00e9crivain-reporter au c\u0153ur des ann\u00e9es trente|date=2004|publisher=Presses Univ. Septentrion|location=Lille|isbn=978-2-85939-842-2|page=184|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2GShcPJaDg4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel did not like Kessel's novel, considering it \"a bit of a soap opera\",<ref name=\"Europe of Cultures\">{{cite web|last1=Durieux|first1=Christian|title=Conversation with Luis Bu\u00f1uel on Belle de jour|url=http://fresques.ina.fr/europe-des-cultures-en/fiche-media/Europe00048/conversation-with-luis-bunuel-on-belle-de-jour.html|website=Europe of Cultures|publisher=INA Institute|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> but he took on the challenge because: \"I found it interesting to try to turn something I didn't like into something I did.\"<ref name=\"levy belle de jour\">{{cite web|last1=Levy|first1=Emanuel|title=Belle de Jour (1967): Bunuel's Masterpiece Starring Catherine Deneuve|url=http://emanuellevy.com/pick-of-the-week/belle-de-jour-1967-bunuels-masterpiece-starring-catherine-deneuve/|website=Cinema 24/7|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> So he and Carri\u00e8re set out enthusiastically to interview women in the brothels of Madrid to learn about their sexual fantasies.<ref name=\"belle de jour tcm\">{{cite web|last=Landazuri|first=Margarita|title=Belle de jour|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article.html?id=628630%7C636738|website=TCM Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel also was not happy about the choice of the 22-year-old [[Catherine Deneuve]] for the title role, feeling that she had been foisted upon him by the Hakim brothers and Deneuve's lover at the time, director [[Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut]].<ref name=\"moma belle de jour\">{{cite web|last1=Silver|first1=Charles|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel's Belle de Jour|url=http://www.moma.org/explore/inside_out/2014/04/22/luis-bunuels-belle-de-jour/|website=Inside/Out|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> As a result, both actress and director found working together difficult, with Deneuve claiming, \"I felt they showed more of me than they'd said they were going to. There were moments when I felt totally used. I was very unhappy,\"<ref name=\"anderson belle\">{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Melissa|title=Belle de jour: Tough Love|url=https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/2121-belle-de-jour-tough-love|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> and Bu\u00f1uel deriding her prudery on the set and complaining that the hairdresser had to bind her breasts in order to assure her that they would not show on screen.<ref name=zohn>{{cite web|last1=Zohn|first1=Patricia|title=Belle de Jour: Catherine Deneuve and Her Shades of Grey |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/patricia-zohn/catherine-deneuve_b_1395172.html|website=HuffPost Arts and Culture| publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=29 October 2014|date=2 April 2012}}</ref> The resulting film has been described by film critic [[Roger Ebert]] as \"possibly the best-known erotic film of modern times, perhaps the best\",<ref>{{cite web| last1=Ebert| first1=Roger| title=Belle de Jour|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-belle-de-jour-1967|website=Great Movies|publisher=Roger Ebert.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> even though, as another critic has written, \"in terms of explicit sexual activity, there is little in ''Belle de jour'' we might not see in a [[Doris Day]] comedy from the same year\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Melville|first1=David|title=Who Let the Cats Out? Bu\u00f1uel, Deneuve and Belle de jour|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2013/cteq/who-let-the-cats-out-bunuel-deneuve-and-belle-de-jour/|website=Senses of Cinema|publisher=Film Victoria|accessdate=29 October 2014|date=9 September 2013}}</ref> It was Bu\u00f1uel's most successful film at the box office.<ref name=\"anderson belle\" />\n\nCritics have noted Bu\u00f1uel's habit of following up a commercial or critical success with a more personal, idiosyncratic film that might have less chance of popular esteem.<ref name=\"Polizzotti milky way\">{{cite web|last1=Polizzotti|first1=Mark| title=The Milky Way: Easy Striders|url=https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/611-the-milky-way-easy-striders|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter the worldwide success of his 1967 ''Belle de jour'', and upon viewing [[Jean-Luc Godard]]'s film ''La Chinoise'', Bu\u00f1uel, who had wanted to make a film about Catholic heresies for years, told Carri\u00e8re: \"If that is what today's cinema is like, then we can make a film about heresies.\"<ref name=\"supernal dreams\">{{cite web| last1=French| first1=Lawrence| title=Supernal Dreams: Jean-Claude Carriere on Luis Bunuel's Sublime Fantasy, \"The Milky Way\" | url=http://cinefantastiqueonline.com/2009/02/supernal-dreams-jean-claude-carriere-on-luis-bunuels-sublime-fantasy-the-milky-way/|website=Cinefantastique Online|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> The two spent months researching Catholic history and created the 1969 film [[The Milky Way (1969 film)|''The Milky Way'']], a \"picaresque road film\"<ref name=Nochimson>{{cite book|last1=Nochimson|first1=Martha|title=World on Film: An Introduction| date=2010| publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=New York|isbn=978-1405139793|page=294|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DXK5gkQwAs8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> that tells the story of two vagabonds on [[Camino de Santiago|pilgrimage to the tomb of the Apostle James]] at [[Santiago de Compostela]], during which they travel through time and space to take part in situations illustrating heresies that arose from the six major Catholic dogmas.<ref name=mazur>{{cite book|last1=Mazur|first1=Eric Michael|title=Encyclopedia of Religion and Film|date=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-0313330728|page=101|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JPNfox6H5qwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]], reviewing the film in the ''New York Times'', compared it to [[George Stevens]]' blockbuster ''[[The Greatest Story Ever Told]]'', in that Bu\u00f1uel had made a film about Jesus casting nearly all the famous French performers of the time in cameo roles.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Canby| first1=Vincent|title='The Milky Way':Bunuel Weaves Surreal Spiritual Journey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=990CE5D8123AE03BBC4F51DFB766838B669EDE|accessdate=11 December 2014|work=New York Times|date=27 January 1970}}</ref> ''The Milky Way'' was banned in Italy, only to have the Catholic Church intervene on its behalf.<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.152}}\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=A few great directors have the ability to draw us into their dream world, into their personalities and obsessions and fascinate us with them for a short time. This is the highest level of escapism the movies can provide for us \u2013 just as our elementary identification with a hero or a heroine was the lowest.<ref name=zohn /> |source=Film critic [[Roger Ebert]], on ''Tristana''<ref name=\"ebert tristana\">{{cite web|last1=Ebert|first1=Roger|title=Tristana|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/tristana-1970|website=Roger Ebert.com| publisher=Ebert Digital LLC|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nThe 1970 film ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'' is a film about a young woman who is seduced and manipulated by her guardian, who attempts to thwart her romance with a young artist and who eventually induces her to marry him after she loses one of her legs due to a tumor. It has been considered by scholar Beth Miller the least understood of Bu\u00f1uel's films, and consequently one of the most underrated, due to a \"consistent failure to apprehend its political and, especially, its socialist-feminist statement\".<ref name=\"beth miller\">{{cite book|last1=Miller|first1=Beth|title=\"From Mistress to Murderess,\" in Women in Hispanic Literature: Icons and Fallen Idols, edited by Beth Kurti Miller|date=1983|publisher=University of California Press| isbn=978-0520043671| pages=340\u201341|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8cCIcUaEznYC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel had wanted to make a film of [[Benito P\u00e9rez Gald\u00f3s]]' novel ''[[Tristana (novel)|Tristana]]'' as early as 1952, even though he considered Gald\u00f3s' book the author's weakest, in Bu\u00f1uel's words: \"of the 'I love you, my little pigeon' genre, very kitsch\".<ref name=fujiwara>{{cite web|last1=Fujiwara|first1=Chris|title=Tristana|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article.html?isPreview=&id=628630%7C449958&name=Tristana|website=TCM Summer Under the Stars|publisher=Turner Entertainment Network|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> After finishing ''Viridiana'' and in the wake of the scandal its release caused in 1962, the Spanish censor flatly turned down this project,<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.152}} and Bu\u00f1uel had to wait for 8 years before he could receive backing from the Spanish production company Epoca Films.<ref name=fujiwara /> The censors had threatened to deny permission for the film on the grounds that it encouraged duelling, so Bu\u00f1uel had to approach the subject matter very gingerly, in addition to making concessions to his French/Italian/Spanish producers, who insisted on casting two of the three primary roles with actors not of Bu\u00f1uel's choosing: [[Franco Nero]] and Catherine Deneuve.<ref name=\"faulkner literary adaptations\" />{{rp|p.128}} On this occasion, however, Deneuve and Bu\u00f1uel had a more mutually satisfactory working relationship, with Deneuve telling an interviewer, \"but in the end, you know, it was actually rather a wonderful shoot. ''Tristana'' is one of my favorite films. Personally, as an actress, I prefer ''Tristana'' to ''Belle de Jour''.\"<ref name=fujiwara />\n\nThe germ of the idea for their next film together, ''[[The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie]]'' (1972) came from Bu\u00f1uel and Serge Silberman discussing uncanny repetition in everyday life; Silberman told an anecdote about how he had invited some friends for dinner at his house, only to forget about it, so that, on the night of the dinner party, he was absent and his wife was in her nightclothes.<ref name=pinkos>{{cite web| last1=Pinkos| first1=Jefferey| title=Dinner Is Served| url=http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeoisie/| website=Lone Star Film Society| accessdate=12 December 2014| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223031928/http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeoisie/| archivedate=23 December 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film tells of a group of affluent friends who are continually stymied in their attempts to eat a meal together, a situation that a number of critics have contrasted to the opposite dilemma of the characters in ''[[The Exterminating Angel]]'', where guests of a dinner party are mysteriously unable to leave after having completed their meal.<ref name=lim /> For this film, Bu\u00f1uel, Silberman and Carri\u00e8re assembled a top-flight cast of European performers, \"a veritable rogues' gallery of French art-house cinema\", according to one critic.<ref name=\"budd wilkins\">{{cite web|last1=Wilkins|first1=Budd|title=The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeoisie-6699|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> For the first time, Bu\u00f1uel made use of a [[video monitors|video-playback monitor]], which allowed him to make much more extensive use of [[crane shot]]s and elaborate [[tracking shot]]s, and enabled him to cut the film in the camera and eliminate the need for [[Re-shoot|reshoots]].<ref name=pinkos /> Filming required only two months and Bu\u00f1uel claimed that editing took only one day.<ref name=pinkos /> When the film was released, Silberman decided to skip the Cannes Festival in order to concentrate on getting it nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]], which it won, leading Bu\u00f1uel to express his contempt for a process that relied on the judgment of, \"2500 idiots, including for example the assistant dress designer of the studio\".<ref name=pinkos />\n\nAs was his habit, Bu\u00f1uel took advantage of the popular success of ''Discreet Charm'' to make one of the \"puzzling, idiosyncratic films he ''really'' wanted to make\".<ref name=\"Polizzotti milky way\" /> In 1973, at the [[Monastery of El Paular|Monastery of Paular]] in the Spanish [[Somosierra]], he wrote the screenplay for ''[[The Phantom of Liberty]]''(1974) with Carri\u00e8re for production by Silberman and his Hollywood partners.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.249}} The resulting film is a series of 12 distinctive episodes with separate protagonists, linked together only by following a character from one episode to another in a relay-race manner.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lanzagorta|first1=Marco|title=The Phantom of Liberty| url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2002/cteq/phantom/|website=Senses of Cinema|publisher=Film Victoria, Australia|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel has stated that he made the film as a tribute to poet [[Benjamin P\u00e9ret]], a founding member of French Surrealism,<ref name=\"bill krohn\" />{{rp|p.170}} and called it his \"most Surrealist film\".<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.249}}\n\nBu\u00f1uel's final film was ''[[That Obscure Object of Desire]]'' (1977), adapted by Bu\u00f1uel and Carri\u00e8re from an 1898 novel by [[Pierre Lou\u00ffs]] called ''[[La Femme et le pantin]]'', which had already been used as the basis of films directed by [[Josef von Sternberg]] ([[The Devil is a Woman (1935 film)|''The Devil is a Woman'']], 1935) and [[Julien Duvivier]] (''[[La Femme et le Pantin]]'', 1959). The film, which tells the story of an older man who is obsessed by a young woman who continually evades his attempts to consummate a sexual relationship, starred the Spanish actor [[Fernando Rey]], appearing in his fourth Bu\u00f1uel film. Initially, the part of the young woman was to be played by [[Maria Schneider (actress)|Maria Schneider]], who had achieved international fame for her roles in ''[[Last Tango in Paris]]'' and [[The Passenger (1975 film)|''The Passenger'']],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grimes|first1=William|title=Maria Schneider, Actress in ''Last Tango'', Dies at 58|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/04/movies/04schneider.html|accessdate=16 December 2014|work=New York Times|date=4 February 2011}}</ref> but once shooting started, according to Carri\u00e8re, her drug usage resulted in a \"lackluster and dull\" performance that caused tempestuous arguments with Bu\u00f1uel on the set and her eventual dismissal.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Thomson|first1=David|title=David Thomson on Films: Remembering Maria Schneider|journal=New Republic|date=8 February 2011|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/books-and-arts/82975/david-thomson-films-remembering-maria-schneider|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref> Serge Silberman, the producer, decided to abandon the project at that point, but was convinced by Bu\u00f1uel to continue shooting with two different actresses, [[\u00c1ngela Molina]] and [[Carole Bouquet]] playing the same role in alternating sequences throughout the film. In his autobiography, Bu\u00f1uel claimed that this unusual casting decision was his own idea after drinking two dry martinis, saying: \"If I had to list all the benefits derived from alcohol, it would be endless\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pinkos|first1=Jefferey|title=Bu\u00f1uel's Pursuit of That Obscure Object|url=http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/that-obscure-object-of-desire/|website=Lone Star Film Society|accessdate=17 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223155848/http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/that-obscure-object-of-desire/|archivedate=23 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Others have reported that Carri\u00e8re had first broached the idea while developing the film's scenario, but had been brushed off by Bu\u00f1uel as \"the whim of a rainy day\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=That Obscure Object of Desire|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/that-obscure-object-of-desire|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Last years (1978\u20131983)===\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"Luis waited for death for a long time, like a good Spaniard, and when he died he was ready. His relationship with death was like that one has with a woman. He felt the love, hate, tenderness, ironical detachment of a long relationship, and he didn't want to miss the last encounter, the moment of union. \"I hope I will die alive,\" he told me. At the end it was as he had wished. His last words were 'I'm dying'.\"<ref name=\"carriere flickhead\" />  |source=Long-time friend and collaborator, [[Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re]]}}\nAfter the release of ''[[That Obscure Object of Desire]]'', Bu\u00f1uel retired from filmmaking.<ref name=\"McAdam\">{{cite web |last1=McAdam |first1=Conor |title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel is a Walking Contradiction |url=https://outtake.tribecashortlist.com/the-man-y-luis-bu%C3%B1uel-s-8260076236f0 |website=Outtake |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> In 1982, he wrote (along with Carri\u00e8re) his autobiography, ''Mon Dernier Soupir'' (''My Last Sigh''), which provides an account of his life, friends, and family as well as a representation of his eccentric personality. In it, he recounts dreams, encounters with many well-known writers, actors, and artists such as [[Pablo Picasso]] and [[Charlie Chaplin]] as well as antics, like dressing up as a nun and walking around town.<ref name=\"my last sigh\" />{{rp|p. 83}}\n\nIn his seventies, Bu\u00f1uel once told his friend, novelist [[Carlos Fuentes]]: \"I'm not afraid of death. I'm afraid of dying alone in a hotel room, with my bags open and a shooting script on the night table. I must know whose fingers will close my eyes.\"<ref name=\"fuentes discreet charm\">{{cite web|last1=Fuentes|first1=Carlos|title=The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeosie|url=https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/109-the-discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeosie|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel died in Mexico City in 1983 of [[cirrhosis of the liver]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1983/07/30/surrealist-spanish-filmmaker-luis-bunuel-83/ca199f00-ca7c-4925-92da-2db4fdff7adf/|title=Surrealist Spanish Filmmaker Luis Bunuel, 83|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> Fuentes has recounted that Bu\u00f1uel spent his last week in hospital discussing theology with the Jesuit brother Julian Pablo, a long time friend.<ref name=\"fuentes milky way\">{{cite web|last1=Fuentes|first1=Carlos|title=The Milky Way: The Heretic's Progress|url=https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/610-the-milky-way-the-heretic-s-progress|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> His funeral was very private, involving only family and close friends, among them poets [[Octavio Paz]] and [[Homero Aridjis]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aridjis |first1=Homero |title=Octavio Paz: The Poet in His Labyrinth |url=http://www.log24.com/log08/saved/080419-Paz.html |website=Log24.com |publisher=Journal Archives of Steven H. Cullinane |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Dead man laughing\">{{cite news |last1=Tuckman |first1=Jo |title=Dead man laughing |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/dec/29/art |accessdate=22 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited |date=28 Dec 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Technique and influences==\n{{main|Filmmaking technique of Luis Bu\u00f1uel}}\n[[File:SilviaPinalStatue.JPG|thumb|Silvia Pinal was one of Bu\u00f1uel's \"stock company\" of actors and was his preferred choice for the lead in his film ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'', a part which finally went to [[Catherine Deneuve]]<ref name=\"faulkner literary adaptations\">{{cite book|last1=Faulkner|first1=Sally|title=Literary Adaptations in Spanish Cinema|date=2004|publisher=Tamesis|location=London|isbn=978-1855660984|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yeMgJsea3-8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref> ]]\nBu\u00f1uel's technique of filmmaking was strongly influenced by mise-en-scene, sound editing and use of music. The influences on his filmmaking have included a positive relationship to surrealism and a critical approach to atheism and religion. Bu\u00f1uel's style of directing was extremely economical; he shot films in a few weeks, rarely deviating from his script (the scene in ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'' where [[Catherine Deneuve]] exposes her breasts to Saturno \u2013 but not the audience \u2013 being a noted exception) and shooting as much as possible in order to minimize editing time.<ref>{{cite book|last=Alexander|first=Sean|title=\"Luis Bu\u00f1uel\", in The Scarecrow Video Movie Guide|year=2004|publisher=Sasquatch Books|location=Seattle WA|isbn=978-1-57061-415-6|pages=31|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qiQLs-6SocC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>   He remained true throughout his working life to an operating philosophy that he articulated at the beginning of his career in 1928:  \"The guiding idea, the silent procession of images that are concrete, decisive, measured in space and time\u2014in a word, the film\u2014was first projected inside the brain of the filmmaker\".<ref name=\"an unspeakable betrayal\" />{{rp|p.135}}  In this, Bu\u00f1uel has been compared with [[Alfred Hitchcock]], another director famous for precision, efficiency and preplanning, for whom actually shooting the film was an anticlimax, since each man would know, in Bu\u00f1uel's words, \"exactly how each scene will be shot and what the final montage will be\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Stam|first=Robert|title=\"Hitchcock and Bu\u00f1uel: Authority, Desire and the Absurd\", in Hitchcock's Rereleased Films: From Rope to Vertigo, ed. by Walter Raubicheck and Walter Srebnick|year=1991|publisher=Wayne State University Press|location=Detroit|isbn=978-0-8143-2326-7|pages=117|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CfVeQ5BaPVsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  According to actress [[Jeanne Moreau]]:  \"He was the only director I know who never threw away a shot. He had the film in his mind. When he said 'action' and 'cut,' you knew that what was in between the two would be printed.\"<ref name=yakir>{{cite web|last1=Yakir|first1=Dan|title=Two Old Masters: Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://www.filmcomment.com/article/luis-bunuel-remembered|website=Film Comment|publisher=Film Society of Lincoln Center|accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Tributes==\n[[File:Instituto IES Luis Bu\u00f1uel.jpg|thumb|left|Instituto de Educaci\u00f3n Secundaria (IES) Luis Bu\u00f1uel, Zaragoza, Spain]]\n* In 1994, a retrospective of Bu\u00f1uel's works was organized by the [[Kunst- und Ausstellungshalle der Bundesrepublik Deutschland|Kunst- und Ausstellungshalle]] in Bonn, as homage to one of the most internationally revered figures in world cinema.<ref name=\"d'lugo\">{{cite book|last=D'Lugo|first=Marvin|title=\"Bu\u00f1uel in the Cathedral of Culture\" in Marsha Kinder (ed.), Luis Bu\u00f1uel's The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie|year=1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, New York|isbn=978-0-521-56831-9|pages=108}}</ref> {{rp|p.101}}  This was followed in the summer of 1996 by a commemoration of the centenary of the birth of cinema held by the [[Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof\u00eda]] in Madrid, which included a unique retrospective, jointly sponsored by the King of Spain and the President of Mexico, called ''\u00bfBu\u00f1uel!. La mirada del siglo'', honoring his special status as Spanish cinema's most emblematic figure.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u00bfBu\u00f1uel!. La mirada del siglo|url=http://www.museoreinasofia.es/publicaciones/catalogo.html?idPub=326|website=Cat\u00e1logo de publicaciones|publisher=Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof\u00eda|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref>[[File:Liceo Espa\u00f1ol Luis Bu\u00f1uel.jpg|thumb|[[Liceo Espa\u00f1ol Luis Bu\u00f1uel]]]]\n* A secondary school in [[Zaragoza]], Spain has been named for Bu\u00f1uel: Instituto de Educaci\u00f3n Secundaria Ies Luis Bu\u00f1uel.<ref>{{cite web|title=IES Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://iesluisbunuel.com/|publisher=iesluisbunuel.com/|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref> [[Liceo Espa\u00f1ol Luis Bu\u00f1uel]], a Spanish international school, is in [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], [[France]], near Paris.<ref>{{cite web|title=Historia del Liceo Espa\u00f1ol|url=http://www.educacion.gob.es/exterior/centros/luisbunuel/es/secretaria/historia.shtml|website=Liceo Espa\u00f1ol Luis Bu\u00f1uel|publisher=Gobierno de Espana. Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n* In [[Calanda, Spain]] a bust of the head of Luis Bu\u00f1uel is on display at the [[Centro Bu\u00f1uel Calanda]] (CBC), a museum devoted to the director.<ref>{{cite book|last=Simonis|first=Damien|title=Spain \u2013 ebook edition. 7th Edition|year=2009|publisher=Lonely Planet|location=Oakland, CA|isbn=978-1-74179-000-9|pages=467|url=https://books.google.com/?id=B1pFbOvxN1wC&pg=PA467&lpg=PA467&dq=Head+of+Luis+Bu%C3%B1uel+in+Centro+Bu%C3%B1uel+Calanda.#v=onepage}}</ref>  The mission of the CBC is to serve as a reference center both for connoisseurs of Bu\u00f1uel and for anyone interested in the arts of [[Aragon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=el CBC|url=http://www.cbcvirtual.com/menu.jsp|publisher=cbcvirtual.com|accessdate=9 August 2012}}</ref>\n* One of the main theatres at the [[Palais des Festivals et des Congr\u00e8s]], where the [[Cannes Film Festival]] is held, is named after him: ''Salle Bu\u00f1uel''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Acc\u00e8s aux projections|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/fr/festivalServices/festivalGuideTheatres.html|publisher=Festival de Cannes|accessdate=26 July 2012}}</ref>\n* To mark the centenary of his birth, in 2000 the Cannes festival partnered with the Spanish film industry, to pay tribute to Luis Bu\u00f1uel.  This tribute consisted of three events: (1) the inauguration, for Cannes 2000, of the Palace's new Luis Bu\u00f1uel room, (2) an original exhibition organized by L'Instituto de la Cinematograf\u00eda y de las Artes Audiovisuales entitled \"The Secret World of Bu\u00f1uel\", and (3) an exceptional projection of ''Viridiana'', the Palme d'Or winner in 1961, in the presence of specially invited artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tribute to Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/archives/evenementPresentation/id/76/title/evenementHommages/year/2000.html|website=Around the selection 2000|publisher=Festival de Cannes|accessdate=26 July 2012}}</ref>\n* The Luis Bu\u00f1uel Film Institute (LBFI) is housed in the [[The Downtown Independent|Downtown Independent Theatre]], Los Angeles, and has as its mission: \"to form the vital and innovative arena for the promotion of the work of Luis Bu\u00f1uel, and a seminal resource for the development of new research, knowledge and scholarship on his life and work, extending across his body of films and writings\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel Film Institute|url=http://www.luisbunuelfilminstitute.com/about.php|publisher=Luis Bu\u00f1uel Film Institute|accessdate=16 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921084950/http://luisbunuelfilminstitute.com/about.php|archive-date=21 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Characterizations==\nBu\u00f1uel has been portrayed as a character in many films and television productions.  A portion of the television mini-series ''Lorca, muerte de un poeta'' (1987\u20131988), directed by [[Juan Antonio Bardem]] recreates the student years of Bu\u00f1uel, Lorca and Dal\u00ed, with Fernando Valverde portraying Bu\u00f1uel in two episodes.<ref>{{cite web|last=Selas|first=Alejandro Reche|title=La Hispalense rendir\u00e1 homenaje a Bu\u00f1uel en marco del Festival de Cine|url=http://www.diariodesevilla.es/article/ocio/496982/la/hispalense/rendira/homenaje/bunuel/marco/festival/cine.html|website=Diario de Sevilla|publisher=[[Joly Digital]]|accessdate=7 August 2012}}</ref>  He was played by Dimiter Guerasimof in the 1991 biopic ''Dal\u00ed'', directed by [[Antoni Ribas]], despite the fact that Dal\u00ed and his attorney had written to Ribas objecting to the project in its early stages in 1985.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dal\u00ed se opone a un proyecto de pel\u00edcula de Antoni Ribas sobre el pintor|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1985/01/18/cultura/474850803_850215.html|accessdate=7 August 2012|newspaper=El Pais|date=18 January 1985}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel appeared as a character in Alejandro Pelayo's 1993 film ''Miroslava'', based on the life of actress [[Miroslava (actress)|Miroslava Stern]], who committed suicide after appearing in ''Ensayo de un crimen'' (1955).<ref>{{cite book|last=Montes Garces|first=Elizabeth|title=Relocating Identities in Latin American Cultures|year=2007|publisher=University of Calgary Press|location=Calgary|isbn=978-1-55238-209-7|pages=139\u2013140|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l0KA5n4Gm9UC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel was played by three actors, [[El Gran Wyoming]] (old age), Pere Arquillu\u00e9 (young adult) and Juan Carlos Jim\u00e9nez Mar\u00edn (child), in [[Carlos Saura]]'s 2001 fantasy, ''Bu\u00f1uel y la mesa del rey Salom\u00f3n'', which tells of Bu\u00f1uel, Lorca and Dal\u00ed setting out in search of the mythical table of King Salom\u00f3n, which is thought to have the power to see into the past, the present and the future.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bu\u00f1uel y la mesa del Rey Salom\u00f3n|url=http://www.clubcultura.com/clubcine/bunuel_saura/bunuel_saura1.htm|website=Noticias|publisher=ClubCine|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref>  Bu\u00f1uel was a character in a 2001 television miniseries ''[[Severo Ochoa]]: La conquista de un Nobel'', on the life of the Spanish [[\u00e9migr\u00e9]] and [[Nobel Prize]] winner in medicine, who was also at the Residencia de Estudiantes during Bu\u00f1uel's time there.<ref>{{cite web|title=Residencia de Estudiantes \u2013 History|url=http://www.residencia.csic.es/en/info/history.htm|publisher=Residencia de Estudiantes|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> [[Matt Lucas]] portrayed Bu\u00f1uel in Richard Curson Smith's 2002 TV movie ''Surrealissimo: The Scandalous Success of Salvador Dal\u00ed'', a comedy depicting Dal\u00ed's \"trial\" by the Surrealists in 1934 for his pro-Hitler sympathies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rojas|first=Carlos|title=Salvador Dal\u00ed, Or The Art of Spitting on Your Mother's Portrait|year=1993|publisher=Penn State Press|location=University Park PA|isbn=978-0-271-00842-4|pages=98|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MWF5s2yfFqwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>  A 2005 short called ''[[The Death of Salvador Dali]]'', directed by Delaney Bishop, contains sequences in which Bu\u00f1uel appears, played by Alejandro Cardenas.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Death of Salvador Dali \u2013 Press release|url=http://www.dalimovie.com/Press.html|publisher=dalimovie.com|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> [[Paul Morrison (director)|Paul Morrison]]'s ''[[Little Ashes]]'' hypothesizes a love affair between Dal\u00ed and Lorca, with Bu\u00f1uel (played by [[Matthew McNulty]]) looking on suspiciously.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=David|title=Were Spain's two artistic legends secret gay lovers?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/oct/28/spain.books|accessdate=8 August 2012|newspaper=The Observer|date=27 October 2007|location=London}}</ref> Bu\u00f1uel, played by Adrien de Van, is one of many notable personalities encountered by [[Woody Allen]]'s protagonist in ''[[Midnight in Paris]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite news|last=Berger|first=Joseph|title=Decoding Woody Allen's ''Midnight in Paris''|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/28/movies/midnight-in-paris-a-historical-view.html|accessdate=8 August 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=27 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nBu\u00f1uel was given the Career Golden Lion in 1982 by the [[Venice Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Golden Lion for Career Achievement |url=http://www.carnivalofvenice.com/the-city/events-in-venice/venice-film-festival/awards-and-acknowledgements/golden-lion/golden-lion-for-career-achievement?lang=en |website=Portale di Venezia |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> and the [[International Federation of Film Critics|FIPRESCI Prize]] \u2013 Honorable Mention in 1969 by the [[Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Berlinale - International Film Festival Berlin |url=https://www.inter-film.org/festivals/berlinale-international-film-festival-berlin |website=inter-film |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> In 1977, he received the [[National Prize for Arts and Sciences]] for Fine Arts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Salazar |first1=David |title=Famed Mexican Auteur Arturo Ripstein's 'Bleak Street' Gets US Run |url=https://www.latinpost.com/articles/104216/20151223/famed-mexican-auteur-arturo-ripsteins-bleak-street-gets-run.htm |website=Latin Post |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> At the [[11th Moscow International Film Festival]] in 1979, he was awarded the Honorable Prize for his contribution to cinema.<ref name=\"Moscow1979\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1979 |title=11th Moscow International Film Festival (1979) |accessdate=20 January 2013 |website=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403102012/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1979 |archivedate=3 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{main|Luis Bu\u00f1uel filmography}}\n\n=== Documentaries about Bu\u00f1uel ===\n* ''Dans l'oeil de Luis Bu\u00f1uel''. France, 2013, 54 min., book and director: Fran\u00e7ois L\u00e9vy-Kuentz, Producer: KUIV Productions, arte France.\n* ''El \u00faltimo gui\u00f3n \u2013 Bu\u00f1uel en la memoria''. Spain, Germany, France, 2008, 45 min., Book and director: Javier Espada und Gaizka Urresti, Producer: Imval Producciones\n* ''Tras Nazar\u00edn (Following Nazar\u00edn)''.  Spain/Mexico, 2015. Directed by Javier Espada. Ircania Producciones. Utilizes still photos taken by Bu\u00f1uel and [[Manuel \u00c1lvarez Bravo]] to link the images of the film to the Mexican countryside. Includes interviews with Jean Claude Carri\u00e8re,  [[Ignacio L\u00f3pez Tarso]],  Silvia Pinal, [[Arturo Ripstein]] and [[Carlos Reygadas]], along with critics and film scholars.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tras Nazar\u00edn (Following Nazar\u00edn) |url=https://www.moma.org/calendar/events/6633 |website=MoMA |publisher=Museum of Modern Art}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Luis Bu\u00f1uel}}\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|onlinebooks=yes|about=yes|wikititle=Luis Bu\u00f1uel}}\n\n{{Portal|Film}}\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Art film]]\n* [[Cinema of Mexico]]\n* [[Cinema of Spain]]\n* [[Experimental film]]\n* [[Generation of '27]]\n* [[List of atheists in film, radio, television and theater]]\n* [[List of banned films]]\n* [[Satire]]\n* [[Surrealism]]\n* [[Surrealist cinema]]\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{See also|Luis Bu\u00f1uel bibliography}}\n* J. Francisco Aranda ''Luis Bu\u00f1uel: Biografia Critica'' (Spanish Edition) Paperback: 479 pages. Publisher: Lumen; Nueva ed. rev. y aumentada edition (1975) . Language: Spanish . {{ISBN|8426410553}}. {{ISBN|978-8426410559}}.\n*Robert Bresson and Luis Bu\u00f1uel. ''La politica de los autores/ The Politics of Authors'' (La Memoria Del Cine) (Spanish Edition) Paidos Iberica Ediciones S a (April 2003), 189 pages, {{ISBN|8449314143}}\n* Luis Bu\u00f1uel, ''Mi Ultimo Suspiro'' (English translation ''My Last Sigh'' [[Alfred A. Knopf]], 1983).\n*{{cite book|last=Bu\u00f1uel|first=Luis|title=An Unspeakable Betrayal: Selected Writings of Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tK3KPgv34U8C|date=1 March 2002|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-23423-9}}\n* Luis Bu\u00f1uel, Manuel Lopez Villegas. ''Escritos de Luis Bunuel (Fundidos En Negro / Fused in Black)'' (Spanish Edition), Editorial Paginas de Espuma; Paperback, February 2, 2000, 296 pp,{{ISBN|8493124303}}\n* Luis Bu\u00f1uel, Raf\u00e6l Bu\u00f1uel, Juan Luis Bu\u00f1uel (Afterword). ''An Unspeakable Betrayal: Selected Writings of Luis Bu\u00f1uel.'' Publisher: University of California Press; First edition (April 6, 2000), pp 277, {{ISBN|0520208404}}\n* [https://www.amazon.es/Luis-Bunuel-1929-1939-Wisconsin-Studies/dp/0299284743 ''Luis Bu\u00f1uel: The Red Years, 1929\u20131939'' (Wisconsin Film Studies).]\n*Luis Bu\u00f1uel. ''El discreto encanto de la burguesia (Coleccion Voz imagen'', Serie cine ; 26) (Spanish Edition) Paperback \u2013 159 pages, Publisher: Ayma; 1. ed edition (1973), {{ISBN|8420912646}}\n*Luis Bu\u00f1uel. ''El fantasma de la libertad'' (Serie cine) (Spanish Edition) Serie cine Paperback,  Publisher: Ayma; 1. ed edition (1975) 148 pages, {{ISBN|8420912840}}\n*Luis Bu\u00f1uel. ''Obra literaria'' (Spanish Edition) Publisher: Heraldo de Aragon (1982),291 pages, {{ISBN|8485492749}}\n*Luis Bu\u00f1uel. ''L'Age d'or: Correspondance Luis Bunuel-Charles de Noailles : lettres et documents (1929\u20131976'') (Les Cahiers du Musee national d'art moderne)  Centre Georges Pompidou (publ), 1993, pp 190, {{ISBN|2858507457}}\n* Froylan Enciso, ''En defensa del poeta Bu\u00f1uel, en Andar fronteras. El servicio diplom\u00e1tico de Octavio Paz en Francia (1946\u20131951)'', Siglo XXI, 2008, pp.&nbsp;130\u2013134 y 353\u2013357.\n*{{cite book|last=Durgnat|first=Raymond|title=Luis Bunuel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_lbzZWIbgwkC|year=1977|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-03424-2}}\n* Javier Espada y Elena Cervera, ''M\u00e9xico fotografiado por Luis Bu\u00f1uel''.\n* Javier Espada y Elena Cervera, ''Bu\u00f1uel. Entre 2 Mundos''.\n* Javier Espada y Asier Mensuro, ''Album fotografico de la familia Bu\u00f1uel''.\n*{{cite book|last1=Gubern|first1=Rom\u00e1n|last2=Hammond|first2=Paul|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel: The Red Years, 1929\u20131939|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=elueEkeLL_oC|date=4 January 2012|publisher=University of Wisconsin Pres|isbn=978-0-299-28474-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Higginbotham|first=Virginia|title=Luis Bu\u00f1uel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WalZAAAAMAAJ|year=1979|publisher=Twayne Publishers|isbn=978-0-8057-9261-4}}\n* Michael Koller [https://web.archive.org/web/20101225061923/http://archive.sensesofcinema.com/contents/cteq/01/12/chien.html \"Un Chien Andalou\", ''Senses of Cinema'' January 2001] Retrieved on 26 July 2006.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = L\u00f3pez | first1 = Ignacio Javier | year = 2001 | title = The Old Age of William Tell: A Study of Bu\u00f1uel's '\"Tristana\"' | url = | journal = [[Modern Language Notes|MLN]] | volume = 116 | issue = 2| pages = 295\u2013314 | doi=10.1353/mln.2001.0023}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = L\u00f3pez | first1 = Ignacio Javier | year = 2003 | title = Film, Freud and Paranoia: Dal\u00ed and the Representation of Male Desire in ''An Andalusian Dog'' | url = | journal = [[Diacritics (journal)|Diacritics]] | volume = 31 | issue = 2| pages = 35\u201348 | doi = 10.1353/dia.2003.0010 }}\n*{{cite book|last1=Santaolalla|first1=Isabel|last2=Evans|first2=Peter William|title=Luis Bunuel: New Readings| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lH2GAAAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=British Film Institute|isbn=978-1-84457-003-4}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{External links|section|date=May 2017}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000320|Luis Bu\u00f1uel}}\n* [http://www.luisbunuelfilminstitute.com/ The Luis Bu\u00f1uel Film Institute]\n* [http://www.sensesofcinema.com/2005/great-directors/bunuel/ Senses of Cinema: Great Directors Critical Database]\n* [http://www.theyshootpictures.com/bunuelluis.htm They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?]\n* ''La furia umana'', n\u00b06, multilanguage dossier (texts by Gilberto Perez, Adrian Martin, Toni D'Angela, Alberto Abruzzese and others) * * \n* [http://www.lafuriaumana.it/index.php/archive/53-la-furia-umana-nd-6-autumn-2010- ''La furia umana'']\n* [http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/MRC/Bunuelbib.html Bunuel Bibliography (via UC Berkeley)]\n* [http://www.1worldfilms.com/luis_bunuel.htm Bu\u00f1uel biography]\n\n{{Luis Bu\u00f1uel}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Luis Bu\u00f1uel\n| list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestForeignLanguageFilm 1961\u20131980}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Screenplay}}\n{{Prix de la mise en scene 1946\u20131959}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Director}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Director}}\n}}\n{{Surrealism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bunuel, Luis}}\n[[Category:Luis Bu\u00f1uel| ]]\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:Anti-Catholicism in Spain]]\n[[Category:Aragonese film directors]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Foreign Language Film Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Director Ariel Award winners]]\n[[Category:Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Director winners]]\n[[Category:Complutense University of Madrid alumni]]\n[[Category:Critics of religions]]\n[[Category:Directors of Palme d'Or winners]]\n[[Category:Directors of Golden Lion winners]]\n[[Category:Exiles of the Spanish Civil War in Mexico]]\n[[Category:French atheists]]\n[[Category:French experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:French film directors]]\n[[Category:Golden Ariel Award winners]]\n[[Category:Mexican atheists]]\n[[Category:Mexican experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Mexican film directors]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Mexico]]\n[[Category:People from Calanda]]\n[[Category:Silent film directors]]\n[[Category:Spanish atheists]]\n[[Category:Spanish experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Spanish film directors]]\n[[Category:Spanish Marxists]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of the Spanish Civil War (Republican faction)]]\n[[Category:Spanish surrealist artists]]\n[[Category:Surrealist filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cirrhosis]]\n", "name_user": "Masato.harada", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMexico (1946\u20131953)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luis_Bu%C3%B1uel"}
{"title_page": "U Thant", "text_new": "{{short description|Third Secretary-General of the United Nations}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}}\n{{Burmese name|U|\"U Thant\" in Burmese is the same as saying \"Mr. Thant\" in English=}}    ''Side-note:'' \"U Thant''\" in Burmese is the same as'' \"Mr. Thant\" ''in English.'' {{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix    = [[His Excellency]] [[Burmese names#Honorifics|U]]\n| name                = Thant\n|native_name   = {{nobold|{{my|\u101e\u1014\u1037\u103a}}}}\n| nationality = [[Bamar|Burmese]]\n| image = U Thant (1963).jpg\n| caption = U Thant in 1963\n| alt = Official portrait of U Thant with a UN flag in the background. \n| order = 3rd [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]]\n| term_start = 30 November 1961\n| term_end = 31 December 1971\n| predecessor = [[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]]\n| successor = [[Kurt Waldheim]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1909|1|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Pantanaw]], [[British rule in Burma|Burma]], [[British Raj|British India]]\n| death_date = {{nowrap|{{death date and age|1974|11|25|1909|1|22|df=yes}}}}\n| death_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n| death_cause = Lung cancer\n| resting_place = [[Kandawmin Garden Mausolea]], [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]]\n| parents = {{unbulleted list |Po Hnit |Nan Thaung}}\n| spouse = Daw Thein Tin (died 1989)\n| children = {{unbulleted list |Maung Bo |Tin Maung Thant |Aye Aye Thant}}\n| relations = {{unbulleted list|Khant {{small|(brother)}} |Thaung {{small|(brother)}} |Tin Maung {{small|(brother)}} |[[Thant Myint-U]] {{small|(grandson)}}}}\n| signature = U Thant Signature.svg\n}}\n{{Burmese characters}}\n\n'''Thant''' ({{IPAc-en|\u03b8|\u0251\u02d0|n|t}}; {{MYname|MY=\u101e\u1014\u1037\u103a|MLCTS=san.}}; {{IPA-my|\u03b8a\u0330\u0270\u0303|IPA}}; 22 January 1909 \u2013 25 November 1974), known honorifically as '''U Thant''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|u\u02d0|_|\u02c8|\u03b8|\u0251\u02d0|n|t}}),{{efn|\"[[Burmese names#Honorifics|U]]\" is an [[honorific]] in [[Burmese language|Burmese]], roughly equal to \"Mr\". \"Thant\" was his only name, per Burmese convention. In Burmese, he was known as '''Pantanaw U Thant''', in reference to his hometown, Pantanaw.}} was a [[Burma|Burmese]] diplomat and the [[Secretary-General of the United Nations#Secretaries-General|third Secretary-General]] of the [[United Nations]] from 1961 to 1971, the first non-[[Scandinavia]]n to hold the position. He held the office for a record 10 years and one month (3,683 days) (taking into account a one-month vacancy in November\u2013December 1966).<ref>[https://www.un.org/sg/en/content/u-thant UN website's biography of Thant]</ref>\n\nA native of [[Pantanaw]], Thant was educated at the National High School and at [[Rangoon University]]. In the days of tense political climate in Burma, he held moderate views positioning himself between fervent nationalists and British loyalists. He was a close friend of Burma's first Prime Minister [[U Nu]] and served in various positions in Nu's cabinet from 1948 to 1961. Thant had a calm and unassuming demeanor that won his colleagues' respect.{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=147}}\n\nHe was appointed as Secretary-General in 1961, when his predecessor [[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]] [[1961 Ndola United Nations DC-6 crash|died in an air crash]]. In his first term, Thant facilitated negotiations between U.S. President [[John F. Kennedy]] and Soviet premier [[Nikita Khrushchev]] during the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] of 1962, helping to avert a global catastrophe. Later, in December that year, Thant ordered [[Operation Grandslam]], which ended a secessionist insurgency in [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Congo]]. He was reappointed as Secretary-General on 2 December 1966 by a unanimous vote of the Security Council. During his second term Thant was well known for publicly criticizing American conduct in the [[Vietnam War]]. He oversaw the entry of several newly independent African and Asian states into the UN. He refused to serve a third term, and retired in 1971.\n\nThant died of [[lung cancer]] in 1974. A devout [[Buddhist]] and the foremost Burmese diplomat on the international stage, he was widely admired and held in great respect by the Burmese populace. When the military government refused him any honours, riots broke out in Rangoon; these were violently crushed by the government, leaving scores of casualties.\n\n== Early life ==\n[[File:U Thant in 1927.PNG|thumb|left|Thant as a [[Rangoon University]] student in 1927]]\n\nThant, the eldest of four sons, was born in [[Pantanaw]], colonial Burma, to a moderately wealthy family of landowners and rice merchants. His father Po Hnit, who had been educated in [[Calcutta]], was the only person in the town who could communicate well in English.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=29}} He was a founding member of the [[Burma Research Society]] and had helped establish ''[[The Sun (Rangoon)|The Sun]]'' (''Thuriya'') newspaper in Rangoon. {{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=29}}<ref name=\"mm\">{{cite book |title=Dr. Maung Maung: Gentleman, Scholar, Patriot |editor=Robert H. Taylor |publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies |year=2008 |pages=211\u2013212 |isbn=978-981-230-409-4}}</ref> Although his family members were ethnic [[Bamar people|Bamars]] and devout [[Buddhist]]s, Thant's father, according to Thant Myint-U (U Thant's grandson), had distant ancestors who were \"people from both India and China, Buddhists and Muslims, as well as Shans and Mons\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Where China Meets India: Burma and the New Crossroad of Asia |publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux |author=Thant Myint-U |year=2011 |location=New York |pages=76 |isbn=978-0-374-98408-3 |author-link=Thant Myint-U}}</ref> He hoped that all his four sons would each earn a degree.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=32}} His other sons, Khant, Thaung, and Tin Maung went on to become politicians and scholars.<ref name=\"mm\"/>\n\nPo Hnit had collected a personal library of various American and British books and cultivated a reading habit among his children. As a result Thant became an avid reader and his school friends nicknamed him \"The Philosopher\".{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=144}} Apart from reading, he enjoyed various sports including hiking, swimming and playing [[chinlone]].{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=33}} He went to the National High School in Pantanaw. At the age of eleven Thant participated in strikes against the University Act of 1920. He dreamed of becoming a journalist and surprised the family by writing an article for the ''[[Union of Burma Boy Scouts]]'' magazine. When Thant was fourteen, his father died and a series of inheritance disputes forced Thant's mother, Nan Thaung, and her four children into difficult financial times.<ref>Franda, Marcus F. (2006). ''The United Nations in the 21st century: management and reform processes in a troubled organization''. Rowman & Littlefield. p. 53. {{ISBN|978-0-7425-5334-7}}.</ref>\n\nAfter the death of his father, Thant believed he would not be able to complete a four-year degree and instead worked for a two-year teaching certificate at Rangoon University in 1926. As the eldest son he had to fulfill his filial duties and responsibilities to the family. At university, Thant, together with Nu, the future Prime Minister of Burma, studied history under [[D. G. E. Hall]]. Nu was told by a distant mutual relative to take care of Thant and the two soon became close friends.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=88}} Thant was elected joint secretary of the University Philosophical Association and secretary of the Literary and Debating Society.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=89}} In Rangoon, Thant met [[John Sydenham Furnivall|J.S. Furnivall]], the founder of The Burma Book Club and ''[[The World of Books]]'' magazine, to which Thant regularly contributed. Promising a good post, Furnivall urged Thant to complete four-year university course and join Civil Service but Thant refused.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=93}} After earning the certificate, he returned to Pantanaw to teach at the National High School as a senior teacher in 1928. He contacted Furnivall and Nu regularly, writing articles and participating in ''The World of Books'' translation competitions.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=94}}\n\nIn 1931, Thant won first place in All Burma Teachership Examination and became the school's headmaster by the age of twenty-five.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=97}}{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}} Urged by Thant, his friend Nu took the local superintendent of schools position. Thant regularly contributed to several newspapers and magazines under the pen name \"Thilawa\" and translated a number of books, including one on the [[League of Nations]].<ref>Naing, Saw Yan (January 22, 2009). [http://www.irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=14975 Remembering U Thant and His Achievements]. ''[[The Irrawaddy]]''.</ref> His major influences were Sir [[Stafford Cripps]], [[Sun Yat-sen]] and [[Mahatma Gandhi]].{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=144}} In the days of tense political climate in Burma, Thant stood moderate grounds between fervent nationalists and British loyalists.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}}\n\n== Civil servant ==\n[[File:U Nu with U Thant.jpg|thumb|Thant with U Nu in 1955 on an early morning walk]]\nDuring the World War II, the Japanese occupied Burma from 1942 to 1945. They brought Thant to Rangoon to lead the Educational Reorganizing Committee. However, Thant did not have any real power, and returned to Pantanaw. When the Japanese ordered making Japanese compulsory in Pantanaw high schools, Thant defied the orders and cooperated with the growing anti-Japanese resistance.{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=145}}\n\nIn 1948, Burma gained independence from the United Kingdom. Nu became the prime minister of the newly independent Burma and appointed Thant as director of broadcasting in 1948. By then, civil war had broken out. The Karen insurgency began and Thant risked his life to go to Karen camps to negotiate for peace. The negotiations broke down, and in 1949 the advancing insurgents burned his hometown, including his house. The insurgents pushed the front to within four miles of the capital Rangoon before they were beaten back. In the following year, Thant was appointed secretary to the government of Burma in the [[Ministry of Information (Burma)|Ministry of Information]]. From 1951 to 1957, Thant was secretary to the prime minister, writing speeches for U Nu, arranging his foreign travel, and meeting foreign visitors. During this entire period, he was U Nu's closest confidant and advisor.{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=145}}\n\nHe also took part in a number of international conferences and was the secretary of the 1955 [[Bandung Conference]] in [[Indonesia]], which gave birth to the [[Non-Aligned Movement]]. From 1957 to 1961, he was Burma's permanent representative to the United Nations and became actively involved in negotiations over [[Nationalism and resistance in Algeria|Algerian independence]]. In 1961, Thant was named Chairman of the UN Congo Commission. The Burmese government awarded him the title ''Maha Thray Sithu'' as a commander in the [[Pyidaungsu Sithu Thingaha|order of Pyidaungsu Sithu]].<ref>H.W. Wilson Company (1962). ''Current biography, Volume 23.'' H. W. Wilson Co.</ref>\n\n== United Nations Secretary-General ==\n[[File:U Thant swearing in.jpg|thumb|Thant swearing in to the United Nations Secretariet|left]]\n\nIn September 1961, United Nations Secretary-General [[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]] was killed [[1961 Ndola United Nations DC-6 crash|in a plane crash]] ''en route'' to Congo. The Security Council hurriedly searched for a new Secretary-General, but over the next few weeks it was in a deadlock, with the United States and the Soviet Union unable to agree on any candidate proposed by other members. The superpowers backed down when representatives from smaller nations and the Non-Aligned Movement proposed Thant to fill Hammarskj\u00f6ld's unexpired term.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}} On 3 November 1961, Thant was unanimously appointed as acting Secretary-General by the [[United Nations General Assembly|General Assembly]], on the recommendation of the [[UN Security Council|Security Council]] in [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 168|Resolution 168]]. On 30 November 1961, the General Assembly unanimously appointed him secretary-general for a term of office ending on 3 November 1966. During his first term, he was widely credited for his role in defusing the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] and for ending the [[Congo Crisis|civil war in the Congo]]. He also said that he wanted to ease tensions between major powers while serving at the UN.<ref>[http://www.upi.com/Audio/Year_in_Review/Events-of-1962/1962-Elections,-Other-Events/12295509437657-7/#title \"1962 In Review]. [[United Press International]].</ref>\n\n=== First term: Cuban Missile Crisis and War in Congo ===\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = At a critical moment\u2014when the nuclear powers seemed set on a collision course\u2014the Secretary-General's intervention led to the diversion of the Soviet ships headed for Cuba and interception by our Navy. This was the indispensable first step in the peaceful resolution of the Cuban crisis.\n |source = \u2014[[Adlai Stevenson II|Adlai Stevenson]], Senate Foreign Relations Committee 88th Congress, March 13, 1963{{Sfn|Dorn & Pauk|2009|p=265}}\n |width  = 25%\n |align  = right}}\n[[File:U Thant and John F. Kennedy.PNG|thumb|Thant shakes hands with [[John F. Kennedy]] during his visit to the UN Headquarters.]]\n\nIn less than one year in office, Thant faced a critical challenge to defuse the Cuban Missile Crisis, the moment when the world came closest to a nuclear war. On 20 October 1962, two days before public announcements were made, U.S President [[John F. Kennedy]] showed Thant [[Lockheed U-2|U-2]] aerial reconnaissance photographs of Soviet missile installations in Cuba. The President then ordered a naval \"quarantine\" to remove all offensive weapons from Soviet ships bound for Cuba. Meanwhile, Soviet ships were approaching the quarantine zone. To avoid a naval confrontation, Thant proposed that the U.S should make non-invasion guarantees in exchange for missile withdrawal from the Soviet Union. Soviet Premier Khrushchev welcomed the proposal, which formed the basis of further negotiations.{{Sfn|Dorn & Pauk|2012|p=80}} Khrushchev further agreed to suspend missile shipments while the negotiations were ongoing.<ref name=\"nyt62\">{{cite news |title=Kennedy Agrees to Talks on Thant Plan, Khrushchev Accepts It; Blockade Goes On; Russian Tanker Intercepted and Cleared |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/97/10/19/home/crisis-26.html |accessdate=7 April 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=26 October 1962}}</ref> However, on 27 October 1962, a U-2 plane was shot down over Cuba, deepening the crisis. Kennedy was under intense pressure to invade from the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the [[EXCOMM|Executive Committee]] (ExComm). Kennedy hoped Thant would play the role of mediator and subsequently replied to ExComm and the Joint Chiefs, \"On the other hand we have U Thant, and we don't want to sink a ship...right in the middle of when U Thant is supposedly arranging for the Russians to stay out.\"{{Sfn|Dorn & Pauk|2009|p=273}}\n\nNegotiations continued. The U.S agreed to dismantle missiles in Turkey and guaranteed never to invade Cuba in exchange for removal of Soviet missiles in Cuba. Thant flew to Cuba and discussed with [[Fidel Castro]] allowing UN missile inspectors and the return of the body of the downed U-2 pilot. Castro, furious that the Soviets had agreed to remove missiles without his knowledge, categorically rejected any UN inspectors, although he did return the pilot's body. The inspection was done at sea by US reconnaissance aircraft and warships. The crisis was resolved and a war between superpowers was averted.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}}{{Sfn|Dorn & Pauk|2009|p=292}}\n\nAlthough a manifest pacifist and a devout Buddhist, Thant did not hesitate to use force when required. During the Congo Civil War in 1962, Katangan secessionists led by [[Moise Tshombe]] repeatedly attacked UN Operation in the Congo forces (ONUC). In December 1962, after ONUC suffered a sustained four-day attack in Katanga, Thant ordered the \"[[Operation Grandslam]]\" to gain \"complete freedom of movement for ONUC all over Katanga.\" The operation proved to be decisive and ended the secessionist insurgency once and for all. By January 1963, the secessionist capital Elizabethville was under full UN control.{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=161}} In his speech at the [[Columbia University]] Thant expressed expectation of completion of the [[United Nations Operation in the Congo]] in mid 1964.<ref name=\"Institut\">Tomanovi\u0107, M. (1965). ''Hronika me\u0111unarodnih doga\u0111aja 1964''. [[Belgrade]]. [http://www.diplomacy.bg.ac.rs/index_en.php Institute of International Politics and Economics], p.223. (in [[Serbo-Croatian]])</ref>\n\nFor his role in defusing the Cuban crisis and other peacekeeping efforts, the Norwegian Permanent Representative of the United Nations informed Thant that he would be awarded the 1965 Nobel Peace prize. He humbly replied, \"Is not the Secretary-General merely doing his job when he works for peace?\"{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=147}} On the other hand, Chairman [[Gunnar Jahn]] of the Nobel Peace prize committee lobbied heavily against giving Thant the prize which was at the last minute awarded to [[UNICEF]]. The rest of the committee all wanted the prize to go to Thant. The disagreement lasted three years and in 1966 and 1967 no prize was given, with Gunnar Jahn effectively vetoing an award to Thant.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lundestad |first1=Geir |title=The Nobel Peace Prize, 1901-2000 |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/themes/peace/lundestad-review/ |website=nobelprize.org |accessdate=7 April 2018 |quote=In 1965 and 1966 a majority of the committee clearly favored giving the prize to the third Secretary General, U Thant, and even to the first, Norway's Trygve Lie, but chairman Jahn more or less vetoed this.}}</ref> Outraged, Thant's undersecretary and Nobel Prize laureate [[Ralph Bunche]] called Gunnar Jahn's decision \"gross injustice to U Thant.\"{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=147}}\n\nOn Christmas Eve 1963, intercommunal clashes broke out in Cyprus. Turkish Cypriots withdrew into their enclaves, leaving the central government wholly under Greek Cypriot control. A \"peace-making force\" established under British command was unable to put an end to the fighting, and a conference on Cyprus held in London in January 1964 ended in disagreement. On 4 March 1964, amid the danger of broader hostilities, the Security Council unanimously authorized Thant to establish a UN Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP), with a limited three-month mandate to prevent the recurrence of fighting and to restore order. The Council further asked the secretary-general to appoint a mediator to seek a peaceful settlement of the Cyprus problem. Thant appointed Galo Plaza Lasso as mediator but when his report was rejected by Turkey in March 1965, Plaza resigned and the function of mediator lapsed.<ref name=nc/>\n\nIn April 1964, Thant accepted the [[Holy See]]'s designation of itself as a [[permanent observer]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCann |first1=Eamonn |title=How did the Holy See get recognition as a state? It just did |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/how-did-the-holy-see-get-recognition-as-a-state-it-just-did-1.1664452 |accessdate=7 April 2018 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=23 January 2014 |quote=In March 1964 pope Paul VI wrote to UN secretary general U Thant saying he was minded to appoint a permanent observer. In April, U Thant wrote back saying, in effect, fair enough, come ahead.}}</ref> There appeared to be no involvement of the General Assembly or the UN Security Council in the decision.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kissling |first1=F. |last2=Shannon |first2=D. |title=Church and state at the United Nations. A case of the emperor's new clothes. |journal=Conscience (Washington, D.C.) |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=11\u20132 |pmid=12178922 |year=1996}}</ref>\n\n=== Second term: Arab\u2013Israeli conflict and Vietnam War===\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = After the Six-Day War, [Thant] allowed himself to become a convenient scapegoat for international inaction, accepting this unenviable role with as much Buddhist detachment as could be summoned.\n |source = \u2014[[Walter Dorn]], 2007{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=177}}\n |width  = 25%\n |align  = right}}\nThant was re-appointed secretary-general of the United Nations by the General Assembly on 2 December 1966, on the unanimous recommendation of the Security Council. His term of office continued until 31 December 1971, when he retired. During his time in office he oversaw the entry into the UN of dozens of new Asian and African states, and was a firm opponent of [[apartheid]] in South Africa. He also established many of the UN's development and environmental agencies, funds and programmes, including the [[UN Development Programme]] (UNDP), the [[UN University]], the [[United Nations Conference on Trade and Development]], [[United Nations Institute for Training and Research]] (UNITAR), and the [[UN Environmental Programme]]. The [[Six-Day War]] between [[Arab]] countries and [[Israel]], the [[Prague Spring]] and subsequent Soviet invasion of [[Czechoslovakia]], and the [[Bangladesh Liberation War|Indo\u2013Pakistani War]] of 1971 leading to the birth of [[Bangladesh]] all took place during his tenure as secretary-general.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}}\n\n[[File:U-Thant 2.jpg|thumb|right|Thant meets with U.S President Lyndon B. Johnson in the Cabinet Room of the White House on 21 February 1968.]]\n\nHe was criticized in the US and Israel for agreeing to pull UNEF troops out of the [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]] in 1967 in response to a request from [[Egypt]]ian president [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|Nasser]].<ref>Rikhye, Indar Jit (1980). ''The Sinai Blunder: Withdrawal of the United Nations Emergency Force leading to the Six-Day War of June 1967''. Routledge. {{ISBN|978-0-7146-3136-3}}.</ref> The Permanent Representative of Egypt had informed Thant that the Egyptian government had decided to terminate UNEF's presence in the Sinai and the Gaza Strip, and requested steps that would withdraw the force as soon as possible, which Thant was obligated to accept. The UN afterwards stated, \"Because Israel refused to accept UNEF on its territory, the Force had to be deployed only on the Egyptian side of the border, and thus its functioning was entirely contingent upon the consent of Egypt as the host country. Once that consent was withdrawn, its operation could no longer be maintained.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/peacekeeping/missions/past/unef1backgr2.html |title=Middle East UNEF: Background |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=23 May 2014}}</ref> Thant, by flying to [[Cairo]] in a last-minute peace effort, tried to persuade Nasser not to go to war with Israel.\n\nIn Israel, his abrupt unilateral withdrawal of UNEF without any diplomatic process or wider consultation was regarded as a violation of United Nations assurances and commitments given to Israel in 1957, on the basis of which Israel had withdrawn from Sinai and Gaza at that time,<ref>''Abba Eban: An Autobiography'' by Abba Eban (Random House, 1977), pp. 321\u2013322</ref> and it \"thereafter inspired Israel's refusal to place her vital interests again in United Nations hands\".<ref>''Abba Eban: An Autobiography'' by Abba Eban (Random House, 1977), p. 323</ref>\n\nThe Cyprus crisis resurfaced in November 1967, but Turkey's threatened military intervention was averted, largely as a result of US opposition. Negotiations conducted by Cyrus Vance for the US and Jos\u00e9 Rolz-Bennett on behalf of the secretary-general led to a settlement. Intercommunal talks began in June 1968, through the good offices of the secretary-general, as part of the settlement. The talks bogged down, but Thant proposed a formula for their reactivation under the auspices of his special representative, B.F. Osorio-Tafall, and they were resumed in 1972, after Thant had left office.<ref name=nc>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationsencyclopedia.com/United-Nations/The-Secretary-General-DEVELOPMENTS-UNDER-U-THANT-1961-1971.html#b |title=The Secretary-General \u2013 Developments under U Thant, 1961\u20131971 |publisher=National Encyclopedia |accessdate=24 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nThant's once good relationship with the US government deteriorated rapidly when he publicly criticized American conduct of the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>Dennen, Leon (August 12, 1968). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ttEdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=b0YEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4623,4372187&dq= U Thant Speaks No Evil on Czech Crisis]. ''Daily News''.</ref> His secret attempts at direct peace talks between [[federal government of the United States|Washington]] and [[Hanoi]] were eventually rejected by the [[Lyndon B. Johnson|Johnson]] Administration.\n\nIn 1971, the participation of the [[People's Republic of China]] in the United Nations, which was a long-standing problem, was realized. Thant sent a message to the Chinese government asking China to send a delegation.<ref>{{cite news |work=The New York Times |date=1971-10-28 |title=Thant Asks China to Name Delegate to Council Soon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/10/28/archives/thant-asks-china-to-name-delegate-to-council-soon-thant-urges-china.htmlfirst=Tad |last=Szulc |accessdate=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Retirement ===\nOn 23 January 1971, Thant categorically announced that he would \"under no circumstances\" be available for a third term as secretary-general. The UN Security Council was deadlocked for many weeks in the search for a successor before finally settling \u2013 on 21 December 1971 \u2013 on [[Kurt Waldheim]]. The date was Waldheim's 53rd birthday, and just ten days before Thant's second term was to end.\n\nUnlike his two predecessors, Thant retired after ten years on speaking terms with all the big powers. In 1961, when he was first appointed, the [[Soviet Union]] tried to insist on a ''troika'' formula of three secretaries-general, one representing each [[Cold War]] bloc, to maintain equality in the United Nations between the superpowers. By 1966, when Thant was reappointed, all the big powers, in a unanimous vote of the Security Council, affirmed the importance of the secretary-generalship and his good offices, a clear tribute to Thant's work.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}}\n\nIn his farewell address to the United Nations General Assembly, Secretary-General Thant stated that he felt a \"great sense of relief bordering on liberation\" on relinquishing the \"burdens of office\".<ref name=\"NYTObit\">{{cite news |last1=Whitman |first1=Alden |title=U Thant Is Dead of Cancer at 65 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/11/26/archives/u-thant-is-dead-of-cancer-at-65-ut-thant-is-dead-of-cancer-united.html |accessdate=6 April 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=26 November 1974}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Popham |first1=Peter |title=The Lady and the Peacock: The Life of Aung San Suu Kyi |date=2011 |publisher=[[Rider Books]] |isbn=978-1-61519-064-5 |page=[https://archive.org/details/ladypeacocklifeo0000poph/page/224 224]|url=https://archive.org/details/ladypeacocklifeo0000poph |url-access=registration |accessdate=6 April 2018 |quote=Already unwell, he told the General Assembly that he felt \"a great sense of relief, bordering on liberation\" at relinquishing \"the burdens of office\"...}}</ref> In an editorial published around 27 December 1971, praising Thant, ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated that \"the wise counsel of this dedicated man of peace will still be needed after his retirement\". The editorial was titled \"The Liberation of U Thant\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The Liberation of U Thant |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/12/29/archives/the-liberation-of-u-thant.html |accessdate=6 April 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=29 December 1971}}</ref>\n\nAfter his retirement, Thant was appointed a senior fellow of the Adlai Stevenson Institute of International Affairs. He spent the last years of his life writing and advocating the development of a true global community and other general themes he had tried to promote while he was secretary-general.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}} While serving as secretary-general, Thant lived in [[Riverdale, Bronx]], on a {{convert|4.75|acre|ha|adj=on}} estate near 232nd Street, between Palisade and Douglas Avenues.<ref>Dunlap, David W. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE5D81731F935A25752C1A961948260 \"Bronx Residents Fighting Plans Of a Developer\"], ''The New York Times'', November 16, 1987. Accessed 2008-05-04. \"A battle has broken out in the Bronx over the future of the peaceful acreage where U Thant lived when he headed the United Nations. A group of neighbours from Riverdale and Spuyten Duyvil has demanded that the city acquire as a public park the {{convert|4.75|acre|m2|adj=on}} parcel known as the Douglas-U Thant estate, north of 232d Street, between Palisade and Douglas Avenues.\"</ref>\n\n== Death and legacy ==\n{{See also | U Thant funeral crisis}}\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = U Thant has put the world deeply in his debt.\n |source = \u2014John F. Kennedy, October 1962{{Sfn|Dorn & Pauk|2009|p=261}}\n |width  = 25%\n |align  = right}}\n[[File:Tomb of U Thant.jpg|thumb|left|[[Kandawmin Garden Mausolea|Thant's tomb]], Shwedagon Pagoda Road, Rangoon]]\nThant died of lung cancer in New York on 25 November 1974.<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/> By that time, Burma was ruled by a [[military junta]] which refused him any honours. The then Burmese president [[Ne Win]] was envious of Thant's international stature and the respect that was accorded him by the Burmese populace. Ne Win also resented Thant's close links with the democratic government of [[U Nu]] which Ne Win had overthrown in a coup d'\u00e9tat on 2 March 1962.\n\nHowever, Thant's grandson, [[Thant Myint-U]], wrote in the book ''The River of Lost Footsteps: Histories of Burma'' that intense animosity between Thant and Ne Win went back only to 1969, when Ne Win believed Thant was conniving with Nu after Nu denounced Ne Win at a press corp meeting at the UN headquarters. Ne Win told his men to consider Thant as an enemy of the state, despite Thant denouncing Nu's action as inappropriate.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Thant Myint-U |title=The River of Lost Footsteps: Histories of Burma |date=2006 |publisher=[[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]] |pages=311}}</ref>\n\nRegardless of the reasons, Ne Win ordered that Thant be buried without any official involvement or ceremony.\n\nFrom the United Nations headquarters in New York where he was laid in state, Thant's body was flown back to [[Yangon|Rangoon]], but no guard of honour or high-ranking officials were on hand at the airport when the coffin arrived except for U Aung Tun, deputy minister of education, who was subsequently dismissed from office.<ref>''Asian almanac, Volume 13.'' (1975). s.n. p. 6809.</ref> On the day of Thant's funeral on 5 December 1974, tens of thousands of people lined the streets of Rangoon to pay their last respects. Thant's coffin was displayed at Rangoon's Kyaikasan race course for a few hours before the scheduled burial. The coffin of Thant was then snatched by a group of students just before it was scheduled to leave for burial in an ordinary [[Kyandaw Cemetery|Rangoon cemetery]]. The student demonstrators buried Thant on the former grounds of the Rangoon University Students Union (RUSU), which Ne Win had dynamited and [[1962 Rangoon University Protests|destroyed on 8 July 1962.]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2002/dec/06/guardianobituaries |location=London |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Martin |last=Smith |title=General Ne Win |date=December 6, 2002}}</ref>\n\n[[U Thant Funeral Crisis|During the period of 5\u201311 December]], the student demonstrators also built a temporary mausoleum for Thant on the grounds of the RUSU and gave anti-government speeches. In the early morning hours of 12 December 1974, government troops stormed the campus, killed some of the students guarding the makeshift mausoleum, removed Thant's coffin, and reburied it in [[Kandawmin Garden Mausolea]] near the [[Shwedagon Pagoda]], where it has continued to lie.<ref name=at>Soe-win, Henry (June 17, 2008). [http://www.asiantribune.com/?q=node/11810 Peace Eludes U Thant]. ''[[Asian Tribune]]''.</ref> Upon hearing of the storming of the [[Rangoon University]] campus and the forcible removal of Thant's coffin, many people rioted in the streets of Rangoon. [[Martial law]] was declared in Rangoon and the surrounding metropolitan areas. What has come to be known as the U Thant crisis\u2014the student-led protests over the shabby treatment of Thant by the Ne Win government\u2014was crushed by the Burmese government.<ref name=at/>\n\nThant's memoirs, ''View from the UN'', were posthumously published, initially by [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] in 1978.\n\nIn April 2012, UN Secretary-General [[Ban Ki-moon]] paid his respects at U Thant's mausoleum during a visit to Yangon.\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:U Thant's family 1964.PNG|350px|thumb|Thant and his family, including brothers Khant Thaung and Tin Maung, his mother Nan Thaung, and his daughter Aye Aye Thant and her husband, Tyn Myint-U, in 1964]]\nThant had three brothers: Khant, Thaung, and Tin Maung.<ref>{{cite book |author=Bingham, June |title=U Thant: The Search For Peace |publisher=Victor Gollancz |year=1966 |page=43}}</ref> He was married to Daw Thein Tin. They had two sons, but lost both; Maung Bo died in infancy, and Tin Maung Thant fell from a bus during a visit to Yangon. Tin Maung Thant's funeral procession, which was attended by dignitaries, was grander than that of the state funeral of Commodore Than Pe, a member of the 17-man [[Union Revolutionary Council|Revolutionary Council]] and minister of health and education. Thant was survived by a daughter, an adopted son, five grandchildren, and five great-grandchildren (three girls and two boys). His only grandson, [[Thant Myint-U]], is a historian and a former senior official in the UN's Department of Political Affairs and the author of ''The River of Lost Footsteps'', in part a biography of Thant.\n\nDuring his tenure as Secretary-General, Thant followed [[unidentified flying object|UFO]] reports with some interest; in 1967, he arranged for American atmospheric physicist [[James E. McDonald]] to speak before the UN's Outer Space Affairs Group regarding UFOs.<ref>Letter to U Thant / James E. McDonald. \u2013 Tucson, Ariz. : J.E. McDonald, 1967. \u2013 2 s;Druffel, Ann; ''Firestorm: Dr. James E. McDonald's Fight for UFO Science''; 2003, Wild Flower Press; {{ISBN|0-926524-58-5}}</ref>\n\n== Awards, honors, and memorials ==\nThant was generally reluctant to receive prizes and honors due to his own humility as well as publicity associated with them. He declined Burma's second highest honor awarded to him by U Nu's government in 1961. When he was informed that the 1965 Nobel Prize would instead go to UNICEF due to Chairman Gunnar Jahn's veto, Thant, according to [[Walter Dorn]], \"recorded his pleasure\".{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=147}} However, he did accept the [[Jawaharlal Nehru Award for International Understanding]] in 1965,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iccrindia.net/jnawardlist.html |title=List of the recipients of the Jawaharlal Nehru Award |publisher=ICCR India |accessdate=9 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901175835/http://www.iccrindia.net/jnawardlist.html |archivedate=September 1, 2013 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> the [[Gandhi Peace Award]] in 1972, [[United Nations Prize in the Field of Human Rights]] in 1973 and more than two dozen honorary degrees.\n\nThant received honorary degrees (LL.D) from Carleton University, Williams College, Princeton University, Mount Holyoke College, Harvard University, Dartmouth College, University of California at Berkeley, University of Denver, Swarthmore College, New York University, Moscow University, Queen's University, Colby College, Yale University, University of Windsor, Hamilton College,  Fordham University, Manhattan College, University of Michigan, Delhi University, University of Leeds, Louvain University,  University of Alberta, Boston University, Rutgers University, University of Dublin (Trinity College), Laval University, Columbia University, the University of the Philippines Diliman, and Syracuse University. He also received the Doctor of Divinity from The First Universal Church; Doctor of International Law from Florida International University; Doctor of Laws from University of Hartford; Doctor of Civil Laws degree, honoris causa from Colgate University; Doctor of Humane Letters from Duke University.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/Overview/SG/sg3bio.html |title=U Thant (Myanmar): Third United Nations Secretary-General |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn his memory, [[Sri Chinmoy]], the leader of the UN Meditation Group founded by Thant, established the [[U Thant Peace Award]] which acknowledges and honors individuals or organizations for distinguished accomplishments toward the attainment of world peace. The meditation team also named a tiny island in the East River opposite the headquarters of the United Nations [[U Thant Island]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/06/nyregion/fyi-652520.html |work=The New York Times |first=Daniel B. |last=Schneider |title=F.Y.I. |date=October 6, 1996}}</ref> The road Jalan U-Thant (U-Thant Road) and the township [[Taman U-Thant]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]] are also named in his honor.<ref>[[List of roads in Kuala Lumpur]]</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, in an effort spearheaded by his daughter Aye Aye Thant and his grandson Thant Myint-U, Thant's house in Yangon was being converted into a museum which would feature his photos, works and personal belongings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irrawaddy.org/burma/multimedia-burma/u-thants-rangoon-home-exhibit-inspire.html |title=At U Thant's Rangoon Home, an Exhibit to Inspire |work=The Irrawaddy |date=December 23, 2013 |accessdate=9 June 2014 |author=Kyaw Phyo Tha}}</ref> In October 2013, the building of an U Thant library near his Pantanaw house was underway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irrawaddy.org/feature/u-thant-library-project-stalling-due-lack-funds.html |title=U Thant Library Project Stalling Due to Lack of Funds |work=The Irrawaddy |date=October 3, 2013 |accessdate=24 May 2014 |author=Simon Roughneen}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{portal-inline|Biography}}\n* {{portal-inline|Politics}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== Citations ==\n===Endnotes===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== References ===\n* {{cite book |title=U Thant: The Search for Peace |publisher=Knopf Publishing Group |author=June Bingham Birge |authorlink=June Bingham Birge |year=1966 |location=New York |ref={{Sfnref|Bingham|1966}}}}\n* {{cite journal | url=http://walterdorn.org/pub/144 |title=Unsung Mediator: U Thant and the Cuban Missile Crisis | author=[[Walter Dorn|A. Walter Dorn]] and Robert Pauk |journal=[[Diplomatic History (journal)|Diplomatic History]] |date=April 2009 |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=261\u2013291 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-7709.2008.00762.x |ref={{Sfnref|Dorn & Pauk|2009}}}}\n* {{cite book |title=Timing the De-escalation of International Conflicts |url=https://archive.org/details/timingdeescalati00stua |url-access=registration |publisher=[[Syracuse University Press]] |author=Louis Kriesberg, Stuart J. Thorson |year=1991 |location=Syracuse, NY |isbn=0815625219 |ref={{Sfnref|Louis & Stuart|1991}}}}\n* {{cite journal |title=The closest brush: How a UN secretary-general averted doomsday |author=A. Walter Dorn and Robert Pauk |journal=[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]] |date=November 2012  |volume=68 |issue=6 |pages=79\u201384 |doi=10.1177/0096340212464363 |ref={{Sfnref|Dorn & Pauk|2012}}| bibcode=2012BuAtS..68f..79D}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |title=U Thant |encyclopedia=Salem Press Biographical Encyclopedia:Research Starters |publisher=Salem Press |author=Lewis, Terrance L. |year=2012 |ref={{Sfnref|Lewis|2012}}}}\n* {{cite book |author=A. Walter Dorn |editor=Kille, Kent |chapter=U Thant: Buddhism in Action |title=The UN Secretary-General and Moral Authority: Ethics and Religion in International Leadership |publisher=[[Georgetown University Press]] |chapter-url=http://walterdorn.org/pdf/UThant-BuddhismInAction_Dorn_SG-MoralAuthority_2007.pdf |location=Washington, DC |year=2007 |isbn=978-1-58901-180-9 |ref={{Sfnref|Dorn|2007}}}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |author=Bernard J. Firestone|title=The United Nations under U Thant, 1961\u20131971 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |location=Metuchen, N.J |year=2001 |isbn=0-8108-3700-5}}\n* {{cite book |author=Ramses Nassif |title=U Thant in New York, 1961\u20131971: A Portrait of the Third UN Secretary-General |publisher=St. Martin's Press |location=New York |year=1988 |isbn=0-312-02117-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/uthantinnewyork100nass}}\n* Hanwong, L. (2014). \u02bb\u016a than nai th\u0101na l\u0113kh\u0101thik\u0101n \u02bbOngk\u0101n Sahaprach\u0101ch\u0101t ch\u0101o \u02bb\u0112ch\u012ba khon r\u01e3k [U Thant as the first Asian secretary-general of the United Nations]. In A. Khamson, T. Weerakietsoontorn & C. Khuntong (Eds.), ''Y\u014d\u031cn phinit ph\u016bs\u0101ng prawattis\u0101t \u02bb\u0112ch\u012ba Tawan\u02bb\u014d\u031ck Ch\u012bang Tai'' [Reflections on Makers of Southeast Asian History 2] (pp. 131\u201363). Bangkok: Reviews of Southeast Asian History and Culture Project (TRF). (in Thai)\n* {{cite book |author=U Thant |title=View from the UN |publisher=Doubleday |location=Garden City, NY |year=1978 |isbn=0-385-11541-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/viewfromun00utha_0}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|U Thant}}\n* [https://www.un.org/av/photo/subjects/sg3.htm UN Photos of U Thant] from the United Nations website\n* [https://www.un.org/sg/en/content/u-thant Official UNSG biography] from the United Nations website\n\n{{-}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]] ({{flagicon|Sweden}})}}\n{{s-ttl |title={{flagicon|UN}} [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]] |years=November 1961 \u2013 December 1971}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Kurt Waldheim]] ({{flagicon|Austria}})}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{United Nations}}\n{{LN and UN Secretaries-General}}\n{{Gandhi Peace Award laureates}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thant, U}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:Amateur radio people]]\n[[Category:Burmese diplomats]]\n[[Category:Burmese people of World War II]]\n[[Category:Burmese Theravada Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Cold War diplomats]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from lung cancer]]\n[[Category:People from Ayeyarwady Region]]\n[[Category:People of the Congo Crisis]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of Myanmar to the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Union of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Burmese officials of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Secretaries-General of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:University of Yangon alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Third Secretary-General of the United Nations}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}}\n{{Burmese name|U|\"U Thant\" in Burmese is the same as saying \"Mr. Thant\" in English=}}    ''Side-note:'' \"U Thant''\" in Burmese is the same as'' \"Mr. Thant\" ''in English.'' {{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix    = [[His Excellency]] [[Burmese names#Honorifics|U]]\n| name                = Thant\n|native_name   = {{nobold|{{my|\u101e\u1014\u1037\u103a}}}}\n| nationality = [[Bamar|Burmese]]\n| image = U Thant (1963).jpg\n| caption = U Thant in 1963\n| alt = Official portrait of U Thant with a UN flag in the background. \n| order = 3rd [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]]\n| term_start = 30 November 1961\n| term_end = 31 December 1971\n| predecessor = [[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]]\n| successor = [[Kurt Waldheim]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1909|1|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Pantanaw]], [[British rule in Burma|Burma]], [[British Raj|British India]]\n| death_date = {{nowrap|{{death date and age|1974|11|25|1909|1|22|df=yes}}}}\n| death_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n| death_cause = Lung cancer\n| resting_place = [[Kandawmin Garden Mausolea]], [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]]\n| parents = {{unbulleted list |Po Hnit |Nan Thaung}}\n| spouse = Daw Thein Tin (died 1989)\n| children = {{unbulleted list |Maung Bo |Tin Maung Thant |Aye Aye Thant}}\n| relations = {{unbulleted list|Khant {{small|(brother)}} |Thaung {{small|(brother)}} |Tin Maung {{small|(brother)}} |[[Thant Myint-U]] {{small|(grandson)}}}}\n| signature = U Thant Signature.svg\n}}\n{{Burmese characters}}\n\n'''Thant''' ({{IPAc-en|\u03b8|\u0251\u02d0|n|t}}; {{MYname|MY=\u101e\u1014\u1037\u103a|MLCTS=san.}}; {{IPA-my|\u03b8a\u0330\u0270\u0303|IPA}}; 22 January 1909 \u2013 25 November 1974), known honorifically as '''U Thant''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|u\u02d0|_|\u02c8|\u03b8|\u0251\u02d0|n|t}}),{{efn|\"[[Burmese names#Honorifics|U]]\" is an [[honorific]] in [[Burmese language|Burmese]], roughly equal to \"Mr\". \"Thant\" was his only name, per Burmese convention. In Burmese, he was known as '''Pantanaw U Thant''', in reference to his hometown, Pantanaw.}} was a [[Burma|Burmese]] diplomat and the [[Secretary-General of the United Nations#Secretaries-General|third Secretary-General]] of the [[United Nations]] from 1961 to 1971, the first non-[[Scandinavia]]n to hold the position. He held the office for a record 10 years and one month (3,683 days) (taking into account a one-month vacancy in November\u2013December 1966).<ref>[https://www.un.org/sg/en/content/u-thant UN website's biography of Thant]</ref>\n\nA native of [[Pantanaw]], Thant was educated at the National High School and at [[Rangoon University]]. In the days of tense political climate in Burma, he held moderate views positioning himself between fervent nationalists and British loyalists. He was a close friend of Burma's first Prime Minister [[U Nu]] and served in various positions in Nu's cabinet from 1948 to 1961. Thant had a calm and unassuming demeanor that won his colleagues' respect.{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=147}}\n\nHe was appointed as Secretary-General in 1961, when his predecessor [[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]] [[1961 Ndola United Nations DC-6 crash|died in an air crash]]. In his first term, Thant facilitated negotiations between U.S. President [[John F. Kennedy]] and Soviet premier [[Nikita Khrushchev]] during the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] of 1962, helping to avert a global catastrophe. Later, in December that year, Thant ordered [[Operation Grandslam]], which ended a secessionist insurgency in [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Congo]]. He was reappointed as Secretary-General on 2 December 1966 by a unanimous vote of the Security Council. During his second term Thant was well known for publicly criticizing American conduct in the [[Vietnam War]]. He oversaw the entry of several newly independent African and Asian states into the UN. He refused to serve a third term, and retired in 1971.\n\nThant died of [[lung cancer]] in 1974. A devout [[Buddhist]] and the foremost Burmese diplomat on the international stage, he was widely admired and held in great respect by the Burmese populace. When the military government refused him any honours, riots broke out in Rangoon; these were violently crushed by the government, leaving scores of casualties.\n\n== Early life ==\n[[File:U Thant in 1927.PNG|thumb|left|Thant as a [[Rangoon University]] student in 1927]]\n\nThant, the eldest of four sons, was born in [[Pantanaw]], colonial Burma, to a moderately wealthy family of landowners and rice merchants. His father Po Hnit, who had been educated in [[Calcutta]], was the only person in the town who could communicate well in English.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=29}} He was a founding member of the [[Burma Research Society]] and had helped establish ''[[The Sun (Rangoon)|The Sun]]'' (''Thuriya'') newspaper in Rangoon. {{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=29}}<ref name=\"mm\">{{cite book |title=Dr. Maung Maung: Gentleman, Scholar, Patriot |editor=Robert H. Taylor |publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies |year=2008 |pages=211\u2013212 |isbn=978-981-230-409-4}}</ref> Although his family members were ethnic [[Bamar people|Bamars]] and devout [[Buddhist]]s, Thant's father, according to Thant Myint-U (U Thant's grandson), had distant ancestors who were \"people from both India and China, Buddhists and Muslims, as well as Shans and Mons\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Where China Meets India: Burma and the New Crossroad of Asia |publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux |author=Thant Myint-U |year=2011 |location=New York |pages=76 |isbn=978-0-374-98408-3 |author-link=Thant Myint-U}}</ref> He hoped that all his four sons would each earn a degree.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=32}} His other sons, Khant, Thaung, and Tin Maung went on to become politicians and scholars.<ref name=\"mm\"/>\n\nPo Hnit had collected a personal library of various American and British books and cultivated a reading habit among his children. As a result Thant became an avid reader and his school friends nicknamed him \"The Philosopher\".{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=144}} Apart from reading, he enjoyed various sports including hiking, swimming and playing [[chinlone]].{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=33}} He went to the National High School in Pantanaw. At the age of eleven Thant participated in strikes against the University Act of 1920. He dreamed of becoming a journalist and surprised the family by writing an article for the ''[[Union of Burma Boy Scouts]]'' magazine. When Thant was fourteen, his father died and a series of inheritance disputes forced Thant's mother, Nan Thaung, and her four children into difficult financial times.<ref>Franda, Marcus F. (2006). ''The United Nations in the 21st century: management and reform processes in a troubled organization''. Rowman & Littlefield. p. 53. {{ISBN|978-0-7425-5334-7}}.</ref>\n\nAfter the death of his father, Thant believed he would not be able to complete a four-year degree and instead worked for a two-year teaching certificate at Rangoon University in 1926. As the eldest son he had to fulfill his filial duties and responsibilities to the family. At university, Thant, together with Nu, the future Prime Minister of Burma, studied history under [[D. G. E. Hall]]. Nu was told by a distant mutual relative to take care of Thant and the two soon became close friends.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=88}} Thant was elected joint secretary of the University Philosophical Association and secretary of the Literary and Debating Society.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=89}} In Rangoon, Thant met [[John Sydenham Furnivall|J.S. Furnivall]], the founder of The Burma Book Club and ''[[The World of Books]]'' magazine, to which Thant regularly contributed. Promising a good post, Furnivall urged Thant to complete four-year university course and join Civil Service but Thant refused.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=93}} After earning the certificate, he returned to Pantanaw to teach at the National High School as a senior teacher in 1928. He contacted Furnivall and Nu regularly, writing articles and participating in ''The World of Books'' translation competitions.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=94}}\n\nIn 1931, Thant won first place in All Burma Teachership Examination and became the school's headmaster by the age of twenty-five.{{Sfn|Bingham|1966|p=97}}{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}} Urged by Thant, his friend Nu took the local superintendent of schools position. Thant regularly contributed to several newspapers and magazines under the pen name \"Thilawa\" and translated a number of books, including one on the [[League of Nations]].<ref>Naing, Saw Yan (January 22, 2009). [http://www.irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=14975 Remembering U Thant and His Achievements]. ''[[The Irrawaddy]]''.</ref> His major influences were Sir [[Stafford Cripps]], [[Sun Yat-sen]] and [[Mahatma Gandhi]].{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=144}} In the days of tense political climate in Burma, Thant stood moderate grounds between fervent nationalists and British loyalists.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}}\n\n== Civil servant ==\n[[File:U Nu with U Thant.jpg|thumb|Thant with U Nu in 1955 on an early morning walk]]\nDuring the World War II, the Japanese occupied Burma from 1942 to 1945. They brought Thant to Rangoon to lead the Educational Reorganizing Committee. However, Thant did not have any real power, and returned to Pantanaw. When the Japanese ordered making Japanese compulsory in Pantanaw high schools, Thant defied the orders and cooperated with the growing anti-Japanese resistance.{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=145}}\n\nIn 1948, Burma gained independence from the United Kingdom. Nu became the prime minister of the newly independent Burma and appointed Thant as director of broadcasting in 1948. By then, civil war had broken out. The Karen insurgency began and Thant risked his life to go to Karen camps to negotiate for peace. The negotiations broke down, and in 1949 the advancing insurgents burned his hometown, including his house. The insurgents pushed the front to within four miles of the capital Rangoon before they were beaten back. In the following year, Thant was appointed secretary to the government of Burma in the [[Ministry of Information (Burma)|Ministry of Information]]. From 1951 to 1957, Thant was secretary to the prime minister, writing speeches for U Nu, arranging his foreign travel, and meeting foreign visitors. During this entire period, he was U Nu's closest confidant and advisor.{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=145}}\n\nHe also took part in a number of international conferences and was the secretary of the 1955 [[Bandung Conference]] in [[Indonesia]], which gave birth to the [[Non-Aligned Movement]]. From 1957 to 1961, he was Burma's permanent representative to the United Nations and became actively involved in negotiations over [[Nationalism and resistance in Algeria|Algerian independence]]. In 1961, Thant was named Chairman of the UN Congo Commission. The Burmese government awarded him the title ''Maha Thray Sithu'' as a commander in the [[Pyidaungsu Sithu Thingaha|order of Pyidaungsu Sithu]].<ref>H.W. Wilson Company (1962). ''Current biography, Volume 23.'' H. W. Wilson Co.</ref>\n\n== United Nations Secretary-General ==\n[[File:U Thant swearing in.jpg|thumb|Thant swearing in to the United Nations Secretariet|left]]\n\nIn September 1961, United Nations Secretary-General [[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]] was killed [[1961 Ndola United Nations DC-6 crash|in a plane crash]] ''en route'' to Congo. The Security Council hurriedly searched for a new Secretary-General, but over the next few weeks it was in a deadlock, with the United States and the Soviet Union unable to agree on any candidate proposed by other members. The superpowers backed down when representatives from smaller nations and the Non-Aligned Movement proposed Thant to fill Hammarskj\u00f6ld's unexpired term.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}} On 3 November 1961, Thant was unanimously appointed as acting Secretary-General by the [[United Nations General Assembly|General Assembly]], on the recommendation of the [[UN Security Council|Security Council]] in [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 168|Resolution 168]]. On 30 November 1961, the General Assembly unanimously appointed him secretary-general for a term of office ending on 3 November 1966. During his first term, he was widely credited for his role in defusing the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] and for ending the [[Congo Crisis|civil war in the Congo]]. He also said that he wanted to ease tensions between major powers while serving at the UN.<ref>[http://www.upi.com/Audio/Year_in_Review/Events-of-1962/1962-Elections,-Other-Events/12295509437657-7/#title \"1962 In Review]. [[United Press International]].</ref>\n\n=== First term: Cuban Missile Crisis and War in Congo ===\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = At a critical moment\u2014when the nuclear powers seemed set on a collision course\u2014the Secretary-General's intervention led to the diversion of the Soviet ships headed for Cuba and interception by our Navy. This was the indispensable first step in the peaceful resolution of the Cuban crisis.\n |source = \u2014[[Adlai Stevenson II|Adlai Stevenson]], Senate Foreign Relations Committee 88th Congress, March 13, 1963{{Sfn|Dorn & Pauk|2009|p=265}}\n |width  = 25%\n |align  = right}}\n[[File:U Thant and John F. Kennedy.PNG|thumb|Thant shakes hands with [[John F. Kennedy]] during his visit to the UN Headquarters.]]\n\nIn less than one year in office, Thant faced a critical challenge to defuse the Cuban Missile Crisis, the moment when the world came closest to a nuclear war. On 20 October 1962, two days before public announcements were made, U.S President [[John F. Kennedy]] showed Thant [[Lockheed U-2|U-2]] aerial reconnaissance photographs of Soviet missile installations in Cuba. The President then ordered a naval \"quarantine\" to remove all offensive weapons from Soviet ships bound for Cuba. Meanwhile, Soviet ships were approaching the quarantine zone. To avoid a naval confrontation, Thant proposed that the U.S should make non-invasion guarantees in exchange for missile withdrawal from the Soviet Union. Soviet Premier Khrushchev welcomed the proposal, which formed the basis of further negotiations.{{Sfn|Dorn & Pauk|2012|p=80}} Khrushchev further agreed to suspend missile shipments while the negotiations were ongoing.<ref name=\"nyt62\">{{cite news |title=Kennedy Agrees to Talks on Thant Plan, Khrushchev Accepts It; Blockade Goes On; Russian Tanker Intercepted and Cleared |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/97/10/19/home/crisis-26.html |accessdate=7 April 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=26 October 1962}}</ref> However, on 27 October 1962, a U-2 plane was shot down over Cuba, deepening the crisis. Kennedy was under intense pressure to invade from the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the [[EXCOMM|Executive Committee]] (ExComm). Kennedy hoped Thant would play the role of mediator and subsequently replied to ExComm and the Joint Chiefs, \"On the other hand we have U Thant, and we don't want to sink a ship...right in the middle of when U Thant is supposedly arranging for the Russians to stay out.\"{{Sfn|Dorn & Pauk|2009|p=273}}\n\nNegotiations continued. The U.S agreed to dismantle missiles in Turkey and guaranteed never to invade Cuba in exchange for removal of Soviet missiles in Cuba. Thant flew to Cuba and discussed with [[Fidel Castro]] allowing UN missile inspectors and the return of the body of the downed U-2 pilot. Castro, furious that the Soviets had agreed to remove missiles without his knowledge, categorically rejected any UN inspectors, although he did return the pilot's body. The inspection was done at sea by US reconnaissance aircraft and warships. The crisis was resolved and a war between superpowers was averted.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}}{{Sfn|Dorn & Pauk|2009|p=292}}\n\nAlthough a manifest pacifist and a devout Buddhist, Thant did not hesitate to use force when required. During the Congo Civil War in 1962, Katangan secessionists led by [[Moise Tshombe]] repeatedly attacked UN Operation in the Congo forces (ONUC). In December 1962, after ONUC suffered a sustained four-day attack in Katanga, Thant ordered the \"[[Operation Grandslam]]\" to gain \"complete freedom of movement for ONUC all over Katanga.\" The operation proved to be decisive and ended the secessionist insurgency once and for all. By January 1963, the secessionist capital Elizabethville was under full UN control.{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=161}} In his speech at the [[Columbia University]] Thant expressed expectation of completion of the [[United Nations Operation in the Congo]] in mid 1964.<ref name=\"Institut\">Tomanovi\u0107, M. (1965). ''Hronika me\u0111unarodnih doga\u0111aja 1964''. [[Belgrade]]. [http://www.diplomacy.bg.ac.rs/index_en.php Institute of International Politics and Economics], p.223. (in [[Serbo-Croatian]])</ref>\n\nFor his role in defusing the Cuban crisis and other peacekeeping efforts, the Norwegian Permanent Representative of the United Nations informed Thant that he would be awarded the 1965 Nobel Peace prize. He humbly replied, \"Is not the Secretary-General merely doing his job when he works for peace?\"{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=147}} On the other hand, Chairman [[Gunnar Jahn]] of the Nobel Peace prize committee lobbied heavily against giving Thant the prize which was at the last minute awarded to [[UNICEF]]. The rest of the committee all wanted the prize to go to Thant. The disagreement lasted three years and in 1966 and 1967 no prize was given, with Gunnar Jahn effectively vetoing an award to Thant.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lundestad |first1=Geir |title=The Nobel Peace Prize, 1901-2000 |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/themes/peace/lundestad-review/ |website=nobelprize.org |accessdate=7 April 2018 |quote=In 1965 and 1966 a majority of the committee clearly favored giving the prize to the third Secretary General, U Thant, and even to the first, Norway's Trygve Lie, but chairman Jahn more or less vetoed this.}}</ref> Outraged, Thant's undersecretary and Nobel Prize laureate [[Ralph Bunche]] called Gunnar Jahn's decision \"gross injustice to U Thant.\"{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=147}}\n\nOn Christmas Eve 1963, intercommunal clashes broke out in Cyprus. Turkish Cypriots withdrew into their enclaves, leaving the central government wholly under Greek Cypriot control. A \"peace-making force\" established under British command was unable to put an end to the fighting, and a conference on Cyprus held in London in January 1964 ended in disagreement. On 4 March 1964, amid the danger of broader hostilities, the Security Council unanimously authorized Thant to establish a UN Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP), with a limited three-month mandate to prevent the recurrence of fighting and to restore order. The Council further asked the secretary-general to appoint a mediator to seek a peaceful settlement of the Cyprus problem. Thant appointed Galo Plaza Lasso as mediator but when his report was rejected by Turkey in March 1965, Plaza resigned and the function of mediator lapsed.<ref name=nc/>\n\nIn April 1964, Thant accepted the [[Holy See]]'s designation of itself as a [[permanent observer]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCann |first1=Eamonn |title=How did the Holy See get recognition as a state? It just did |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/how-did-the-holy-see-get-recognition-as-a-state-it-just-did-1.1664452 |accessdate=7 April 2018 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=23 January 2014 |quote=In March 1964 pope Paul VI wrote to UN secretary general U Thant saying he was minded to appoint a permanent observer. In April, U Thant wrote back saying, in effect, fair enough, come ahead.}}</ref> There appeared to be no involvement of the General Assembly or the UN Security Council in the decision.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kissling |first1=F. |last2=Shannon |first2=D. |title=Church and state at the United Nations. A case of the emperor's new clothes. |journal=Conscience (Washington, D.C.) |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=11\u20132 |pmid=12178922 |year=1996}}</ref>\n\n=== Second term: Arab\u2013Israeli conflict and Vietnam War===\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = After the Six-Day War, [Thant] allowed himself to become a convenient scapegoat for international inaction, accepting this unenviable role with as much Buddhist detachment as could be summoned.\n |source = \u2014[[Walter Dorn]], 2007{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=177}}\n |width  = 25%\n |align  = right}}\nThant was re-appointed secretary-general of the United Nations by the General Assembly on 2 December 1966, on the unanimous recommendation of the Security Council. His term of office continued until 31 December 1971, when he retired. During his time in office he oversaw the entry into the UN of dozens of new Asian and African states, and was a firm opponent of [[apartheid]] in South Africa. He also established many of the UN's development and environmental agencies, funds and programmes, including the [[UN Development Programme]] (UNDP), the [[UN University]], the [[United Nations Conference on Trade and Development]], [[United Nations Institute for Training and Research]] (UNITAR), and the [[UN Environmental Programme]]. The [[Six-Day War]] between [[Arab]] countries and [[Israel]], the [[Prague Spring]] and subsequent Soviet invasion of [[Czechoslovakia]], and the [[Bangladesh Liberation War|Indo\u2013Pakistani War]] of 1971 leading to the birth of [[Bangladesh]] all took place during his tenure as secretary-general.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}}\n\n[[File:U-Thant 2.jpg|thumb|right|Thant meets with U.S President Lyndon B. Johnson in the Cabinet Room of the White House on 21 February 1968.]]\n\nHe was criticized in the US and Israel for agreeing to pull UNEF troops out of the [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]] in 1967 in response to a request from [[Egypt]]ian president [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|Nasser]].<ref>Rikhye, Indar Jit (1980). ''The Sinai Blunder: Withdrawal of the United Nations Emergency Force leading to the Six-Day War of June 1967''. Routledge. {{ISBN|978-0-7146-3136-3}}.</ref> The Permanent Representative of Egypt had informed Thant that the Egyptian government had decided to terminate UNEF's presence in the Sinai and the Gaza Strip, and requested steps that would withdraw the force as soon as possible, which Thant was obligated to accept. The UN afterwards stated, \"Because Israel refused to accept UNEF on its territory, the Force had to be deployed only on the Egyptian side of the border, and thus its functioning was entirely contingent upon the consent of Egypt as the host country. Once that consent was withdrawn, its operation could no longer be maintained.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/peacekeeping/missions/past/unef1backgr2.html |title=Middle East UNEF: Background |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=23 May 2014}}</ref> Thant, by flying to [[Cairo]] in a last-minute peace effort, tried to persuade Nasser not to go to war with Israel.\n\nIn Israel, his abrupt unilateral withdrawal of UNEF without any diplomatic process or wider consultation was regarded as a violation of United Nations assurances and commitments given to Israel in 1957, on the basis of which Israel had withdrawn from Sinai and Gaza at that time,<ref>''Abba Eban: An Autobiography'' by Abba Eban (Random House, 1977), pp. 321\u2013322</ref> and it \"thereafter inspired Israel's refusal to place her vital interests again in United Nations hands\".<ref>''Abba Eban: An Autobiography'' by Abba Eban (Random House, 1977), p. 323</ref>\n\nThe Cyprus crisis resurfaced in November 1967, but Turkey's threatened military intervention was averted, largely as a result of US opposition. Negotiations conducted by Cyrus Vance for the US and Jos\u00e9 Rolz-Bennett on behalf of the secretary-general led to a settlement. Intercommunal talks began in June 1968, through the good offices of the secretary-general, as part of the settlement. The talks bogged down, but Thant proposed a formula for their reactivation under the auspices of his special representative, B.F. Osorio-Tafall, and they were resumed in 1972, after Thant had left office.<ref name=nc>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationsencyclopedia.com/United-Nations/The-Secretary-General-DEVELOPMENTS-UNDER-U-THANT-1961-1971.html#b |title=The Secretary-General \u2013 Developments under U Thant, 1961\u20131971 |publisher=National Encyclopedia |accessdate=24 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nThant's once good relationship with the US government deteriorated rapidly when he publicly criticized American conduct of the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>Dennen, Leon (August 12, 1968). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ttEdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=b0YEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4623,4372187&dq= U Thant Speaks No Evil on Czech Crisis]. ''Daily News''.</ref> His secret attempts at direct peace talks between [[federal government of the United States|Washington]] and [[Hanoi]] were eventually rejected by the [[Lyndon B. Johnson|Johnson]] Administration.\n\nIn 1971, the participation of the [[People's Republic of China]] in the United Nations, which was a long-standing problem, was realized. Thant sent a message to the Chinese government asking China to send a delegation.<ref>{{cite news |work=The New York Times |date=1971-10-28 |title=Thant Asks China to Name Delegate to Council Soon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/10/28/archives/thant-asks-china-to-name-delegate-to-council-soon-thant-urges-china.htmlfirst=Tad |last=Szulc |accessdate=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Retirement ===\nOn 23 January 1971, Thant categorically announced that he would \"under no circumstances\" be available for a third term as secretary-general. The UN Security Council was deadlocked for many weeks in the search for a successor before finally settling \u2013 on 21 December 1971 \u2013 on [[Kurt Waldheim]]. The date was Waldheim's 53rd birthday, and just ten days before Thant's second term was to end.\n\nUnlike his two predecessors, Thant retired after ten years on speaking terms with all the big powers. In 1961, when he was first appointed, the [[Soviet Union]] tried to insist on a ''troika'' formula of three secretaries-general, one representing each [[Cold War]] bloc, to maintain equality in the United Nations between the superpowers. By 1966, when Thant was reappointed, all the big powers, in a unanimous vote of the Security Council, affirmed the importance of the secretary-generalship and his good offices, a clear tribute to Thant's work.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}}\n\nIn his farewell address to the United Nations General Assembly, Secretary-General Thant stated that he felt a \"great sense of relief bordering on liberation\" on relinquishing the \"burdens of office\".<ref name=\"NYTObit\">{{cite news |last1=Whitman |first1=Alden |title=U Thant Is Dead of Cancer at 65 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/11/26/archives/u-thant-is-dead-of-cancer-at-65-ut-thant-is-dead-of-cancer-united.html |accessdate=6 April 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=26 November 1974}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Popham |first1=Peter |title=The Lady and the Peacock: The Life of Aung San Suu Kyi |date=2011 |publisher=[[Rider Books]] |isbn=978-1-61519-064-5 |page=[https://archive.org/details/ladypeacocklifeo0000poph/page/224 224]|url=https://archive.org/details/ladypeacocklifeo0000poph |url-access=registration |accessdate=6 April 2018 |quote=Already unwell, he told the General Assembly that he felt \"a great sense of relief, bordering on liberation\" at relinquishing \"the burdens of office\"...}}</ref> In an editorial published around 27 December 1971, praising Thant, ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated that \"the wise counsel of this dedicated man of peace will still be needed after his retirement\". The editorial was titled \"The Liberation of U Thant\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The Liberation of U Thant |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/12/29/archives/the-liberation-of-u-thant.html |accessdate=6 April 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=29 December 1971}}</ref>\n\nAfter his retirement, Thant was appointed a senior fellow of the Adlai Stevenson Institute of International Affairs. He spent the last years of his life writing and advocating the development of a true global community and other general themes he had tried to promote while he was secretary-general.{{Sfn|Lewis|2012}} While serving as secretary-general, Thant lived in [[Riverdale, Bronx]], on a {{convert|4.75|acre|ha|adj=on}} estate near 232nd Street, between Palisade and Douglas Avenues.<ref>Dunlap, David W. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE5D81731F935A25752C1A961948260 \"Bronx Residents Fighting Plans Of a Developer\"], ''The New York Times'', November 16, 1987. Accessed 2008-05-04. \"A battle has broken out in the Bronx over the future of the peaceful acreage where U Thant lived when he headed the United Nations. A group of neighbours from Riverdale and Spuyten Duyvil has demanded that the city acquire as a public park the {{convert|4.75|acre|m2|adj=on}} parcel known as the Douglas-U Thant estate, north of 232d Street, between Palisade and Douglas Avenues.\"</ref>\n\n== Death and legacy ==\n{{See also | U Thant funeral crisis}}\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = U Thant has put the world deeply in his debt.\n |source = \u2014John F. Kennedy, October 1962{{Sfn|Dorn & Pauk|2009|p=261}}\n |width  = 25%\n |align  = right}}\n[[File:Tomb of U Thant.jpg|thumb|left|[[Kandawmin Garden Mausolea|Thant's tomb]], Shwedagon Pagoda Road, Rangoon]]\nThant died of lung cancer in New York on 25 November 1974.<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/> By that time, Burma was ruled by a [[military junta]] which refused him any honours. The then Burmese president [[Ne Win]] was envious of Thant's international stature and the respect that was accorded him by the Burmese populace. Ne Win also resented Thant's close links with the democratic government of [[U Nu]] which Ne Win had overthrown in a coup d'\u00e9tat on 2 March 1962.\n\nHowever, Thant's grandson, [[Thant Myint-U]], wrote in the book ''The River of Lost Footsteps: Histories of Burma'' that intense animosity between Thant and Ne Win went back only to 1969, when Ne Win believed Thant was conniving with Nu after Nu denounced Ne Win at a press corp meeting at the UN headquarters. Ne Win told his men to consider Thant as an enemy of the state, despite Thant denouncing Nu's action as inappropriate.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Thant Myint-U |title=The River of Lost Footsteps: Histories of Burma |date=2006 |publisher=[[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]] |pages=311}}</ref>\n\nRegardless of the reasons, Ne Win ordered that Thant be buried without any official involvement or ceremony.\n\nFrom the United Nations headquarters in New York where he was laid in state, Thant's body was flown back to [[Yangon|Rangoon]], but no guard of honour or high-ranking officials were on hand at the airport when the coffin arrived except for U Aung Tun, deputy minister of education, who was subsequently dismissed from office.<ref>''Asian almanac, Volume 13.'' (1975). s.n. p. 6809.</ref> On the day of Thant's funeral on 5 December 1974, tens of thousands of people lined the streets of Rangoon to pay their last respects. Thant's coffin was displayed at Rangoon's Kyaikasan race course for a few hours before the scheduled burial. The coffin of Thant was then snatched by a group of students just before it was scheduled to leave for burial in an ordinary [[Kyandaw Cemetery|Rangoon cemetery]]. The student demonstrators buried Thant on the former grounds of the Rangoon University Students Union (RUSU), which Ne Win had dynamited and [[1962 Rangoon University Protests|destroyed on 8 July 1962.]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2002/dec/06/guardianobituaries |location=London |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Martin |last=Smith |title=General Ne Win |date=December 6, 2002}}</ref>\n\n[[U Thant Funeral Crisis|During the period of 5\u201311 December]], the student demonstrators also built a temporary mausoleum for Thant on the grounds of the RUSU and gave anti-government speeches. In the early morning hours of 12 December 1974, government troops stormed the campus, killed some of the students guarding the makeshift mausoleum, removed Thant's coffin, and reburied it in [[Kandawmin Garden Mausolea]] near the [[Shwedagon Pagoda]], where it has continued to lie.<ref name=at>Soe-win, Henry (June 17, 2008). [http://www.asiantribune.com/?q=node/11810 Peace Eludes U Thant]. ''[[Asian Tribune]]''.</ref> Upon hearing of the storming of the [[Rangoon University]] campus and the forcible removal of Thant's coffin, many people rioted in the streets of Rangoon. [[Martial law]] was declared in Rangoon and the surrounding metropolitan areas. What has come to be known as the U Thant crisis\u2014the student-led protests over the shabby treatment of Thant by the Ne Win government\u2014was crushed by the Burmese government.<ref name=at/>\n\nThant's memoirs, ''View from the UN'', were posthumously published, initially by [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] in 1978.\n\nIn April 2012, UN Secretary-General [[Ban Ki-moon]] paid his respects at U Thant's mausoleum during a visit to Yangon.\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:U Thant's family 1964.PNG|350px|thumb|Thant and his family, including brothers Khant Thaung and Tin Maung, his mother Nan Thaung, and his daughter Aye Aye Thant and her husband, Tyn Myint-U, in 1964]]\nThant had three brothers: Khant, Thaung, and Tin Maung.<ref>{{cite book |author=Bingham, June |title=U Thant: The Search For Peace |publisher=Victor Gollancz |year=1966 |page=43}}</ref> He was married to Daw Thein Tin. They had two sons, but lost both; Maung Bo died in infancy, and Tin Maung Thant fell from a bus during a visit to Yangon. Tin Maung Thant's funeral procession, which was attended by dignitaries, was grander than that of the state funeral of Commodore Than Pe, a member of the 17-man [[Union Revolutionary Council|Revolutionary Council]] and minister of health and education. Thant was survived by a daughter, an adopted son, five grandchildren, and five great-grandchildren (three girls and two boys). His only grandson, [[Thant Myint-U]], is a historian and a former senior official in the UN's Department of Political Affairs and the author of ''The River of Lost Footsteps'', in part a biography of Thant.\n\nDuring his tenure as Secretary-General, Thant followed [[unidentified flying object|UFO]] reports with some interest; in 1967, he arranged for American atmospheric physicist [[James E. McDonald]] to speak before the UN's Outer Space Affairs Group regarding UFOs.<ref>Letter to U Thant / James E. McDonald. \u2013 Tucson, Ariz. : J.E. McDonald, 1967. \u2013 2 s;Druffel, Ann; ''Firestorm: Dr. James E. McDonald's Fight for UFO Science''; 2003, Wild Flower Press; {{ISBN|0-926524-58-5}}</ref>\n\n== Awards, honors, and memorials ==\nThant was generally reluctant to receive prizes and honors due to his own humility as well as publicity associated with them. He declined Burma's second highest honor awarded to him by U Nu's government in 1961. When he was informed that the 1965 Nobel Prize would instead go to UNICEF due to Chairman Gunnar Jahn's veto, Thant, according to Walter Dorn, \"recorded his pleasure\".{{Sfn|Dorn|2007|p=147}} However, he did accept the [[Jawaharlal Nehru Award for International Understanding]] in 1965,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iccrindia.net/jnawardlist.html |title=List of the recipients of the Jawaharlal Nehru Award |publisher=ICCR India |accessdate=9 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901175835/http://www.iccrindia.net/jnawardlist.html |archivedate=September 1, 2013 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> the [[Gandhi Peace Award]] in 1972, [[United Nations Prize in the Field of Human Rights]] in 1973 and more than two dozen honorary degrees.\n\nThant received honorary degrees (LL.D) from Carleton University, Williams College, Princeton University, Mount Holyoke College, Harvard University, Dartmouth College, University of California at Berkeley, University of Denver, Swarthmore College, New York University, Moscow University, Queen's University, Colby College, Yale University, University of Windsor, Hamilton College,  Fordham University, Manhattan College, University of Michigan, Delhi University, University of Leeds, Louvain University,  University of Alberta, Boston University, Rutgers University, University of Dublin (Trinity College), Laval University, Columbia University, the University of the Philippines Diliman, and Syracuse University. He also received the Doctor of Divinity from The First Universal Church; Doctor of International Law from Florida International University; Doctor of Laws from University of Hartford; Doctor of Civil Laws degree, honoris causa from Colgate University; Doctor of Humane Letters from Duke University.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/Overview/SG/sg3bio.html |title=U Thant (Myanmar): Third United Nations Secretary-General |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn his memory, [[Sri Chinmoy]], the leader of the UN Meditation Group founded by Thant, established the [[U Thant Peace Award]] which acknowledges and honors individuals or organizations for distinguished accomplishments toward the attainment of world peace. The meditation team also named a tiny island in the East River opposite the headquarters of the United Nations [[U Thant Island]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/06/nyregion/fyi-652520.html |work=The New York Times |first=Daniel B. |last=Schneider |title=F.Y.I. |date=October 6, 1996}}</ref> The road Jalan U-Thant (U-Thant Road) and the township [[Taman U-Thant]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]] are also named in his honor.<ref>[[List of roads in Kuala Lumpur]]</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, in an effort spearheaded by his daughter Aye Aye Thant and his grandson Thant Myint-U, Thant's house in Yangon was being converted into a museum which would feature his photos, works and personal belongings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irrawaddy.org/burma/multimedia-burma/u-thants-rangoon-home-exhibit-inspire.html |title=At U Thant's Rangoon Home, an Exhibit to Inspire |work=The Irrawaddy |date=December 23, 2013 |accessdate=9 June 2014 |author=Kyaw Phyo Tha}}</ref> In October 2013, the building of an U Thant library near his Pantanaw house was underway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irrawaddy.org/feature/u-thant-library-project-stalling-due-lack-funds.html |title=U Thant Library Project Stalling Due to Lack of Funds |work=The Irrawaddy |date=October 3, 2013 |accessdate=24 May 2014 |author=Simon Roughneen}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{portal-inline|Biography}}\n* {{portal-inline|Politics}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== Citations 